{"title_page": "Marupuram", "text_new": "{{About||the 2016 film|Marupuram (2016 film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2019}}\n{{Notability|film|date=October 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Marupuram\n| image          =\n| director       = [[Viji Thampi]]\n| producer       = [[Joy Thomas]]\n| writer         = [[Renjith]]<br>[[Kaloor Dennis]]\n| starring       = [[Jayaram]]<br>[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br>[[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]]<br>[[Sukumaran]]<br>[[Jagathy Sreekumar]]\n| music          = [[Mohan Sithara]]\n| cinematography = [[K. G. Jayan]]<br>[[Jayanan Vincent]]\n| editing        =  K. P. Puthran\n| studio         = [[Jubilee Productions]]\n| distributor    = Jubilee Productions\n| runtime        = 139 minutes        \n| country        = India\n| language       = Malayalam\n}}\n\n'''''Marupuram'''''  (\"The Other Side\") is a 1990 [[Malayalam]]-[[language]] [[action fiction|action]] [[crime]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film, directed by [[Viji Thampi]] and jointly written by [[Renjith]] and [[Kaloor Dennis]]. The film stars [[Jayaram]], [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], [[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]], [[Sukumaran]], [[Jagathy Sreekumar]], [[M. G. Soman]], [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]], [[Lalu Alex]], [[Jagadish]] and [[Devan (actor)|Devan]].\n\nThe movie is a thriller from [[Viji Thampi]], [[Renjith]] and [[Kaloor Dennis]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nTwo friends, Sethu ([[Jayaram]]) and Roy (Mukesh), are staying at a lodge owned by Rathna ([[Urvashi]]) and managed by Chakkuni ([[Jagathy]]). Sethu and Roy do con jobs to make ends meet and save money to send Roy abroad for a better life. They attempt a burglary that goes wrong and lands them in jail. After their release, Sethu decides to part ways with Roy. Sethu reaches the lodge as he's in love with Rathna. Chakkuni helps Sethu by giving him some educational certificates that belonged to a previous tenant. Sethu changes his name to Albert (the name on the educational certificate) and lands in a job as a company supervisor. Sethu lives in fear that someone will recognize him as Sethu costing him his job and sending him to prison again for forgery. Bharathan Menon, a friend of Sethu's boss and comes to visit him along with his family. His daughter is depressed and refuses marriage. Menon's meeting with Sethu startles and surprises him. He informs Sethu that he has seen him somewhere and starts probing, which frightens Sethu.\n\nSalim ([[Keerikkadan Jose]]) comes to town and starts inquiring about Albert. His agenda is to bump off Sethu. his first attempt fails. After Sethu returns, he sees Roy who has come to meet him. After dropping him off, Salim attacks Sethu again but loses his life accidentally.\n\nIssac Thomas ([[Sukumaran]]) investigates Salim's death. He finds a note of Albert's address in Salim's wallet and his encounter with Sethu raises doubt of Sethu's actual identity. The investigation begins and becomes more complex. The real Albert is dead and the suspect list is long, as everyone has a motive to kill Albert. Issac Thomas' investigation leads him from one suspect to another, and finally, it is revealed that it was Francis who killed Albert to protect his brother Binoy & his friends, who raped Menon's daughter while she was eloping with Albert. Francis then dumps Albert's body in Menon's garage and proceeds to blackmail him to get more time for an earlier deal they had between them. Sethu is exonerated and reunites with Roy & Rathnamma.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast list|\n*[[Jayaram]] as Sethumadhavan\n*[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Roy\n*[[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]] as Rathnamma\n*[[Sukumaran]]  as Issac Thomas\n*[[Jagathi Sreekumar]] as Chakkunni\n*[[Manoj K. Jayan]] as Albert Alex\n*[[Lalu Alex]] as Adv. R. K. Pillai\n*[[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]] as Rasheed\n*[[Jagadish]] as Mathew\n*[[M. G. Soman]] as Bharathan Menon\n*[[Devan (actor)|Devan]] as Francis\n*[[Keerikkadan Jose]] as Salim\n*[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Binoy\n*[[Mahesh (actor)|Mahesh]] as Binoy's Friend\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]] as Krishnanunni Menon\n*[[Jagannathan (actor)|Jagannathan]] as Nair\n*Kaveri as Maya Menon\n*[[Paravoor Bharathan]] as Rathnamma's Father\n*[[Spadikam George]] as Police Officer\n*[[Nandhu]] as Autorickshaw Driver\n*Appa Haja as Binoy's Friend\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|0279948}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Viji Thampi]]\n\n{{1990s-Malayalam-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About||the 2016 film|Marupuram (2016 film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2019}}\n{{Notability|film|date=October 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Marupuram\n| image          =\n| director       = [[Viji Thampi]]\n| producer       = [[Joy Thomas]]\n| writer         = [[Renjith]]<br>[[Kaloor Dennis]]\n| starring       = [[Jayaram]]<br>[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br>[[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]]<br>[[Sukumaran]]<br>[[Jagathy Sreekumar]]\n| music          = [[Mohan Sithara]]\n| cinematography = [[K. G. Jayan]]<br>[[Jayanan Vincent]]\n| editing        =  K. P. Puthran\n| studio         = [[Jubilee Productions]]\n| distributor    = Jubilee Productions\n| runtime        = 139 minutes        \n| country        = India\n| language       = Malayalam\n}}\n\n'''''Marupuram'''''  (\"The Other Side\") is a 1990 [[Malayalam]]-[[language]] [[action fiction|action]] [[crime]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film, directed by [[Viji Thampi]] and jointly written by [[Renjith]] and [[Kaloor Dennis]]. The film stars [[Jayaram]], [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], [[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]], [[Sukumaran]], [[Jagathy Sreekumar]], [[M. G. Soman]], [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]], [[Lalu Alex]], [[Jagadish]] and [[Devan (actor)|Devan]].\n\nThe movie is a thriller from the team of [[Viji Thampi]], [[Renjith]] and [[Kaloor Dennis]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nTwo friends, Sethu ([[Jayaram]]) and Roy (Mukesh), are staying at a lodge owned by Rathna ([[Urvashi]]) and managed by Chakkuni ([[Jagathy]]). Sethu and Roy do con jobs to make ends meet and save money to send Roy abroad for a better life. They attempt a burglary that goes wrong and lands them in jail. After their release, Sethu decides to part ways with Roy. Sethu reaches the lodge as he's in love with Rathna. Chakkuni helps Sethu by giving him some educational certificates that belonged to a previous tenant. Sethu changes his name to Albert (the name on the educational certificate) and lands in a job as a company supervisor. Sethu lives in fear that someone will recognize him as Sethu costing him his  job and sending him to prison again for forgery. Bharathan Menon, a friend of Sethu's boss and comes to visit him along with his family. His daughter is depressed and refuses marriage. Menon's meeting with Sethu startles and surprises him. He informs Sethu that he has seen him somewhere and starts probing, which frightens Sethu.\n\nSalim ([[Keerikkadan Jose]]) comes to town and starts inquiring about Albert. His agenda is to bump off Sethu. his first attempt fails. After Sethu returns, he sees Roy who has come to meet him. After dropping him off, Salim attacks Sethu again but loses his life accidentally.\n\nIssac Thomas ([[Sukumaran]]) investigates Salim's death. He finds a note of Albert's address in Salim's wallet and his encounter with Sethu raises doubt of Sethu's actual identity. The investigation begins and becomes more complex. The real Albert is dead and the suspect list is long, as everyone has a motive to kill Albert.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast list|\n*[[Jayaram]] as Sethumadhavan\n*[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Roy\n*[[Urvashi (actress)|Urvashi]] as Rathnamma\n*[[Sukumaran]]  as Issac Thomas\n*[[Jagathi Sreekumar]] as Chakkunni\n*[[Manoj K. Jayan]] as Albert Alex\n*[[Lalu Alex]] as Adv. R. K. Pillai\n*[[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]] as Rasheed\n*[[Jagadish]] as Mathew\n*[[M. G. Soman]] as Bharathan Menon\n*[[Devan (actor)|Devan]] as Francis\n*[[Keerikkadan Jose]] as Salim\n*[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Binoy\n*[[Mahesh (actor)|Mahesh]] as Binoy's Friend\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]] as Krishnanunni Menon\n*[[Jagannathan (actor)|Jagannathan]] as Nair\n*Kaveri as Maya Menon\n*[[Paravoor Bharathan]] as Rathnamma's Father\n*[[Spadikam George]] as Police Officer\n*[[Nandhu]] as Autorickshaw Driver\n*Appa Haja as Binoy's Friend\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|0279948}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Viji Thampi]]\n\n{{1990s-Malayalam-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Daily Prophet Editor", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding final details of the plot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marupuram"}
{"title_page": "Eddie Cooley", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{for|the basketball coach|Ed Cooley}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Eddie Cooley\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Edward James Cooley\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|mf=y|1933|4|15}}\n| birth_place         = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|mf=y|2020|4|15|1933|4|15}}\n| death_place         = [[Meridian, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| origin              = \n| genre               = R&B\n| occupation          =  Songwriter, singer\n| instrument          =  \n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Edward James Cooley''' (April 15, 1933 &ndash; April 15, 2020) was an American [[R&B]] singer and songwriter, who co-wrote the much-recorded song \"[[Fever (Little Willie John song)|Fever]].\"  He also had a US pop hit in 1956 with \"[[Priscilla (Eddie Cooley song)|Priscilla]],\" credited to '''Eddie Cooley and the Dimples'''.\n\n==Life==\nCooley was born in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], later moving to [[New York City]], where he befriended singer and songwriter [[Otis Blackwell]].  Around 1955 he contacted Blackwell with an idea for a song he had written, \"[[Fever (Little Willie John song)|Fever]].\"  According to Blackwell, Cooley said to him: \"Man, I got an idea for a song called 'Fever,' but I can\u00b4t finish it.\"  Blackwell finished writing the song, and it was recorded by [[Little Willie John]], becoming an R&B #1 hit in 1956, and later being recorded by [[Peggy Lee]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], and many others.<ref name=blackcat>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/eddie_cooley.htm |title=Eddie Cooley |website=Rockabilly.nl |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref name=hoffmann/><ref name=marion>{{cite web|url=http://doo-wop.blogg.org/themes-_dimples__1___eddie_cooley___the_-183564.html |title=*DIMPLES (1) (EDDIE COOLEY & THE) - doo-wop |website=Doo-wop.blogg.org |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\nCooley and Blackwell continued to collaborate on songs for musicians on the [[King Records (United States)|King]] label, including [[The 5 Royales]] and [[Joe Tex]].  Later in 1956, Cooley presented a song, \"Priscilla,\" to singer [[Boyd Bennett]], who turned it down.  A [[demo (music)|demo version]] reached Teddy Reig of [[Royal Roost Records]], and he arranged for Cooley to record it with a backing trio of girl singers, The Dimples &ndash; Beverly Coates, Carolyn Coates and Barbara Sanders &ndash; who Blackwell had discovered.<ref name=blackcat/><ref name=marion/>  The record was \"something of an anomaly: a black man performing in a rockabilly style.\"<ref name=hoffmann>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNfx07-AJwcC&pg=PA49&dq=%22eddie+cooley%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eKAQVMeiF4XE7AbGoYDoCA&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22eddie%20cooley%22&f=false  |author=Frank Hoffmann|title=Rhythm and Blues, Rap, and Hip-hop|publisher=Infobase Publishing|date=2005|pages=49\u201350}}</ref>  It was promoted by [[DJ]] [[Alan Freed]], and after first becoming successful on the [[East Coast of the United States|east coast]] rose up the national charts, reaching #20 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot 100|pop chart]] in November 1956. Although Cooley was not primarily a singer, he promoted it by touring. The song was released in the UK on the [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia]] label,<ref name=blackcat/> and also covered by [[Frankie Vaughan]].\n\nEddie Cooley and the Dimples recorded several further singles for the Royal Roost label, but none were successful.  He then returned to songwriting, and his songs were recorded by the female R&B singer [[Tiny Topsy]] (\"Aw! Shucks, Baby\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Tiny-Topsy-Aw-Shucks-Baby/release/963222 |title=Tiny Topsy - Aw! Shucks Baby (Vinyl, LP) |website=Discogs.com |date=2013-07-29 |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> and by [[Buzz Clifford]] and [[Conway Twitty]].  In 1959, he made his last recordings, for [[Herb Abramson]]'s [[Triumph Records (United States)|Triumph]] label, but again they were unsuccessful.  In the early 1960s, after Blackwell had had continued success as a songwriter for Elvis Presley, in particular, he approached Cooley to contribute tracks to the album ''We Wrote 'Em, We Sing 'Em''.  Cooley performed \"Fever\" and \"Lay It On\" on the album, released by [[MGM Records|MGM]] in 1961.<ref name=blackcat/>\n\nIn 2015, Eddie Cooley was reported to be living in [[Rose Hill, Jasper County, Mississippi]].<ref>[https://exploregram.com/driving-through-rose-hill-mississippi-i-took-a-portrait-of-eddie-cooley/  Christaan Felber, Portrait of Eddie Cooley, ''Exploregram.com'', July 7, 2015]</ref>  He died at Anderson Regional Medical Center in [[Meridian, Mississippi]] on April 15, 2020, his 87th birthday.<ref>[https://obituaries.meridianstar.com/obituary/eddie-cooley-1079018573  Obituary: Eddie Cooley], ''Meridian Star'', April 15, 2020. Retrieved April 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Eddie Cooley}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooley, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{for|the basketball coach|Ed Cooley}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Eddie Cooley\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Edward James Cooley\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|mf=y|1933|4|15}}\n| birth_place         = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|mf=y|2020|4|15|1933|4|15}}\n| death_place         = [[Meridian, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| origin              = \n| genre               = R&B\n| occupation          =  Songwriter, singer\n| instrument          =  \n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Edward James Cooley''' (April 15, 1933 &ndash; April 15, 2020) was an American [[R&B]] singer and songwriter, who co-wrote the much-recorded song \"[[Fever (Little Willie John song)|Fever]]\".  He also had a US pop hit in 1956 with \"[[Priscilla (Eddie Cooley song)|Priscilla]]\", credited to '''Eddie Cooley and the Dimples'''.\n\n==Life==\nCooley was born in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], later moving to [[New York City]], where he befriended singer and songwriter [[Otis Blackwell]].  Around 1955 he contacted Blackwell with an idea for a song he had written, \"[[Fever (Little Willie John song)|Fever]].\"  According to Blackwell, Cooley said to him: \"Man, I got an idea for a song called 'Fever,' but I can\u00b4t finish it.\"  Blackwell finished writing the song, and it was recorded by [[Little Willie John]], becoming an R&B #1 hit in 1956, and later being recorded by [[Peggy Lee]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], and many others.<ref name=blackcat>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/eddie_cooley.htm |title=Eddie Cooley |website=Rockabilly.nl |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref name=hoffmann/><ref name=marion>{{cite web|url=http://doo-wop.blogg.org/themes-_dimples__1___eddie_cooley___the_-183564.html |title=*DIMPLES (1) (EDDIE COOLEY & THE) - doo-wop |website=Doo-wop.blogg.org |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\nCooley and Blackwell continued to collaborate on songs for musicians on the [[King Records (United States)|King]] label, including [[The 5 Royales]] and [[Joe Tex]].  Later in 1956, Cooley presented a song, \"Priscilla,\" to singer [[Boyd Bennett]], who turned it down.  A [[demo (music)|demo version]] reached Teddy Reig of [[Royal Roost Records]], and he arranged for Cooley to record it with a backing trio of girl singers, The Dimples &ndash; Beverly Coates, Carolyn Coates and Barbara Sanders &ndash; who Blackwell had discovered.<ref name=blackcat/><ref name=marion/>  The record was \"something of an anomaly: a black man performing in a rockabilly style.\"<ref name=hoffmann>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNfx07-AJwcC&pg=PA49&dq=%22eddie+cooley%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eKAQVMeiF4XE7AbGoYDoCA&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22eddie%20cooley%22&f=false  |author=Frank Hoffmann|title=Rhythm and Blues, Rap, and Hip-hop|publisher=Infobase Publishing|date=2005|pages=49\u201350}}</ref>  It was promoted by [[DJ]] [[Alan Freed]], and after first becoming successful on the [[East Coast of the United States|east coast]] rose up the national charts, reaching #20 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot 100|pop chart]] in November 1956. Although Cooley was not primarily a singer, he promoted it by touring. The song was also released in the UK, on the [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia]] label <ref name=blackcat/>, and also covered by Frankie Vaughan.\n\nEddie Cooley and the Dimples recorded several further singles for the Royal Roost label, but none were successful.  He then returned to songwriting, and his songs were recorded by the female R&B singer [[Tiny Topsy]] (\"Aw! Shucks, Baby\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Tiny-Topsy-Aw-Shucks-Baby/release/963222 |title=Tiny Topsy - Aw! Shucks Baby (Vinyl, LP) |website=Discogs.com |date=2013-07-29 |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> and by [[Buzz Clifford]] and [[Conway Twitty]].  In 1959, he made his last recordings, for [[Herb Abramson]]'s [[Triumph Records (United States)|Triumph]] label, but again they were unsuccessful.  In the early 1960s, after Blackwell had had continued success as a songwriter for Elvis Presley, in particular, he approached Cooley to contribute tracks to the album ''We Wrote 'Em, We Sing 'Em''.  Cooley performed \"Fever\" and \"Lay It On\" on the album, released by [[MGM Records|MGM]] in 1961.<ref name=blackcat/>\n\nIn 2015, Eddie Cooley was reported to be living in [[Rose Hill, Jasper County, Mississippi]].<ref>[https://exploregram.com/driving-through-rose-hill-mississippi-i-took-a-portrait-of-eddie-cooley/  Christaan Felber, Portrait of Eddie Cooley, ''Exploregram.com'', July 7, 2015]</ref>  He died at Anderson Regional Medical Center in [[Meridian, Mississippi]] on April 15, 2020, his 87th birthday.<ref>[https://obituaries.meridianstar.com/obituary/eddie-cooley-1079018573  Obituary: Eddie Cooley], ''Meridian Star'', April 15, 2020. Retrieved April 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Eddie Cooley}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooley, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Tjhiggin", "label": "safe", "comment": "punc and link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eddie_Cooley"}
{"title_page": "Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox University\n  | name            = Technion<br />Israel Institute of Technology\n  | native_name     = {{Hebrew|\u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}}<br>{{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u062e\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646 - \u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0626\u064a\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627}}<!--Arabic names should be displayed for Israeli government agencies and institutions, as well as former government agencies and institutions-->\n| former_name     = Technikum<br/>(1912-1914)\n  | image           = Technion official seal.svg\n  | image_size      = 180px\n  | type            = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Technical university|Technical]]<br />[[research university|Research]]\n  | established     = April 11, 1912\n  | endowment       = [[US$]]1.6 billion<ref name=\"presidentsreport\">[https://presidentsreport.technion.ac.il/the-technion-in-numbers/ President's Report], 2016</ref>\n  | budget          = [[US$]]416 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.jweekly.com/2018/04/18/israels-world-class-universities-valuable-investment/ |title = Israel's world-class universities are a valuable investment|date = 18 April 2018}}</ref>\n  | staff           = \n  | faculty         = \n  | president       = [[Uri Sivan]]\n  | provost         =\n  | principal       =\n  | rector          =\n  | chancellor      =\n  | vice_chancellor =\n  | students        = 13,703 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\">[http://che.org.il/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Table-8.xlsx Table 8], annual report, [[Council for Higher Education in Israel]], 2014</ref>\n  | undergrad       = 9,251 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | postgrad        = 3,435 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | doctoral        = 1,004 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | city            = [[Haifa]]\n  | state           =\n  | country         = [[Israel]]\n  | campus          = Urban<br />{{convert|1325|dunam|acre}}\n  | colors          = Blue and Gold\n  | affiliations = [[Conference of European Schools for Advanced Engineering Education and Research|CESAER]]<br>EuroTech Universities\n  | website         = [https://www.technion.ac.il/en/home-2/ technion.ac.il]\n  | logo            = TechnionLogo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}} ''Ha-Tekhniyon \u2014 Makhon Tekhnologi le-Yisrael''; {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u062e\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646 - \u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0626\u064a\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627}}<!--Arabic names should be displayed for Israeli government agencies and institutions, as well as former government agencies and institutions-->) is a [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]. Established in 1912 during the [[Ottoman Empire]] and more than 35 years before the State of Israel, the Technion is the oldest university in the country.<ref name=\"technikum\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/862864|title=War of the Languages: Founding of the Technion/Technikum|author=Sveta Reingold|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Technion is ranked as the top university in Israel and the [[Middle East]] and the 85th in the world in the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] of 2019.<ref>http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html</ref> The university offers degrees in science and engineering, and related fields such as architecture, medicine, industrial management, and education. It has 19 academic departments, 60 research centers, and 12 affiliated teaching hospitals.<ref>http://int.technion.ac.il/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Technion-Intl-Brochure-English-2015-16.pdf</ref> Since its founding, it has awarded more than 100,000 degrees<ref>[http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/10/2014-15-welcoming-the-new-academic-year/ 2014\u201315 Welcoming the New Academic Year], Technion website</ref> and its graduates are cited for providing the skills and education behind the creation and protection of the [[State of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3RiIYgCC7Gw|title=Technion Nation - Building Israel the Start-Up Nation|last=Technion|date=11 June 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>[http://startupnationbook.com/ Start-Up Nation Book]. Start-Up Nation Book (18 January 2013). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\nTechnion's 565 faculty members currently include three [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Laureates]] in chemistry. Four [[Nobel Laureates]] have been associated with the university. The current [[List of presidents of the Technion|president of the Technion]] is [[Uri Sivan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Prof-Uri-Sivan-takes-office-as-President-of-Technion-603234|title=Prof. Uri Sivan takes office as President of Technion|publisher=|date = 29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Technion has played a major role in the history of modern Israel. The selection of [[Modern Hebrew|Hebrew]] as the language of instruction, defeating German in the [[War of the Languages]], was an important milestone in Hebrew's consolidation as Israel's official language.<ref>[http://www.jewishhistory.org.il/history.php?search=Haifa&dosearch.x=9&dosearch.y=9&dosearch=Search Jewish History]. Jewish History. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Technion is also a major factor behind the growth of Israel's [[high-tech]] industry and innovation, including the country's technical cluster in [[Silicon Wadi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnpublications.net/2011/06/30/israel-leads-in-high-tech-2/|title=Israel leads in high-tech - Reporting on the Middle East, Science, and Education|website=cnpublications.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcrunch.com/secret-israel-s-high-tech-success/3672|title=The Secret of Israel's High-tech Success (Le Monde)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{Main|History of the Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology}}\n\n[[File:Einstein technion.jpg|thumb|220px|[[Albert Einstein]] at Technion; 11 February 1923]]\n\nThe Technikum was conceived in the early 1900s by the German-Jewish fund [[Ezrah]] as a school of engineering and sciences. It was to be the only institution of higher learning in the then [[History of Palestine#Ottoman era|Ottoman Palestine]], other than the [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] in [[Jerusalem]] (founded in 1907). In October 1913, the board of trustees selected [[German language|German]] as the language of instruction, provoking a major controversy known as the [[War of the Languages]]. After opposition from American and Russian Jews to the use of German, the board of trustees reversed itself in February 1914 and selected Hebrew as the language of instruction. The German name Technikum was also replaced by the Hebrew name Technion.<ref name=\"technikum\"/><ref name=\"cie\">{{cite web|title=Technion University Selects Hebrew as Language of Instruction|url=https://israeled.org/hebrew-language/|website=Center for Israel Education|date=22 February 2018|access-date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTechnion's cornerstone was laid in 1912, and studies began 12 years later in 1924.<ref name=\"cie\"/> In 1923 [[Albert Einstein]] visited and planted the now-famous first [[Arecaceae|palm tree]], as an initiative of [[Nobel Prize|Nobel]] tradition. The first palm tree still stands today in front of the old Technion building, which is now the MadaTech museum, in the Hadar neighborhood. Einstein founded the first Technion Society, and served as its president upon his return to [[Germany]].\n\nIn 1924, [[Arthur Blok]] became the Technion's first president.<ref>https://www.technion.ac.il/en/former-presidents/</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Churchillbuilding.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Churchill Auditorium]]\n[[File:Aerospace Faculty (Technion).JPG|thumb|Aerospace Faculty (Technion)]]\n[[File:Civil and Enviornmental Engineering Faculty Technion.jpg|thumb|Civil and Environmental Engineering Faculty Technion]]\n[[File:ViewtoElectricalengg.jpg|thumb|right|220px|View towards the Electrical and Electronics Engineering Building from Obelisk]]\n[[File:Technion Computer Science Faculty.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Computer Science Faculty Building]]\n[[File:Industrial Engineering and Management at Technion by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|220px|Faculty of Industrial Engineering & Management]]\n[[File:Mathematics department.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Faculty of Mathematics]]\n[[File:Erd\u0151s\u2013Faber\u2013Lov\u00e1sz conjecture.svg|thumb|[[Erd\u0151s\u2013Faber\u2013Lov\u00e1sz conjecture]]]]\n[[File:Technion Faculty of Medicine.jpg|thumb|Technion Faculty of Medicine]]\n[[File:\u05dc\u05d1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05de\u05e4\u05d5\u05e1 \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4.jpg|thumb|Technion Faculty of Mathematics]]\n[[File:Technion-Obelisk.jpg|thumb|right|220px|The Obelisk, the stainless-steel structure 28 meters tall, is a [[kinetic art|kinetic sculpture]]]]\n\n===Haifa===\nTechnion City generally refers to the 1.2-square-kilometer site located on the pine-covered north-eastern slopes of [[Mount Carmel]]. The campus comprises 100 buildings, occupied by thousands of people every day.\n\nThe Technion has two additional campuses. Its original building in midtown Haifa, in use by the Technion until the mid-1980s, now houses the [[Israel National Museum of Science, Technology, and Space|Israel National Museum of Science, Technology and Space]]. The [[Rappaport Faculty of Medicine]] is located in the neighborhood of [[Bat Galim]], adjacent to [[Rambam Hospital]], the largest medical center in Northern Israel.\n\nRecreational activities on the main campus include an Olympic-size swimming pool as well as gymnastics, squash, and tennis facilities.<ref>[http://ciar.technion.ac.il/sport-facilities/ Sports Facilities]. Ciar.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Technion Symphony Orchestra and Choir are composed mainly of Technion students and staff. Each term, the Orchestra offers a series of daytime and evening concerts. Films and live performances by leading Israeli artists take place on campus on a regular basis.\n\n===Tel Aviv===\nTechnion's Division of Continuing Education and External Studies has been operating in the Tel Aviv area since 1958. In July 2013, the Technion moved to a new campus in [[Sarona (colony)|Sarona]]. The Technion satellite campus in Sarona includes three buildings in a 1,800 sq. meter area, with a total of 16 modern classrooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/03/technion-azrieli-sarona-campus-tel-aviv/|title=Technion-Azrieli Sarona Campus|publisher=Technion|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref> Among the programs that study at Sarona are the Technion's International MBA program, which includes students from around the world and guest lecturers from universities such as [[London Business School]], [[Columbia University]], and [[INSEAD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technionmba.com|title=MBA in Israel|publisher=Technion|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell Tech===\n{{Main|Cornell Tech}}\nOn 19 December 2011, a bid by a consortium of [[Cornell University]] and Technion won a competition to establish a new high-tier applied science and engineering institution in New York City. The competition was established by New York City Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] in order to increase entrepreneurship and job growth in the city's technology sector. The winning bid consisted of a {{convert|2100000|sqft|m2}} state-of-the-art tech campus being built on [[Roosevelt Island]], which will have its first phase completed by 2017, with a temporary off-site campus opening in 2013 at the [[Google]] New York City headquarters building at [[111 Eighth Avenue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/Dec11/NYCcover.html|title='Game-changing' tech campus goes to Cornell, Technion|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Harman|first=Danna|title=The Technion: Israel's Hard Drive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/education/edlife/inside-the-technion-israels-premier-technological-institute-and-cornells-global-partner.html|accessdate=20 April 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=14 April 2013}}</ref> The new 'School of Genius' in New York City has been named the Jacobs Technion-Cornell Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tech.cornell.edu/jacobs-technion-cornell-institute|title=Overview|work=Cornell Tech|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Its Founding Director was [[Craig Gotsman]], Technion's Hewlett-Packard Professor of Computer Engineering.\n\nMost recently, [[AOL]] has announced an investment of $5 million in a video research project at the Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2015/01/18/shirt-that-monitors-hearts-destroying-cancer-cells-new-gas-fields-its-good-news-from-israel/|title=Shirt that Monitors Hearts, Destroying Cancer Cells, New Gas Fields: It's Good News from Israel!|work=Jewish Business News|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> \nPositive media coverage abounds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2014/08/8551250/future-island|title=Future island|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> as well as some small scale protests from the margins of political and environmental activism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mondoweiss.net/2013/11/partnership-technions-militarization|title=Technion's role in U.S. militarization and domestic spying|work=Mondoweiss|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Guangdong Technion Israel Institute of Technology===\n{{Main|Guangdong Technion-Israel Institute of Technology}}\n\nIn September 2013 the [[Li Ka Shing Foundation]] and the Technion announced they would be joining forces to create a new institute for technology at [[Shantou University]], [[Guangdong|Guangdong province]], south-eastern China.\nThe Li Ka Shing Foundation pledged a grant of US$130 million for the creation of the institute. The degrees taught, including Bachelors, Masters and Doctorates, will be accredited by the Technion. The total construction costs are $147 million.\nEnglish will be GTIIT's language of instruction. GTIIT will comprise three units: the College of Engineering; the College of Science; and the College of Life Science. The goal is to have about 5,000 students eventually. The institute will eventually grant Technion engineering degrees at all levels - Bachelor, Masters and PhD. Initially the courses offered are Chemical Engineering, Biotechnology and Food Engineering, Materials Engineering.<ref>http://www.gtiit.edu.cn/en/programs-of-study.aspx</ref> By 2020 the institute will start teaching other disciplines from Mechanics to Aerospace Engineering.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Guangdong Technion Israel Institute of Technology (GTIIT) in China is launched|url=http://pard.technion.ac.il/4198-2/|accessdate=4 November 2014|website=pard.technion.co.il|date=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shantou University|url=http://www.lksf.org/shantou-university/|accessdate=4 November 2014|website=[[Li Ka Shing Foundation]]|date=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Neuman|first=Efrat|title=The story behind a HK billionaire's $130 million donation to the Technion|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.550634|accessdate=4 November 2014|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=5 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\n\n===Aerospace Engineering===\nFounded in 1954, the [[Technion Faculty of Aerospace Engineering|Faculty of Aerospace Engineering]] conducts research and education in a wide range of aerospace disciplines. The Aerospace Research Center also consists of the Aerodynamics (wind tunnels) Laboratory, the Aerospace Structures Laboratory, the Combustion and Rocket Propulsion Laboratory, the Turbo and Jet Engine Laboratory, the Flight Control Laboratory and the Design for Manufacturing Laboratory.\n\n===Architecture and Town Planning===\n\nThe Technion Faculty of Architecture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://architecture.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05d0\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05d8\u05e7\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05d9 \u05e2\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd|website=architecture.technion.ac.il}}</ref> awards BArch degrees awarded after five years of study.<ref name=\"technionil\">{{cite web|url=http://architecture.technion.ac.il/faculty.php?pi=15 |title=Technion, Faculty of Architecture and Town Planning |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> Its graduate program in architecture accepts about 15 students each year, and it accepts about 4\u20135 doctoral students, focusing on subjects such as architectural theory and philosophy, bio-climate and energy conscious design, morphology, computer application, person-environment relations, housing, architectural history, and urban design.<ref name=\"technionil\"/>\n\n===Biology===\n\nThe Faculty of Biology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biology.technion.ac.il/|title=Biology Technion|website=biology.technion.ac.il}}</ref> was established in 1971. Advanced research is carried out in 23 research groups, focusing on a variety of aspects of cellular, molecular and developmental biology. The faculty has extensive collaborations with the pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries. The Faculty has around 350 undergraduate students and over 100 graduate students.<ref name=\"The Technion Insider 2007\">The Technion Insider: Technion prospectus from 2007.</ref>\n\n===Biomedical Engineering===\n\nEstablished in 1968, the Faculty of Biomedical Engineering<ref>http://www.bm.technion.ac.il/Pages/Information_BME_Department.aspx</ref> has a multidisciplinary scope nurturing research activities that blend medical and biological engineering. Research projects have resulted in the development of patented medical aids. Recent research breakthroughs include\nthe identification of a structured neurological code for syllables and could let paraplegics \"speak\" virtually through the connection of the brain to a computer.<ref>Siegel, Judy. (23 August 2012) [http://www.jpost.com/Health/Article.aspx?id=282255 Israeli research may help severely paralyzed speak | JPost | Israel News]. JPost. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n===Biotechnology and Food Engineering===\n\nUnique in Israel, the Faculty of Biotechnology and Food Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biotech.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05ea \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05d6\u05d5\u05df - \u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|website=biotech.technion.ac.il}}</ref> offers a blend of courses in engineering, life and natural sciences as well as joint degree programs with the Faculties of Biology and Chemistry. The Faculty houses biotechnology laboratories, as well as a large food processing pilot plant and a packaging laboratory. It currently has 350 undergraduates and more than 120 graduate students.\n\n===Civil and Environmental Engineering===\n\nIn 2002, two of the original Technion Faculties \u2013 Civil and Agricultural engineering, were merged to create the Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cee.technion.ac.il/eng/|title=Technion Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea|first=Minicy Catom Software Engineering Ltd.|last=www.catom.com|website=cee.technion.ac.il}}</ref> Its state vision is to \"maintain and enhance the leading position of the Faculty of Civil & Environmental Engineering amongst the top departments in the world... and to position the Faculty as the national center for research & development and human resources for the sustainable development.\"<ref>[http://cee.technion.ac.il/eng/ Technion Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea]. Cee.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Faculty is the home of Technion's expanding [[Technion International School of Engineering|International School of Engineering]].\n\n===Chemical Engineering===\n\nThe Wolfson Faculty of Chemical Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemeng.technion.ac.il/|title=Home Page - \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05ea - \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df|website=chemeng.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is Israel's oldest and largest faculty in the field, educating the vast majority of chemical engineers in Israel's chemical industries.<ref name=\"The Technion Insider 2007\"/> Research activities include materials, complex fluids, processing, transport and surface phenomena and process control.\n\n===Chemistry===\n\nThe Schulich Faculty of Chemistry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05e9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05da \u2013 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05d4|website=chemistry.technion.ac.il}}</ref> offers a variety of joint programs, including with materials engineering, chemical engineering, physics, and food engineering. It also offers a joint degree with the Faculty of Biology leading to a degree in molecular biochemistry. Around 100 research projects at the faculty are sponsored by industry and national and international foundations. It also offers a variety of outreach and youth programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.technion.ac.il/#|title=\u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05e9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05da|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Computer Science===\n\nFounded in 1969, this is one of the largest Technion faculties, with over 1,000 undergraduate students and 200 graduate students. The Faculty of Computer Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.technion.ac.il|title=Computer Science Department, Technion|first=Yaniv |last=Hamo |website=www.cs.technion.ac.il}}</ref> was ranked 15th among 500 universities in computer sciences for 2011 and 18th of 500 since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html|title=Technion-Israel Institute of Technology - Academic Ranking of World Universities - 2016 - Shanghai Ranking - 2016|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref> The Faculty is located in the Taub Family Science and Technology Center, following the support of the philanthropist [[Henry Taub]].\n\n===Education in Technology and Science===\n\nFounded in 1965, the Department of Education in Technology & Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edu.technion.ac.il/en/|title=\u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05df (\u05d0\u05e8\u05d9) \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5 \u2013 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d7\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05da \u05dc\u05de\u05d3\u05e2 \u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4|website=edu.technion.ac.il}}</ref> became a faculty in 2015. The faculty trains undergraduates in the most advanced methods of teaching science and technology in schools. The faculty is home to a research and development center in the field. It has over 100 graduate students and 350 undergraduate students including second career engineers and scientists who elect to study toward STEM educator career.\n\n===Electrical Engineering===\n\nThe [[Technion Faculty of Electrical Engineering|Faculty of Electrical Engineering]] claims to be the major source of engineers who lead the development of advanced Israeli technology in the fields of electronics, computers and communications. Some 2000 undergraduate students study in the department for a BSc degree in electrical engineering / computer engineering / computer and software engineering, and 400 graduate students study for the degrees of MSc and PhD. The department has extensive relations with industry as well as academic and industrial special liaison support programs.<ref>[http://webee.technion.ac.il/Industrial-Relations/Mission-and-Activities Technion \u2013 Electrical Engineering: Your Portal to High-Tech]. Webee.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n===Humanities and Arts===\nThe Department of Humanities and Arts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://humanities.technion.ac.il/|title=Home Page|website=humanities.technion.ac.il}}</ref> serves all the Technion community, offering courses taught by renowned visiting and adjunct scholars including philosophy of science, social and political sciences, linguistics, psychology, law and anthropology and an array of theoretical and performing arts courses.\n\n====The Technion Theater====\n{{Main|Technion theater}}\n\nThe Technion Theater was established in 1986, by Professor [[Ouriel Zohar]]. The theater teaches 8 courses, and it has about 150 students per semester. The theater presented 52 performances in different styles, some by [[Hanoch Levin]], [[Yehoshua Sobol]], [[Moliere]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Pierre de Marivaux]], [[Henrik Ibsen]] and [[George Bernard Shaw|Bernard Shaw]], [[S\u0142awomir Mro\u017cek]] among others. The theater also presented plays written by the director and the actors. The theater is invited to many festivals in Europe universities. Director [[Scandar Copti]] received [[Ophir Award]] in 2010, played in \"End End\" directed by Zohar, which was presented in [[Jerusalem]] festival in 2001. Shlomo Plessner participated in collective plays \"soft mattress\" and \"Mix Marriage\" 1986\u20131987. The play \"Transparent Chains\" by Sheli Baliti from the Faculty of [[Chemical Engineering]] performed at [[Bratislava]] in 2006, [[Granada]], [[Haifa Cinematheque]], Neve Yosef Festival and the Theatre Department at the [[University of Haifa]] in 2007. The play [[An Enemy of the People]] by Ibsen, the main actor Rooney Navon, Professor at the Faculty of [[Civil and Environmental Engineering]], received honorable nomination at [[Benevento]] in Italy in 2009, and also in [[Isfia]] near Haifa. The Show \"invisible clothes\" written and directed by Ouriel Zohar presented at The International Theater Festival in [[Saint Petersburg State University]] in 2012.\n\n===Industrial Engineering and Management===\n\n[[The William Davidson Faculty of Industrial Engineering & Management]] (IE&M) is the oldest such department in Israel. IE&M was launched as a Technion academic Department in 1958. The Department grew under the leadership of ''Pinchas Naor'', who served as its founding Dean. Naor's vision was to combine Industrial engineering with Management by creating a large, inherently multidisciplinary unit covering a wide spectrum of activities such as applied engineering, mathematical modeling, economics, [[behavioral sciences]], [[operations research]], and statistics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.technion.ac.il/|title=Home - \u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05ea \u05ea\u05e2\u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df|website=ie.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n===Materials Science and Engineering===\n\nHome to Nobel Laureate in Chemistry Distinguished [[Dan Shechtman|Prof. Dan Shechtman]], the Faculty of Materials Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/about-materials-engineering-faculty-technion/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is Israel's major study center in materials science. The Faculty houses the Electron Microscopy Center,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/electron-microscopy-Mika-Materials-Engineering/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> the X-Ray Diffraction Laboratory,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/x-ray-lab-Materials-Engineering/-Engineering/|title=Engineering Nanostructured Thin Films for Greener Electronics \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> the Atomic force microscopy Laboratory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/AFM-atomic-force-microscopy-lab/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> and the Physical and Mechanical Measurements lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/physical-mechanical-measurments-lab/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n===Mathematics===\n\nThe Faculty of Mathematics<ref>https://www.math.technion.ac.il/</ref> houses both pure and applied mathematics, and was home to the mathematician [[Paul Erd\u0151s]]. Founded in 1950, it has around 46 faculty members, 200 undergraduate students and 100 graduate students. It provides instruction for students in all other Technion faculties and organizes mathematics competition for gifted high school students and a summer camp in number theory.\n\n===Mechanical Engineering===\n\nFounded in 1948, the Technion Faculty of Mechanical Engineering<ref name=\"technion.ac.il\">{{cite web|url=http://meeng.technion.ac.il/en/|title=Energy performance analysis of a passive elastic element with a timed clutch for human load carriage - Mechanical Engineering Faculty|website=meeng.technion.ac.il}}</ref> has over 830 students and 215 graduate students. Research is conducted in the faculty's 36 laboratories across the whole spectrum of mechanical engineering, from nano-scale fields through to applied engineering of national projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL5D8815BC3AF656ED|title=Mechanical-Engineering-Technion - YouTube|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\n\nThe Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://md.technion.ac.il|title=The Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine|website=md.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is home to two [[Nobel Laureates]]: [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]]. It is one of four state-sponsored medical schools in Israel. It was founded in 1979 through the philanthropy of [[Bruce Rappaport]] and is active in basic science research and pre-clinical medical training in [[anatomy]], [[biochemistry]], [[biophysics]], [[immunology]], [[microbiology]], [[physiology]], and [[pharmacology]].<ref>[http://www.rambam.org.il/Home+Page/About+Us/News+and+Events/News+2010/Rambam+Mourns+Baruch+Rappaport+Visionary+and+Generous+Donor.htm rambam mourns baruch rappaport visionary and generous donor]. Rambam.org.il (11 January 2010). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> Other facilities on the Faculty of Medicine campus include teaching laboratories, a medical library, lecture halls, and seminar rooms. Academic programs lead to Master of Science (M.S.), Doctor of Philosophy (PhD), and Doctor of Medicine (M.D.) degrees. It also offers medical training leading to a M.D. degree to qualified American and Canadian graduates of pre-med programs under the Technion American Medical School Program (TeAMS).<ref>{{YouTube|KSIoZYsnMBk|Technion American Medical Students Program TEAMS}} (3 June 2012). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The school has developed collaborative research and medical education programs with various institutions in medicine and bio-medical engineering including [[Harvard University]], [[New York University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Haifa-and-NY-researchers-collaborate-on-treatment-for-two-deadly-cancers-452214|title=Haifa and NY researchers collaborate on treatment for two deadly cancers|publisher=}}</ref> [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[University of Toronto]], [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] and [[Mayo Medical School]].\n\n===Physics===\n\nThe Faculty of Physics<ref name=\"technion.ac.il1\">{{cite web|url=http://physics.technion.ac.il/eng/|title=home|website=physics.technion.ac.il}}</ref> engages in experimental and theoretical research in the fields of astrophysics, high energy physics, solid state physics and biophysics. Founded in 1960, it includes the Einstein Institute of Physics, the Lidow Physics Complex, The Rosen Solid State Building and the Werksman Physics Building.\n\n==Multidisciplinary centers==\n\n===Nanotechnology and science===\nThe [[Russell Berrie Nanotechnology Institute]] (RBNI) was established in January 2005 as a joint endeavour of the Russell Berrie Foundation, the government of Israel, and the Technion. It is one of the largest academic programs in Israel, and is among the largest nanotechnology centers in Europe and the US. RBNI has over 110 faculty members, and approximately 300 graduate students and postdoctoral fellows under its auspices at Technion. Its multidisciplinary activities span 14 different faculties.\n\n===Energy research===\nThe [[Grand Technion Energy Program|GTEP Nancy and Stephen Grand Technion Energy Program]] is a multidisciplinary center of excellence bringing together Technion's top researchers in energy science and technology from over nine different faculties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gtep.technion.ac.il/|title=Grand Technion Energy Program - Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Founded in 2007, GTEP's 4-point strategy targets research and development of alternative fuels; renewable energy sources; energy storage and conversion; and energy conservation. The GTEP is presently the only center in Israel offering graduate studies in energy science and technology.\n\n===Space research===\n\nThe [[Asher Space Research Institute|Norman and Helen Asher Space Research Institute (ASRI)]] is a specialized institute dedicated to multidisciplinary [[science|scientific]] [[research]]. Established in 1984, its members come from five Technion faculties, and it has a technical staff of Technion scientists in a variety of space-related fields: (Physics,<ref name=\"technion.ac.il1\"/> Aerospace Engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ae-www.technion.ac.il/|title=Faculty of Aerospace Engineering - Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|website=ae-www.technion.ac.il|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928041040/http://ae-www.technion.ac.il/|archivedate=28 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mechanical Engineering,<ref name=\"technion.ac.il\"/> Electrical Engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webee.technion.ac.il/|title=Technion - Electrical Engineering: Your Portal to High-Tech|website=webee.technion.ac.il}}</ref> Autonomous Systems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasp.technion.ac.il/|title=Home|first=Super|last=User|website=tasp.technion.ac.il}}</ref> and Computer Sciences).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/|title=Computer Science Department, Technion|first=Yaniv |last=Hamo |website=www.cs.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n==Technology transfer==\nTechnion has an impressive record in technology transfer. Its dedicated office to bridge the transition of scientific and technological discovery to successfully commercialized innovation has been active since 2007 as [[T3 Technion Technology Transfer|T<sup>3</sup> \u2013 Technion Technology Transfer.]] As of 2011, 424 [[patents]] were granted to Technion innovations, with 845 patents pending. T<sup>3</sup>'s partners include incubators, entrepreneurs, private investors, [[Venture capital|VCs]] and [[angel groups]]. It has strategic partnerships with [[Microsoft]], [[IBM]], [[Intel]], [[Philips]], [[Johnson & Johnson]], [[Coca-Cola]], among others.\n\n==Technion international==\n\nThe Technion International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://int.technion.ac.il/|title=Technion - Technion International|website=int.technion.ac.il}}</ref> (TI) is a department in the Technion, offering courses taught entirely in English. The TI began its first year in 2009, and now offers a full BSc in Civil Engineering, BSc in Mechanical Engineering as well as various study abroad options, all taught in English. Student come from all over the globe \u2013 Asia, Africa, North and South America, Europe and Israel. They live on campus and enjoy trips around Israel and activities throughout the year.\n\n==Outreach programs==\n\nTechnion offers after-school and summer enrichment courses for young people on subjects ranging from introductory electronics and computer programming to aerospace, architecture, biology, chemistry and physics. Two examples are Scitech<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scitech.technion.ac.il/ |title=Scitech summer camp at the Technion |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> and the Math Summer Camp, devoted to number theory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.math.technion.ac.il/Noam/tomba-e.html |title=Math Summer Camp |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nTechnion recently set up and orchestrated the Israeli chapter of [[Engineers Without Borders]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ci1henu1OQg|title=Engineering with a Soul - Technion Engineers Without Borders|last=Technion|date=27 January 2011|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> which among other projects, installed a network of biogas systems in rural [[Nepal]] providing sustainable energy and improved sanitation.<ref>[http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/studentsStory2.htm TECHNION FOCUS MAGAZINE \u2013 Students \u2013 Engineering with a Soul]. Focus.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n== Technion in the Israeli society ==\nThe Technion takes an active role in empowering students from unrepresented groups in the Israeli society, such as [[Haredim|ultra orthodox Jew]] and Arabs, by giving dedicated scholarships, social programs, and additional financial support. Moreover, the Technion is one of the main sponsors for the Israeli league of FIRST robotics competition which became a formal project of the Technion since 2013. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://he.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIRST|title=FIRST- Hebrew Wikipedia|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 10615 technion ecological garden.jpg|thumb|The technion ecological garden]]\n{{Infobox world university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 93 | ARWU_W_ref = <ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017]</ref>\n| THE_W = | THE_W_ref =\n| QS_W = | QS_W_ref =\n}}\nIn 2015, the Shanghai Academic Ranking rated the Technion as 77th in its list of the top 100 universities in the world.<ref name=\"ARWU\">{{cite web | url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html | title=3 Academic Ranking of World Universities | accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the magazine [[Business Insider]] ranked Technion among the top 25 engineering schools in the world.<ref>[http://israel21c.org/news/technion-in-top-25-engineering-schools-in-the-world/ Technion in Top 25 engineering schools in the world]. ISRAEL21c (10 July 2012). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arwu.org/#|title=World University Rankings 2013-2014|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Center for World University Rankings ranked Technion 51st in the world and third in Israel in its CWUR World University Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwur.org/top100.html|title= Top 100 |publisher=Center for World University Rankings| year=2012 | accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor national rankings in 2011, Technion was ranked the No. 2 of universities in Israel by [[ARWU]]. In global rankings for that year, Technion was ranked #102\u2013150 by ARWU, No. 220 by [[QS World University Rankings|QS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/technion-israel-institute-technology/wur|title=Technion 2011 ranking|publisher=QS|accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was ranked #201\u2013225 by [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2011-2012/201-225.html|title=Technion 2011 ranking|newspaper=Times|accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Technion was the only school outside of the United States to make it into the top 10 on a new Bloomberg Rankings list of schools whose graduates are CEOs of top U.S. tech companies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Israel's Technion Ranks High on Bloomberg List of Schools Sending Graduates to Top Tech Companies|url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/09/02/israels-technion-ranks-high-on-bloomberg-list-of-schools-sending-graduates-to-top-tech-companies/|accessdate=10 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Algemeiner]]|date=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Research highlights==\n[[File:Rasagiline-3D-balls-A.png|thumb|Chemical structure of Rasagline]]\n\n* In 1982, [[Dan Shechtman]] discovered a [[Quasicrystal]] structure. This is a structure with a Symmetry in the order of 5 \u2013 a phenomenon considered impossible until then by the then-current prevailing theories of [[Crystallography]]. In 2011 he won the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for this discovery.\n* In 2004, two Technion professors, [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]], won the Nobel Prize for the discovery of the biological system responsible for disassembling protein in the cell.\n* Shulamit Levenberg, 37, was chosen by ''[[Scientific American]]'' magazine as one of the leading scientists in 2006 for the discovery of a method to transplant skin in a way the body does not reject.<ref>[http://www.bm.technion.ac.il/~shulamit BME Person Info | \u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5 \u05e8\u05e4\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df]. Bm.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n* [[Moussa B.H. Youdim]] developed [[Rasagiline]], a drug marketed by [[Teva Pharmaceuticals]] as [[Azilect|Azilect (TM)]] for the treatment of neurodegenerative disease, especially [[Parkinsons]].\n* In 1998, Technion successfully launched the \"Gurwin TechSat II\" microsatellite, making Technion one of five universities with a student program that designs, builds, and launches its own satellite. The satellite stayed in orbit until 2010<ref>{{cite news |author=Web Development Company |url=http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/newsStory11.htm |title=News |publisher=Technion Focus Magazine |date=10 July 1998 |accessdate=8 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929095838/http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/newsStory11.htm |archivedate=29 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In the 1970s, computer scientists [[Abraham Lempel]] and [[Jacob Ziv]] developed the [[Lempel-Ziv-Welch]] algorithm for data compression. In 1995 and 2007 they won an [[IEEE Richard W. Hamming Medal]] for pioneering work in data compression and especially for developing the algorithm.\n*In 2019, a team of 12 students won a gold medal at [[IGEM competition|iGEM]] for developing bee-free honey<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel21c.org/israeli-students-win-award-for-making-honey-without-bees/|title=Israeli students win award for making honey without bees|last=Blum|first=Brian|date=2019-11-17|website=Israel21c|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> \n\n== The Technion Library System ==\n{{Main|Elyachar Central Library}}\n[[File:Technion Central Library.JPG|thumb|A frontal view of Elyachar Central Library]]\n\nThe Technion library system is made of the Elyachar Central Library and research libraries that are located in the faculty buildings. The Central Library determines professional policies and guidelines and provides services for all the Technion libraries, including the library operating systems, the libraries' [[web portal]], [[library acquisitions|acquisitions]], [[cataloging]], [[library classification|classification]], and [[interlibrary loan]]s.\n\nThe faculty research libraries' aim is to focus on the information needs of their students and academic staff. The libraries are transforming from traditional academic libraries to [[learning commons]]. The transition includes an ongoing process of evaluation of the libraries' collections with the aim of identifying items in high demand and use to keep, valuable items to preserve, items in nominal use to archive in the Central Library, rare and precious items to preserve in the historical archive of the Technion, at the Central Library, and items to withdraw, according to professional criteria.\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe percentage of Arab students at the Technion equals the percentage of the general Arab population in Israel: 20%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/education/edlife/inside-the-technion-israels-premier-technological-institute-and-cornells-global-partner.html|title=Inside the Technion, Israel's premier technological institute and Cornell's global partner.|first=Danna|last=Harman|date=12 April 2013|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/05/new-program-for-outstanding-arab-students-2/|title=Outstanding Arab Students|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Nobel Laureates and notable people ==\n\n===Nobel Laureates===\n\n* 2004 [[Avram Hershko]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2004 [[Aaron Ciechanover]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2011 [[Dan Shechtman]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2013 [[Arieh Warshel]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n\n===Select faculty===<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\n* [[Moshe Arens]], professor of aeronautics from 1957 to 1962.\n* [[Eli Biham]], [[cryptanalyst]] and [[cryptographer]]\n* [[Yaakov Dori]], President\n* [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]], recipients of the 2004 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]] for the discovery of [[ubiquitin]]-mediated [[protein degradation]]\n* [[Amos Horev]], former President, former Chairman of [[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems|Rafael]]; member of the Israeli [[Turkel Commission]] of Inquiry into the [[Gaza flotilla raid]]\n* [[Abraham Lempel]] and [[Jacob Ziv]], developers of the [[Lempel-Ziv]] (LZW) compression algorithm\n* [[Liviu Librescu]], hero during the [[Virginia Tech shooting]]\n* [[Marcelle Machluf]], biotechnology and food engineering\n* [[Shlomo Moran]], computer scientist\n* [[Eliahu Nissim]] (born 1933), Professor of Aeronautical Engineering; President of the [[Open University of Israel]]\n* [[Asher Peres]], co-discoverer of [[quantum teleportation]], awarded the 2004 Rothschild Prize in Physics\n* [[Anat Rafaeli]], [[organisational behaviour]] researcher\n* [[Nathan Rosen]], co-author with [[Albert Einstein]] and [[Boris Podolsky]] of physics paper about the [[EPR paradox]] in [[quantum mechanics]]\n* [[Rachel Shalon]], first woman engineer in Israel\n* [[Shlomo Shamai]], electrical information theorist\n* [[Dan Shechtman]], first observer of [[quasicrystal]]s and winner of the 2011 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]]\n* [[Daniel Weihs]] (born 1942), [[Aeronautical Engineering]] professor \n* [[Shmuel Zaks]], computer scientist and mathematician\n* [[Mario Livio]], astrophysicist and an author of works that popularize science and mathematics\n\n===Notable alumni===<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\nTechnion graduates have been estimated to constitute over 70 percent of the founders and managers of high-tech businesses in Israel. 80 percent of Israeli NASDAQ companies were founded and/or are led by Technion graduates, and 74 percent of managers in Israel's electronic industries hold Technion degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/fast-facts|title=Fast Facts|publisher=Technion|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> In the book, ''Technion Nation'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technioniit.com/2012/03/hot-technion-facts-on-startups.html|title=Hot Technion FACTS on Startups, Innovation, Israel, Science & Technology|last=Johnson|first=Georgina|date=2012-03-02|website=Technion - Israel Institute of Technology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702074631/http://www.technioniit.com/2012/03/hot-technion-facts-on-startups.html|archive-date=2014-07-02|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref> Shlomo Maital, Amnon Frenkel and Ilana Debare document the contribution of Technion alumni in building the modern State of Israel.\n<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\n* [[Shai Agassi]] \u2013 IT entrepreneur, former Executive Board member of [[SAP AG]] and founder of [[Better Place (company)|Better Place]]\n* [[Saul Amarel]] \u2013 pioneer in [[Artificial intelligence]].<ref>Nagourney, Saul. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0DE6DA1F3DF932A15751C1A9649C8B63 \"Saul Amarel, 74, an Innovator In the Artificial Intelligence Field\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 21 December 2002. Accessed 24 November 2007.</ref>\n* [[Ella Amitay Sadovsky]] \u2013 artist\n* [[Ron Arad (pilot)|Ron Arad]] (b. 1958) \u2013 Air Force weapon systems officer; classified as missing in action since 1986\n* [[Itzhak Bentov]] \u2013 inventor and author\n* [[Moti Bodek]] (b. 1961) \u2013 architect \n* [[Andrei Broder]] \u2013 [[captcha]] developer, Vice President of Yahoo, formerly vice president of [[AltaVista]]\n* [[Shimshon Brokman]] (b. 1957) \u2013 Olympic sailor\n* [[Yaron Brook]] \u2013 president and executive director of the [[Ayn Rand Institute]]\n* [[Chaim Elata]] - professor emeritus of mechanical engineering, President of [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]], and Chairman of the [[Israel Public Utility Authority for Electricity]]\n* [[Yona Friedman]] (b. 1923) \u2013 architect\n* [[Yossi Gross]] \u2013 Medical devices innovator and entrepreneur; founding partner of Rainbow Medical\n* [[Andi Gutmans]] \u2013 developer of [[PHP]] and co-founder of [[Zend Technologies]]\n* [[Abraham H. Haddad]] \u2013 computer scientist\n*[[Daniel Hershkowitz]] (born 1953) - politician, mathematician, rabbi, and president of Bar-Ilan University\n* [[Maor Farid]] - researcher at [[MIT]], social activist and author\n* [[Hossam Haick]] \u2013 Scientist and engineer\n* [[Ram Karmi]] (b. 1931) \u2013 architect\n* [[Shaul Ladany]] \u2013 world-record-holding racewalker, [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] survivor, [[Munich Massacre]] survivor, Professor of Industrial Engineering \n* [[Uzi Landau]] \u2013 politician, Minister of Tourism\n* [[Daniel M. Lewin]] \u2013 co-founder and CTO of [[Akamai Technologies|Akamai]], holder of two Technion degrees, killed while resisting the hijacking of [[American Airlines Flight 11|American Airlines Flight]] in the [[September 11th attacks|11 September]] attacks on the United States.\n* [[Yoelle Maarek]] - Research VP, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]].\n* [[Yuval Ne'eman]] (1925\u20132006) - [[Physics|physicist]], politician, and President of [[Tel Aviv University]]\n*[[Eliahu Nissim]] (born 1933) - Professor of Aeronautical Engineering; President of the [[Open University of Israel]]\n* [[Neri Oxman]] \u2013 architect and designer who teaches at MIT, known for her work in [[environmental design]] and [[digital morphogenesis]]\n* [[Guillermo Sapiro]] \u2013 Contributor to [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] software including [[Photoshop]] and [[After Effects]]. Also one of the people who originally developed the [[Lossless JPEG#LOCO-I algorithm|LOCO-I Lossless Image Compression Algorithm]] which is used in [[Mars Rovers]]' [[ICER]] image file format.\n* [[Amos Shapira]], former President of [[El Al Airlines]], [[Cellcom (Israel)|Cellcom]], and the [[University of Haifa]]\n*[[Zehev Tadmor]] (born 1937) - [[chemical engineer]] and president of the Technion\n* [[Yossi Vardi]] \u2013 For over 40 years he has founded and helped build over 60 high-tech companies in a variety of fields, among them software, energy, Internet, mobile, [[electro-optics]] and water technology.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XRhXAAAAYAAJ&q=yossi+vardi+1942&dq=yossi+vardi+1942 |title=Yossi Vardi 1942 |publisher=The Economist, Volume 386, Issues 8561\u20138573 |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Arieh Warshel]] \u2013 chemist known for the development of multiscale models for complex chemical systems and the winner of the 2013 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]].\n* [[Daniel Zajfman]] (born 1959) - physicist; president of the [[Weizmann Institute]]\n*[[Shlomo Zilberstein]] \u2013 [[computer scientist]] known for his contributions to [[artificial intelligence]], as well as a professor and associate dean at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]\n* Yehuda and [[Zohar Zisapel]] \u2013 co-founders of the [[RAD Group]], \"fathers\" of Israel's hi-tech industry\n\n== Partnerships ==\nTechnion and the [[Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt]] have formed a partnership in cyber security, entrepreneurship and materials science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cysec.tu-darmstadt.de/cysec/news_and_events/newsarchiv_cysec/newsarchiv_cysec_details_117184.en.jsp|title=Cooperation with Israel Institute of Technology|last=Cybersecurity|first=Profile Area|date=2016-01-08|website=Profile Area Cybersecurity \u2013 Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intern.tu-darmstadt.de/informationsportal/nachrichten_2/news_details_de_en_135616.de.jsp|title=Neue Partnerschaft mit Technion|last=Darmstadt|first=Technische Universit\u00e4t|date=2015-11-27|website=Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt|language=de|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nTechnion recently became a partner of [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University of St. Louis]] through the McDonnell International Scholars Academy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://global.wustl.edu/mcdonnell-academy/|title=McDonnell International Scholars Academy|website=Global|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Israel Association for Automatic Control]]\n* [[Matam, Haifa]] High tech park in [[Haifa, Israel]]\n* [[List of investors in Bernard L. Madoff Securities]]\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Science and technology in Israel]]\n* [[Unit 8200]]\n* [[Unit 81]]\n* [[Talpiot program]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Technion}}\n*[http://pard.technion.ac.il/ Technion LIVE \u2013 Division of Public Affairs & Resource Development at Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology. Multimedia resource in English.]\n*[http://www.greenprophet.com/2012/09/cornell-technion-tech-hub-plans/ New renderings of Cornell-Technion Campus in New York City]\n*[https://www.technion.ac.il/ Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120515083214/http://radio1m.co.il/ Radio 1m \u2013 The students' radio station]\n*[https://www.calcalistech.com/ctech/articles/0,7340,L-3760876,00.html Technion Suing Senior Professor for 50% of His Company Stake]\n\n{{Technion |state=expanded}}\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n{{CESAER}}\n\n{{coord|32|46|39|N|35|01|18|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Technion - Israel Institute Of Technology}}\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1924]]\n[[Category:Multidisciplinary research institutes]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Israel]]\n[[Category:Technical universities and colleges in Israel]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox University\n  | name            = Technion<br />Israel Institute of Technology\n  | native_name     = {{Hebrew|\u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}}<br>{{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u062e\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646 - \u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0626\u064a\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627}}<!--Arabic names should be displayed for Israeli government agencies and institutions, as well as former government agencies and institutions-->\n| former_name     = Technikum<br/>(1912-1914)\n  | image           = Technion official seal.svg\n  | image_size      = 180px\n  | type            = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Technical university|Technical]]<br />[[research university|Research]]\n  | established     = April 11, 1912\n  | endowment       = [[US$]]1.6 billion<ref name=\"presidentsreport\">[https://presidentsreport.technion.ac.il/the-technion-in-numbers/ President's Report], 2016</ref>\n  | budget          = [[US$]]416 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.jweekly.com/2018/04/18/israels-world-class-universities-valuable-investment/ |title = Israel's world-class universities are a valuable investment|date = 18 April 2018}}</ref>\n  | staff           = \n  | faculty         = \n  | president       = [[Uri Sivan]]\n  | provost         =\n  | principal       =\n  | rector          =\n  | chancellor      =\n  | vice_chancellor =\n  | students        = 13,703 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\">[http://che.org.il/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Table-8.xlsx Table 8], annual report, [[Council for Higher Education in Israel]], 2014</ref>\n  | undergrad       = 9,251 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | postgrad        = 3,435 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | doctoral        = 1,004 (2014)<ref name=\"council2014\"/>\n  | city            = [[Haifa]]\n  | state           =\n  | country         = [[Israel]]\n  | campus          = Urban<br />{{convert|1325|dunam|acre}}\n  | colors          = Blue and Gold\n  | affiliations = [[Conference of European Schools for Advanced Engineering Education and Research|CESAER]]<br>EuroTech Universities\n  | website         = [https://www.technion.ac.il/en/home-2/ technion.ac.il]\n  | logo            = TechnionLogo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}} ''Ha-Tekhniyon \u2014 Makhon Tekhnologi le-Yisrael''; {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u062e\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646 - \u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0626\u064a\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627}}<!--Arabic names should be displayed for Israeli government agencies and institutions, as well as former government agencies and institutions-->) is a [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]. Established in 1912 during the [[Ottoman Empire]] and more than 35 years before the State of Israel, the Technion is the oldest university in the country.<ref name=\"technikum\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/862864|title=War of the Languages: Founding of the Technion/Technikum|author=Sveta Reingold|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Technion is ranked as the top university in Israel and the [[Middle East]] and the 85th in the world in the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] of 2019.<ref>http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html</ref> The university offers degrees in science and engineering, and related fields such as architecture, medicine, industrial management, and education. It has 19 academic departments, 60 research centers, and 12 affiliated teaching hospitals.<ref>http://int.technion.ac.il/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Technion-Intl-Brochure-English-2015-16.pdf</ref> Since its founding, it has awarded more than 100,000 degrees<ref>[http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/10/2014-15-welcoming-the-new-academic-year/ 2014\u201315 Welcoming the New Academic Year], Technion website</ref> and its graduates are cited for providing the skills and education behind the creation and protection of the [[State of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3RiIYgCC7Gw|title=Technion Nation - Building Israel the Start-Up Nation|last=Technion|date=11 June 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>[http://startupnationbook.com/ Start-Up Nation Book]. Start-Up Nation Book (18 January 2013). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\nTechnion's 565 faculty members currently include three [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Laureates]] in chemistry. Four [[Nobel Laureates]] have been associated with the university. The current [[List of presidents of the Technion|president of the Technion]] is [[Uri Sivan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Prof-Uri-Sivan-takes-office-as-President-of-Technion-603234|title=Prof. Uri Sivan takes office as President of Technion|publisher=|date = 29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Technion has played a major role in the history of modern Israel. The selection of [[Modern Hebrew|Hebrew]] as the language of instruction, defeating German in the [[War of the Languages]], was an important milestone in Hebrew's consolidation as Israel's official language.<ref>[http://www.jewishhistory.org.il/history.php?search=Haifa&dosearch.x=9&dosearch.y=9&dosearch=Search Jewish History]. Jewish History. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Technion is also a major factor behind the growth of Israel's [[high-tech]] industry and innovation, including the country's technical cluster in [[Silicon Wadi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnpublications.net/2011/06/30/israel-leads-in-high-tech-2/|title=Israel leads in high-tech - Reporting on the Middle East, Science, and Education|website=cnpublications.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcrunch.com/secret-israel-s-high-tech-success/3672|title=The Secret of Israel's High-tech Success (Le Monde)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{Main|History of the Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology}}\n\n[[File:Einstein technion.jpg|thumb|220px|[[Albert Einstein]] at Technion; 11 February 1923]]\n\nThe Technikum was conceived in the early 1900s by the German-Jewish fund [[Ezrah]] as a school of engineering and sciences. It was to be the only institution of higher learning in the then [[History of Palestine#Ottoman era|Ottoman Palestine]], other than the [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] in [[Jerusalem]] (founded in 1907). In October 1913, the board of trustees selected [[German language|German]] as the language of instruction, provoking a major controversy known as the [[War of the Languages]]. After opposition from American and Russian Jews to the use of German, the board of trustees reversed itself in February 1914 and selected Hebrew as the language of instruction. The German name Technikum was also replaced by the Hebrew name Technion.<ref name=\"technikum\"/><ref name=\"cie\">{{cite web|title=Technion University Selects Hebrew as Language of Instruction|url=https://israeled.org/hebrew-language/|website=Center for Israel Education|date=22 February 2018|access-date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTechnion's cornerstone was laid in 1912, and studies began 12 years later in 1924.<ref name=\"cie\"/> In 1923 [[Albert Einstein]] visited and planted the now-famous first [[Arecaceae|palm tree]], as an initiative of [[Nobel Prize|Nobel]] tradition. The first palm tree still stands today in front of the old Technion building, which is now the MadaTech museum, in the Hadar neighborhood. Einstein founded the first Technion Society, and served as its president upon his return to [[Germany]].\n\nIn 1924, [[Arthur Blok]] became the Technion's first president.<ref>https://www.technion.ac.il/en/former-presidents/</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Churchillbuilding.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Churchill Auditorium]]\n[[File:Aerospace Faculty (Technion).JPG|thumb|Aerospace Faculty (Technion)]]\n[[File:Civil and Enviornmental Engineering Faculty Technion.jpg|thumb|Civil and Environmental Engineering Faculty Technion]]\n[[File:ViewtoElectricalengg.jpg|thumb|right|220px|View towards the Electrical and Electronics Engineering Building from Obelisk]]\n[[File:Technion Computer Science Faculty.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Computer Science Faculty Building]]\n[[File:Industrial Engineering and Management at Technion by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|220px|Faculty of Industrial Engineering & Management]]\n[[File:Mathematics department.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Faculty of Mathematics]]\n[[File:Erd\u0151s\u2013Faber\u2013Lov\u00e1sz conjecture.svg|thumb|[[Erd\u0151s\u2013Faber\u2013Lov\u00e1sz conjecture]]]]\n[[File:Technion Faculty of Medicine.jpg|thumb|Technion Faculty of Medicine]]\n[[File:\u05dc\u05d1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05de\u05e4\u05d5\u05e1 \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4.jpg|thumb|Technion Faculty of Mathematics]]\n[[File:Technion-Obelisk.jpg|thumb|right|220px|The Obelisk, the stainless-steel structure 28 meters tall, is a [[kinetic art|kinetic sculpture]]]]\n\n===Haifa===\nTechnion City generally refers to the 1.2-square-kilometer site located on the pine-covered north-eastern slopes of [[Mount Carmel]]. The campus comprises 100 buildings, occupied by thousands of people every day.\n\nThe Technion has two additional campuses. Its original building in midtown Haifa, in use by the Technion until the mid-1980s, now houses the [[Israel National Museum of Science, Technology, and Space|Israel National Museum of Science, Technology and Space]]. The [[Rappaport Faculty of Medicine]] is located in the neighborhood of [[Bat Galim]], adjacent to [[Rambam Hospital]], the largest medical center in Northern Israel.\n\nRecreational activities on the main campus include an Olympic-size swimming pool as well as gymnastics, squash, and tennis facilities.<ref>[http://ciar.technion.ac.il/sport-facilities/ Sports Facilities]. Ciar.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Technion Symphony Orchestra and Choir are composed mainly of Technion students and staff. Each term, the Orchestra offers a series of daytime and evening concerts. Films and live performances by leading Israeli artists take place on campus on a regular basis.\n\n===Tel Aviv===\nTechnion's Division of Continuing Education and External Studies has been operating in the Tel Aviv area since 1958. In July 2013, the Technion moved to a new campus in [[Sarona (colony)|Sarona]]. The Technion satellite campus in Sarona includes three buildings in a 1,800 sq. meter area, with a total of 16 modern classrooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/03/technion-azrieli-sarona-campus-tel-aviv/|title=Technion-Azrieli Sarona Campus|publisher=Technion|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref> Among the programs that study at Sarona are the Technion's International MBA program, which includes students from around the world and guest lecturers from universities such as [[London Business School]], [[Columbia University]], and [[INSEAD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technionmba.com|title=MBA in Israel|publisher=Technion|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell Tech===\n{{Main|Cornell Tech}}\nOn 19 December 2011, a bid by a consortium of [[Cornell University]] and Technion won a competition to establish a new high-tier applied science and engineering institution in New York City. The competition was established by New York City Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] in order to increase entrepreneurship and job growth in the city's technology sector. The winning bid consisted of a {{convert|2100000|sqft|m2}} state-of-the-art tech campus being built on [[Roosevelt Island]], which will have its first phase completed by 2017, with a temporary off-site campus opening in 2013 at the [[Google]] New York City headquarters building at [[111 Eighth Avenue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/Dec11/NYCcover.html|title='Game-changing' tech campus goes to Cornell, Technion|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Harman|first=Danna|title=The Technion: Israel's Hard Drive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/education/edlife/inside-the-technion-israels-premier-technological-institute-and-cornells-global-partner.html|accessdate=20 April 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=14 April 2013}}</ref> The new 'School of Genius' in New York City has been named the Jacobs Technion-Cornell Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tech.cornell.edu/jacobs-technion-cornell-institute|title=Overview|work=Cornell Tech|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Its Founding Director was [[Craig Gotsman]], Technion's Hewlett-Packard Professor of Computer Engineering.\n\nMost recently, [[AOL]] has announced an investment of $5 million in a video research project at the Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2015/01/18/shirt-that-monitors-hearts-destroying-cancer-cells-new-gas-fields-its-good-news-from-israel/|title=Shirt that Monitors Hearts, Destroying Cancer Cells, New Gas Fields: It's Good News from Israel!|work=Jewish Business News|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> \nPositive media coverage abounds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2014/08/8551250/future-island|title=Future island|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> as well as some small scale protests from the margins of political and environmental activism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mondoweiss.net/2013/11/partnership-technions-militarization|title=Technion's role in U.S. militarization and domestic spying|work=Mondoweiss|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Guangdong Technion Israel Institute of Technology===\n{{Main|Guangdong Technion-Israel Institute of Technology}}\n\nIn September 2013 the [[Li Ka Shing Foundation]] and the Technion announced they would be joining forces to create a new institute for technology at [[Shantou University]], [[Guangdong|Guangdong province]], south-eastern China.\nThe Li Ka Shing Foundation pledged a grant of US$130 million for the creation of the institute. The degrees taught, including Bachelors, Masters and Doctorates, will be accredited by the Technion. The total construction costs are $147 million.\nEnglish will be GTIIT's the language of instruction. GTIIT will comprise three units: the College of Engineering; the College of Science; and the College of Life Science. The goal is to have about 5,000 students eventually. The institute will eventually grant Technion engineering degrees at all levels - Bachelor, Masters and PhD. Initially the courses offered are Chemical Engineering, Biotechnology and Food Engineering, Materials Engineering.<ref>http://www.gtiit.edu.cn/en/programs-of-study.aspx</ref> By 2020 the institute will start teaching other disciplines from Mechanics to Aerospace Engineering.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Guangdong Technion Israel Institute of Technology (GTIIT) in China is launched|url=http://pard.technion.ac.il/4198-2/|accessdate=4 November 2014|website=pard.technion.co.il|date=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shantou University|url=http://www.lksf.org/shantou-university/|accessdate=4 November 2014|website=[[Li Ka Shing Foundation]]|date=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Neuman|first=Efrat|title=The story behind a HK billionaire's $130 million donation to the Technion|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.550634|accessdate=4 November 2014|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=5 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\n\n===Aerospace Engineering===\nFounded in 1954, the [[Technion Faculty of Aerospace Engineering|Faculty of Aerospace Engineering]] conducts research and education in a wide range of aerospace disciplines. The Aerospace Research Center also consists of the Aerodynamics (wind tunnels) Laboratory, the Aerospace Structures Laboratory, the Combustion and Rocket Propulsion Laboratory, the Turbo and Jet Engine Laboratory, the Flight Control Laboratory and the Design for Manufacturing Laboratory.\n\n===Architecture and Town Planning===\n\nThe Technion Faculty of Architecture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://architecture.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05d0\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05d8\u05e7\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05d9 \u05e2\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd|website=architecture.technion.ac.il}}</ref> awards BArch degrees awarded after five years of study.<ref name=\"technionil\">{{cite web|url=http://architecture.technion.ac.il/faculty.php?pi=15 |title=Technion, Faculty of Architecture and Town Planning |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> Its graduate program in architecture accepts about 15 students each year, and it accepts about 4\u20135 doctoral students, focusing on subjects such as architectural theory and philosophy, bio-climate and energy conscious design, morphology, computer application, person-environment relations, housing, architectural history, and urban design.<ref name=\"technionil\"/>\n\n===Biology===\n\nThe Faculty of Biology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biology.technion.ac.il/|title=Biology Technion|website=biology.technion.ac.il}}</ref> was established in 1971. Advanced research is carried out in 23 research groups, focusing on a variety of aspects of cellular, molecular and developmental biology. The faculty has extensive collaborations with the pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries. The Faculty has around 350 undergraduate students and over 100 graduate students.<ref name=\"The Technion Insider 2007\">The Technion Insider: Technion prospectus from 2007.</ref>\n\n===Biomedical Engineering===\n\nEstablished in 1968, the Faculty of Biomedical Engineering<ref>http://www.bm.technion.ac.il/Pages/Information_BME_Department.aspx</ref> has a multidisciplinary scope nurturing research activities that blend medical and biological engineering. Research projects have resulted in the development of patented medical aids. Recent research breakthroughs include\nthe identification of a structured neurological code for syllables and could let paraplegics \"speak\" virtually through the connection of the brain to a computer.<ref>Siegel, Judy. (23 August 2012) [http://www.jpost.com/Health/Article.aspx?id=282255 Israeli research may help severely paralyzed speak | JPost | Israel News]. JPost. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n===Biotechnology and Food Engineering===\n\nUnique in Israel, the Faculty of Biotechnology and Food Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biotech.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05ea \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05d6\u05d5\u05df - \u05d4\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df \u2013 \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|website=biotech.technion.ac.il}}</ref> offers a blend of courses in engineering, life and natural sciences as well as joint degree programs with the Faculties of Biology and Chemistry. The Faculty houses biotechnology laboratories, as well as a large food processing pilot plant and a packaging laboratory. It currently has 350 undergraduates and more than 120 graduate students.\n\n===Civil and Environmental Engineering===\n\nIn 2002, two of the original Technion Faculties \u2013 Civil and Agricultural engineering, were merged to create the Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cee.technion.ac.il/eng/|title=Technion Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea|first=Minicy Catom Software Engineering Ltd.|last=www.catom.com|website=cee.technion.ac.il}}</ref> Its state vision is to \"maintain and enhance the leading position of the Faculty of Civil & Environmental Engineering amongst the top departments in the world... and to position the Faculty as the national center for research & development and human resources for the sustainable development.\"<ref>[http://cee.technion.ac.il/eng/ Technion Faculty of Civil and Environmental Engineering \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05ea]. Cee.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The Faculty is the home of Technion's expanding [[Technion International School of Engineering|International School of Engineering]].\n\n===Chemical Engineering===\n\nThe Wolfson Faculty of Chemical Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemeng.technion.ac.il/|title=Home Page - \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05ea - \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df|website=chemeng.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is Israel's oldest and largest faculty in the field, educating the vast majority of chemical engineers in Israel's chemical industries.<ref name=\"The Technion Insider 2007\"/> Research activities include materials, complex fluids, processing, transport and surface phenomena and process control.\n\n===Chemistry===\n\nThe Schulich Faculty of Chemistry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.technion.ac.il/|title=\u05e9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05da \u2013 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05d4|website=chemistry.technion.ac.il}}</ref> offers a variety of joint programs, including with materials engineering, chemical engineering, physics, and food engineering. It also offers a joint degree with the Faculty of Biology leading to a degree in molecular biochemistry. Around 100 research projects at the faculty are sponsored by industry and national and international foundations. It also offers a variety of outreach and youth programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.technion.ac.il/#|title=\u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05db\u05d9\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05e9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05da|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Computer Science===\n\nFounded in 1969, this is one of the largest Technion faculties, with over 1,000 undergraduate students and 200 graduate students. The Faculty of Computer Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.technion.ac.il|title=Computer Science Department, Technion|first=Yaniv |last=Hamo |website=www.cs.technion.ac.il}}</ref> was ranked 15th among 500 universities in computer sciences for 2011 and 18th of 500 since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html|title=Technion-Israel Institute of Technology - Academic Ranking of World Universities - 2016 - Shanghai Ranking - 2016|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref> The Faculty is located in the Taub Family Science and Technology Center, following the support of the philanthropist [[Henry Taub]].\n\n===Education in Technology and Science===\n\nFounded in 1965, the Department of Education in Technology & Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edu.technion.ac.il/en/|title=\u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05df (\u05d0\u05e8\u05d9) \u05d2\u05e8\u05d5 \u2013 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d7\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05da \u05dc\u05de\u05d3\u05e2 \u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4|website=edu.technion.ac.il}}</ref> became a faculty in 2015. The faculty trains undergraduates in the most advanced methods of teaching science and technology in schools. The faculty is home to a research and development center in the field. It has over 100 graduate students and 350 undergraduate students including second career engineers and scientists who elect to study toward STEM educator career.\n\n===Electrical Engineering===\n\nThe [[Technion Faculty of Electrical Engineering|Faculty of Electrical Engineering]] claims to be the major source of engineers who lead the development of advanced Israeli technology in the fields of electronics, computers and communications. Some 2000 undergraduate students study in the department for a BSc degree in electrical engineering / computer engineering / computer and software engineering, and 400 graduate students study for the degrees of MSc and PhD. The department has extensive relations with industry as well as academic and industrial special liaison support programs.<ref>[http://webee.technion.ac.il/Industrial-Relations/Mission-and-Activities Technion \u2013 Electrical Engineering: Your Portal to High-Tech]. Webee.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n===Humanities and Arts===\nThe Department of Humanities and Arts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://humanities.technion.ac.il/|title=Home Page|website=humanities.technion.ac.il}}</ref> serves all the Technion community, offering courses taught by renowned visiting and adjunct scholars including philosophy of science, social and political sciences, linguistics, psychology, law and anthropology and an array of theoretical and performing arts courses.\n\n====The Technion Theater====\n{{Main|Technion theater}}\n\nThe Technion Theater was established in 1986, by Professor [[Ouriel Zohar]]. The theater teaches 8 courses, and it has about 150 students per semester. The theater presented 52 performances in different styles, some by [[Hanoch Levin]], [[Yehoshua Sobol]], [[Moliere]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Pierre de Marivaux]], [[Henrik Ibsen]] and [[George Bernard Shaw|Bernard Shaw]], [[S\u0142awomir Mro\u017cek]] among others. The theater also presented plays written by the director and the actors. The theater is invited to many festivals in Europe universities. Director [[Scandar Copti]] received [[Ophir Award]] in 2010, played in \"End End\" directed by Zohar, which was presented in [[Jerusalem]] festival in 2001. Shlomo Plessner participated in collective plays \"soft mattress\" and \"Mix Marriage\" 1986\u20131987. The play \"Transparent Chains\" by Sheli Baliti from the Faculty of [[Chemical Engineering]] performed at [[Bratislava]] in 2006, [[Granada]], [[Haifa Cinematheque]], Neve Yosef Festival and the Theatre Department at the [[University of Haifa]] in 2007. The play [[An Enemy of the People]] by Ibsen, the main actor Rooney Navon, Professor at the Faculty of [[Civil and Environmental Engineering]], received honorable nomination at [[Benevento]] in Italy in 2009, and also in [[Isfia]] near Haifa. The Show \"invisible clothes\" written and directed by Ouriel Zohar presented at The International Theater Festival in [[Saint Petersburg State University]] in 2012.\n\n===Industrial Engineering and Management===\n\n[[The William Davidson Faculty of Industrial Engineering & Management]] (IE&M) is the oldest such department in Israel. IE&M was launched as a Technion academic Department in 1958. The Department grew under the leadership of ''Pinchas Naor'', who served as its founding Dean. Naor's vision was to combine Industrial engineering with Management by creating a large, inherently multidisciplinary unit covering a wide spectrum of activities such as applied engineering, mathematical modeling, economics, [[behavioral sciences]], [[operations research]], and statistics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.technion.ac.il/|title=Home - \u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05ea \u05ea\u05e2\u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df|website=ie.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n===Materials Science and Engineering===\n\nHome to Nobel Laureate in Chemistry Distinguished [[Dan Shechtman|Prof. Dan Shechtman]], the Faculty of Materials Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/about-materials-engineering-faculty-technion/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is Israel's major study center in materials science. The Faculty houses the Electron Microscopy Center,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/electron-microscopy-Mika-Materials-Engineering/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> the X-Ray Diffraction Laboratory,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/x-ray-lab-Materials-Engineering/-Engineering/|title=Engineering Nanostructured Thin Films for Greener Electronics \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> the Atomic force microscopy Laboratory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/AFM-atomic-force-microscopy-lab/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref> and the Physical and Mechanical Measurements lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://materials.technion.ac.il/physical-mechanical-measurments-lab/|title=Page not found \u2013 Department of Materials Science and Engineering|website=materials.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n===Mathematics===\n\nThe Faculty of Mathematics<ref>https://www.math.technion.ac.il/</ref> houses both pure and applied mathematics, and was home to the mathematician [[Paul Erd\u0151s]]. Founded in 1950, it has around 46 faculty members, 200 undergraduate students and 100 graduate students. It provides instruction for students in all other Technion faculties and organizes mathematics competition for gifted high school students and a summer camp in number theory.\n\n===Mechanical Engineering===\n\nFounded in 1948, the Technion Faculty of Mechanical Engineering<ref name=\"technion.ac.il\">{{cite web|url=http://meeng.technion.ac.il/en/|title=Energy performance analysis of a passive elastic element with a timed clutch for human load carriage - Mechanical Engineering Faculty|website=meeng.technion.ac.il}}</ref> has over 830 students and 215 graduate students. Research is conducted in the faculty's 36 laboratories across the whole spectrum of mechanical engineering, from nano-scale fields through to applied engineering of national projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL5D8815BC3AF656ED|title=Mechanical-Engineering-Technion - YouTube|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\n\nThe Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://md.technion.ac.il|title=The Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine|website=md.technion.ac.il}}</ref> is home to two [[Nobel Laureates]]: [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]]. It is one of four state-sponsored medical schools in Israel. It was founded in 1979 through the philanthropy of [[Bruce Rappaport]] and is active in basic science research and pre-clinical medical training in [[anatomy]], [[biochemistry]], [[biophysics]], [[immunology]], [[microbiology]], [[physiology]], and [[pharmacology]].<ref>[http://www.rambam.org.il/Home+Page/About+Us/News+and+Events/News+2010/Rambam+Mourns+Baruch+Rappaport+Visionary+and+Generous+Donor.htm rambam mourns baruch rappaport visionary and generous donor]. Rambam.org.il (11 January 2010). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> Other facilities on the Faculty of Medicine campus include teaching laboratories, a medical library, lecture halls, and seminar rooms. Academic programs lead to Master of Science (M.S.), Doctor of Philosophy (PhD), and Doctor of Medicine (M.D.) degrees. It also offers medical training leading to a M.D. degree to qualified American and Canadian graduates of pre-med programs under the Technion American Medical School Program (TeAMS).<ref>{{YouTube|KSIoZYsnMBk|Technion American Medical Students Program TEAMS}} (3 June 2012). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref> The school has developed collaborative research and medical education programs with various institutions in medicine and bio-medical engineering including [[Harvard University]], [[New York University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Haifa-and-NY-researchers-collaborate-on-treatment-for-two-deadly-cancers-452214|title=Haifa and NY researchers collaborate on treatment for two deadly cancers|publisher=}}</ref> [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[University of Toronto]], [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] and [[Mayo Medical School]].\n\n===Physics===\n\nThe Faculty of Physics<ref name=\"technion.ac.il1\">{{cite web|url=http://physics.technion.ac.il/eng/|title=home|website=physics.technion.ac.il}}</ref> engages in experimental and theoretical research in the fields of astrophysics, high energy physics, solid state physics and biophysics. Founded in 1960, it includes the Einstein Institute of Physics, the Lidow Physics Complex, The Rosen Solid State Building and the Werksman Physics Building.\n\n==Multidisciplinary centers==\n\n===Nanotechnology and science===\nThe [[Russell Berrie Nanotechnology Institute]] (RBNI) was established in January 2005 as a joint endeavour of the Russell Berrie Foundation, the government of Israel, and the Technion. It is one of the largest academic programs in Israel, and is among the largest nanotechnology centers in Europe and the US. RBNI has over 110 faculty members, and approximately 300 graduate students and postdoctoral fellows under its auspices at Technion. Its multidisciplinary activities span 14 different faculties.\n\n===Energy research===\nThe [[Grand Technion Energy Program|GTEP Nancy and Stephen Grand Technion Energy Program]] is a multidisciplinary center of excellence bringing together Technion's top researchers in energy science and technology from over nine different faculties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gtep.technion.ac.il/|title=Grand Technion Energy Program - Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Founded in 2007, GTEP's 4-point strategy targets research and development of alternative fuels; renewable energy sources; energy storage and conversion; and energy conservation. The GTEP is presently the only center in Israel offering graduate studies in energy science and technology.\n\n===Space research===\n\nThe [[Asher Space Research Institute|Norman and Helen Asher Space Research Institute (ASRI)]] is a specialized institute dedicated to multidisciplinary [[science|scientific]] [[research]]. Established in 1984, its members come from five Technion faculties, and it has a technical staff of Technion scientists in a variety of space-related fields: (Physics,<ref name=\"technion.ac.il1\"/> Aerospace Engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ae-www.technion.ac.il/|title=Faculty of Aerospace Engineering - Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|website=ae-www.technion.ac.il|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928041040/http://ae-www.technion.ac.il/|archivedate=28 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mechanical Engineering,<ref name=\"technion.ac.il\"/> Electrical Engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webee.technion.ac.il/|title=Technion - Electrical Engineering: Your Portal to High-Tech|website=webee.technion.ac.il}}</ref> Autonomous Systems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasp.technion.ac.il/|title=Home|first=Super|last=User|website=tasp.technion.ac.il}}</ref> and Computer Sciences).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/|title=Computer Science Department, Technion|first=Yaniv |last=Hamo |website=www.cs.technion.ac.il}}</ref>\n\n==Technology transfer==\nTechnion has an impressive record in technology transfer. Its dedicated office to bridge the transition of scientific and technological discovery to successfully commercialized innovation has been active since 2007 as [[T3 Technion Technology Transfer|T<sup>3</sup> \u2013 Technion Technology Transfer.]] As of 2011, 424 [[patents]] were granted to Technion innovations, with 845 patents pending. T<sup>3</sup>'s partners include incubators, entrepreneurs, private investors, [[Venture capital|VCs]] and [[angel groups]]. It has strategic partnerships with [[Microsoft]], [[IBM]], [[Intel]], [[Philips]], [[Johnson & Johnson]], [[Coca-Cola]], among others.\n\n==Technion international==\n\nThe Technion International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://int.technion.ac.il/|title=Technion - Technion International|website=int.technion.ac.il}}</ref> (TI) is a department in the Technion, offering courses taught entirely in English. The TI began its first year in 2009, and now offers a full BSc in Civil Engineering, BSc in Mechanical Engineering as well as various study abroad options, all taught in English. Student come from all over the globe \u2013 Asia, Africa, North and South America, Europe and Israel. They live on campus and enjoy trips around Israel and activities throughout the year.\n\n==Outreach programs==\n\nTechnion offers after-school and summer enrichment courses for young people on subjects ranging from introductory electronics and computer programming to aerospace, architecture, biology, chemistry and physics. Two examples are Scitech<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scitech.technion.ac.il/ |title=Scitech summer camp at the Technion |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> and the Math Summer Camp, devoted to number theory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.math.technion.ac.il/Noam/tomba-e.html |title=Math Summer Camp |publisher=technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nTechnion recently set up and orchestrated the Israeli chapter of [[Engineers Without Borders]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ci1henu1OQg|title=Engineering with a Soul - Technion Engineers Without Borders|last=Technion|date=27 January 2011|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> which among other projects, installed a network of biogas systems in rural [[Nepal]] providing sustainable energy and improved sanitation.<ref>[http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/studentsStory2.htm TECHNION FOCUS MAGAZINE \u2013 Students \u2013 Engineering with a Soul]. Focus.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n\n== Technion in the Israeli society ==\nThe Technion takes an active role in empowering students from unrepresented groups in the Israeli society, such as [[Haredim|ultra orthodox Jew]] and Arabs, by giving dedicated scholarships, social programs, and additional financial support. Moreover, the Technion is one of the main sponsors for the Israeli league of FIRST robotics competition which became a formal project of the Technion since 2013. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://he.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIRST|title=FIRST- Hebrew Wikipedia|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 10615 technion ecological garden.jpg|thumb|The technion ecological garden]]\n{{Infobox world university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 93 | ARWU_W_ref = <ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017]</ref>\n| THE_W = | THE_W_ref =\n| QS_W = | QS_W_ref =\n}}\nIn 2015, the Shanghai Academic Ranking rated the Technion as 77th in its list of the top 100 universities in the world.<ref name=\"ARWU\">{{cite web | url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Technion-Israel-Institute-of-Technology.html | title=3 Academic Ranking of World Universities | accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the magazine [[Business Insider]] ranked Technion among the top 25 engineering schools in the world.<ref>[http://israel21c.org/news/technion-in-top-25-engineering-schools-in-the-world/ Technion in Top 25 engineering schools in the world]. ISRAEL21c (10 July 2012). Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arwu.org/#|title=World University Rankings 2013-2014|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Center for World University Rankings ranked Technion 51st in the world and third in Israel in its CWUR World University Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwur.org/top100.html|title= Top 100 |publisher=Center for World University Rankings| year=2012 | accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor national rankings in 2011, Technion was ranked the No. 2 of universities in Israel by [[ARWU]]. In global rankings for that year, Technion was ranked #102\u2013150 by ARWU, No. 220 by [[QS World University Rankings|QS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/technion-israel-institute-technology/wur|title=Technion 2011 ranking|publisher=QS|accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was ranked #201\u2013225 by [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2011-2012/201-225.html|title=Technion 2011 ranking|newspaper=Times|accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Technion was the only school outside of the United States to make it into the top 10 on a new Bloomberg Rankings list of schools whose graduates are CEOs of top U.S. tech companies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Israel's Technion Ranks High on Bloomberg List of Schools Sending Graduates to Top Tech Companies|url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/09/02/israels-technion-ranks-high-on-bloomberg-list-of-schools-sending-graduates-to-top-tech-companies/|accessdate=10 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Algemeiner]]|date=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Research highlights==\n[[File:Rasagiline-3D-balls-A.png|thumb|Chemical structure of Rasagline]]\n\n* In 1982, [[Dan Shechtman]] discovered a [[Quasicrystal]] structure. This is a structure with a Symmetry in the order of 5 \u2013 a phenomenon considered impossible until then by the then-current prevailing theories of [[Crystallography]]. In 2011 he won the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for this discovery.\n* In 2004, two Technion professors, [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]], won the Nobel Prize for the discovery of the biological system responsible for disassembling protein in the cell.\n* Shulamit Levenberg, 37, was chosen by ''[[Scientific American]]'' magazine as one of the leading scientists in 2006 for the discovery of a method to transplant skin in a way the body does not reject.<ref>[http://www.bm.technion.ac.il/~shulamit BME Person Info | \u05d4\u05e0\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5 \u05e8\u05e4\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05df]. Bm.technion.ac.il. Retrieved on 5 October 2013.</ref>\n* [[Moussa B.H. Youdim]] developed [[Rasagiline]], a drug marketed by [[Teva Pharmaceuticals]] as [[Azilect|Azilect (TM)]] for the treatment of neurodegenerative disease, especially [[Parkinsons]].\n* In 1998, Technion successfully launched the \"Gurwin TechSat II\" microsatellite, making Technion one of five universities with a student program that designs, builds, and launches its own satellite. The satellite stayed in orbit until 2010<ref>{{cite news |author=Web Development Company |url=http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/newsStory11.htm |title=News |publisher=Technion Focus Magazine |date=10 July 1998 |accessdate=8 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929095838/http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May10/newsStory11.htm |archivedate=29 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In the 1970s, computer scientists [[Abraham Lempel]] and [[Jacob Ziv]] developed the [[Lempel-Ziv-Welch]] algorithm for data compression. In 1995 and 2007 they won an [[IEEE Richard W. Hamming Medal]] for pioneering work in data compression and especially for developing the algorithm.\n*In 2019, a team of 12 students won a gold medal at [[IGEM competition|iGEM]] for developing bee-free honey<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel21c.org/israeli-students-win-award-for-making-honey-without-bees/|title=Israeli students win award for making honey without bees|last=Blum|first=Brian|date=2019-11-17|website=Israel21c|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> \n\n== The Technion Library System ==\n{{Main|Elyachar Central Library}}\n[[File:Technion Central Library.JPG|thumb|A frontal view of Elyachar Central Library]]\n\nThe Technion library system is made of the Elyachar Central Library and research libraries that are located in the faculty buildings. The Central Library determines professional policies and guidelines and provides services for all the Technion libraries, including the library operating systems, the libraries' [[web portal]], [[library acquisitions|acquisitions]], [[cataloging]], [[library classification|classification]], and [[interlibrary loan]]s.\n\nThe faculty research libraries' aim is to focus on the information needs of their students and academic staff. The libraries are transforming from traditional academic libraries to [[learning commons]]. The transition includes an ongoing process of evaluation of the libraries' collections with the aim of identifying items in high demand and use to keep, valuable items to preserve, items in nominal use to archive in the Central Library, rare and precious items to preserve in the historical archive of the Technion, at the Central Library, and items to withdraw, according to professional criteria.\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe percentage of Arab students at the Technion equals the percentage of the general Arab population in Israel: 20%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/education/edlife/inside-the-technion-israels-premier-technological-institute-and-cornells-global-partner.html|title=Inside the Technion, Israel's premier technological institute and Cornell's global partner.|first=Danna|last=Harman|date=12 April 2013|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/2014/05/new-program-for-outstanding-arab-students-2/|title=Outstanding Arab Students|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Nobel Laureates and notable people ==\n\n===Nobel Laureates===\n\n* 2004 [[Avram Hershko]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2004 [[Aaron Ciechanover]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2011 [[Dan Shechtman]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n* 2013 [[Arieh Warshel]], Chemistry [[File:Nobel Prize.png|20px]]\n\n===Select faculty===<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\n* [[Moshe Arens]], professor of aeronautics from 1957 to 1962.\n* [[Eli Biham]], [[cryptanalyst]] and [[cryptographer]]\n* [[Yaakov Dori]], President\n* [[Avram Hershko]] and [[Aaron Ciechanover]], recipients of the 2004 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]] for the discovery of [[ubiquitin]]-mediated [[protein degradation]]\n* [[Amos Horev]], former President, former Chairman of [[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems|Rafael]]; member of the Israeli [[Turkel Commission]] of Inquiry into the [[Gaza flotilla raid]]\n* [[Abraham Lempel]] and [[Jacob Ziv]], developers of the [[Lempel-Ziv]] (LZW) compression algorithm\n* [[Liviu Librescu]], hero during the [[Virginia Tech shooting]]\n* [[Marcelle Machluf]], biotechnology and food engineering\n* [[Shlomo Moran]], computer scientist\n* [[Eliahu Nissim]] (born 1933), Professor of Aeronautical Engineering; President of the [[Open University of Israel]]\n* [[Asher Peres]], co-discoverer of [[quantum teleportation]], awarded the 2004 Rothschild Prize in Physics\n* [[Anat Rafaeli]], [[organisational behaviour]] researcher\n* [[Nathan Rosen]], co-author with [[Albert Einstein]] and [[Boris Podolsky]] of physics paper about the [[EPR paradox]] in [[quantum mechanics]]\n* [[Rachel Shalon]], first woman engineer in Israel\n* [[Shlomo Shamai]], electrical information theorist\n* [[Dan Shechtman]], first observer of [[quasicrystal]]s and winner of the 2011 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]]\n* [[Daniel Weihs]] (born 1942), [[Aeronautical Engineering]] professor \n* [[Shmuel Zaks]], computer scientist and mathematician\n* [[Mario Livio]], astrophysicist and an author of works that popularize science and mathematics\n\n===Notable alumni===<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\nTechnion graduates have been estimated to constitute over 70 percent of the founders and managers of high-tech businesses in Israel. 80 percent of Israeli NASDAQ companies were founded and/or are led by Technion graduates, and 74 percent of managers in Israel's electronic industries hold Technion degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technion.ac.il/en/fast-facts|title=Fast Facts|publisher=Technion|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> In the book, ''Technion Nation'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technioniit.com/2012/03/hot-technion-facts-on-startups.html|title=Hot Technion FACTS on Startups, Innovation, Israel, Science & Technology|last=Johnson|first=Georgina|date=2012-03-02|website=Technion - Israel Institute of Technology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702074631/http://www.technioniit.com/2012/03/hot-technion-facts-on-startups.html|archive-date=2014-07-02|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref> Shlomo Maital, Amnon Frenkel and Ilana Debare document the contribution of Technion alumni in building the modern State of Israel.\n<!-- NOTE: Please keep the following in alphabetical order by LAST name -->\n* [[Shai Agassi]] \u2013 IT entrepreneur, former Executive Board member of [[SAP AG]] and founder of [[Better Place (company)|Better Place]]\n* [[Saul Amarel]] \u2013 pioneer in [[Artificial intelligence]].<ref>Nagourney, Saul. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0DE6DA1F3DF932A15751C1A9649C8B63 \"Saul Amarel, 74, an Innovator In the Artificial Intelligence Field\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 21 December 2002. Accessed 24 November 2007.</ref>\n* [[Ella Amitay Sadovsky]] \u2013 artist\n* [[Ron Arad (pilot)|Ron Arad]] (b. 1958) \u2013 Air Force weapon systems officer; classified as missing in action since 1986\n* [[Itzhak Bentov]] \u2013 inventor and author\n* [[Moti Bodek]] (b. 1961) \u2013 architect \n* [[Andrei Broder]] \u2013 [[captcha]] developer, Vice President of Yahoo, formerly vice president of [[AltaVista]]\n* [[Shimshon Brokman]] (b. 1957) \u2013 Olympic sailor\n* [[Yaron Brook]] \u2013 president and executive director of the [[Ayn Rand Institute]]\n* [[Chaim Elata]] - professor emeritus of mechanical engineering, President of [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]], and Chairman of the [[Israel Public Utility Authority for Electricity]]\n* [[Yona Friedman]] (b. 1923) \u2013 architect\n* [[Yossi Gross]] \u2013 Medical devices innovator and entrepreneur; founding partner of Rainbow Medical\n* [[Andi Gutmans]] \u2013 developer of [[PHP]] and co-founder of [[Zend Technologies]]\n* [[Abraham H. Haddad]] \u2013 computer scientist\n*[[Daniel Hershkowitz]] (born 1953) - politician, mathematician, rabbi, and president of Bar-Ilan University\n* [[Maor Farid]] - researcher at [[MIT]], social activist and author\n* [[Hossam Haick]] \u2013 Scientist and engineer\n* [[Ram Karmi]] (b. 1931) \u2013 architect\n* [[Shaul Ladany]] \u2013 world-record-holding racewalker, [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] survivor, [[Munich Massacre]] survivor, Professor of Industrial Engineering \n* [[Uzi Landau]] \u2013 politician, Minister of Tourism\n* [[Daniel M. Lewin]] \u2013 co-founder and CTO of [[Akamai Technologies|Akamai]], holder of two Technion degrees, killed while resisting the hijacking of [[American Airlines Flight 11|American Airlines Flight]] in the [[September 11th attacks|11 September]] attacks on the United States.\n* [[Yoelle Maarek]] - Research VP, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]].\n* [[Yuval Ne'eman]] (1925\u20132006) - [[Physics|physicist]], politician, and President of [[Tel Aviv University]]\n*[[Eliahu Nissim]] (born 1933) - Professor of Aeronautical Engineering; President of the [[Open University of Israel]]\n* [[Neri Oxman]] \u2013 architect and designer who teaches at MIT, known for her work in [[environmental design]] and [[digital morphogenesis]]\n* [[Guillermo Sapiro]] \u2013 Contributor to [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] software including [[Photoshop]] and [[After Effects]]. Also one of the people who originally developed the [[Lossless JPEG#LOCO-I algorithm|LOCO-I Lossless Image Compression Algorithm]] which is used in [[Mars Rovers]]' [[ICER]] image file format.\n* [[Amos Shapira]], former President of [[El Al Airlines]], [[Cellcom (Israel)|Cellcom]], and the [[University of Haifa]]\n*[[Zehev Tadmor]] (born 1937) - [[chemical engineer]] and president of the Technion\n* [[Yossi Vardi]] \u2013 For over 40 years he has founded and helped build over 60 high-tech companies in a variety of fields, among them software, energy, Internet, mobile, [[electro-optics]] and water technology.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XRhXAAAAYAAJ&q=yossi+vardi+1942&dq=yossi+vardi+1942 |title=Yossi Vardi 1942 |publisher=The Economist, Volume 386, Issues 8561\u20138573 |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Arieh Warshel]] \u2013 chemist known for the development of multiscale models for complex chemical systems and the winner of the 2013 [[Nobel Prize in chemistry]].\n* [[Daniel Zajfman]] (born 1959) - physicist; president of the [[Weizmann Institute]]\n*[[Shlomo Zilberstein]] \u2013 [[computer scientist]] known for his contributions to [[artificial intelligence]], as well as a professor and associate dean at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]\n* Yehuda and [[Zohar Zisapel]] \u2013 co-founders of the [[RAD Group]], \"fathers\" of Israel's hi-tech industry\n\n== Partnerships ==\nTechnion and the [[Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt]] have formed a partnership in cyber security, entrepreneurship and materials science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cysec.tu-darmstadt.de/cysec/news_and_events/newsarchiv_cysec/newsarchiv_cysec_details_117184.en.jsp|title=Cooperation with Israel Institute of Technology|last=Cybersecurity|first=Profile Area|date=2016-01-08|website=Profile Area Cybersecurity \u2013 Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intern.tu-darmstadt.de/informationsportal/nachrichten_2/news_details_de_en_135616.de.jsp|title=Neue Partnerschaft mit Technion|last=Darmstadt|first=Technische Universit\u00e4t|date=2015-11-27|website=Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt|language=de|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nTechnion recently became a partner of [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University of St. Louis]] through the McDonnell International Scholars Academy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://global.wustl.edu/mcdonnell-academy/|title=McDonnell International Scholars Academy|website=Global|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Israel Association for Automatic Control]]\n* [[Matam, Haifa]] High tech park in [[Haifa, Israel]]\n* [[List of investors in Bernard L. Madoff Securities]]\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Science and technology in Israel]]\n* [[Unit 8200]]\n* [[Unit 81]]\n* [[Talpiot program]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Technion}}\n*[http://pard.technion.ac.il/ Technion LIVE \u2013 Division of Public Affairs & Resource Development at Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology. Multimedia resource in English.]\n*[http://www.greenprophet.com/2012/09/cornell-technion-tech-hub-plans/ New renderings of Cornell-Technion Campus in New York City]\n*[https://www.technion.ac.il/ Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120515083214/http://radio1m.co.il/ Radio 1m \u2013 The students' radio station]\n*[https://www.calcalistech.com/ctech/articles/0,7340,L-3760876,00.html Technion Suing Senior Professor for 50% of His Company Stake]\n\n{{Technion |state=expanded}}\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n{{CESAER}}\n\n{{coord|32|46|39|N|35|01|18|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Technion - Israel Institute Of Technology}}\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1924]]\n[[Category:Multidisciplinary research institutes]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Israel]]\n[[Category:Technical universities and colleges in Israel]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGuangdong Technion Israel Institute of Technology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technion_%E2%80%93_Israel_Institute_of_Technology"}
{"title_page": "Fiesta (dinnerware)", "text_new": "[[File:Fiesta at Macys in East Wenatchee.jpg|thumb|New Fiesta in a store]]\n[[File:Fiesta ware fundraiser.jpg|thumb|Contemporary Fiesta - 5 pieces for $45 in 2012]]\n'''Fiesta''', often called '''Fiestaware,''' is a line of [[ceramic]] [[ceramic glaze|glazed]] [[dinnerware]] manufactured and marketed by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] of [[Newell, West Virginia]]<ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{cite web\n  | title = Legacies: Collecting America's History, Fiestaware, about 1940\n  | publisher = Smithsonian Institution Press\n  | url =http://www.smithsonianlegacies.si.edu/objectdescription.cfm?ID=223}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web\n  | title = A Different Shade of Green\n  | publisher = The New York Times, Kelly Alexander, November 30, 2002\n  | url =http://www.hlchina.com/FIESTARETAILNEWYORKTIMES.htm}}</ref> since its introduction in 1936,<ref name=\"smithsonian\" /> with a hiatus from 1973 to 1985. Fiesta is noted for its [[Art Deco]] styling featuring concentric circles&mdash;and its range of solid colors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/local/north/2011/11/23/Iconic-dinnerware-that-turns-a-meal-into-a-party/stories/201111230343|title=Iconic dinnerware that turns a meal into a party|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nBoth Fiesta's original shapes and its glazes were designed by [[Frederick Hurten Rhead]], Homer Laughlin's art director.<ref name=\"jasper\">{{cite web\n  | title = History of Homer Laughlin Pottery\n  | publisher = The Collector's Encyclopedia of Homer Laughlin China, Joanne Jasper at Missingpiece.com\n  | url =http://www.missing-piece.com/HLC_HISTORY.html}}</ref> Several of the original shapes were redesigned (and other new shapes added) by Jonathan O. Parry, who became Homer Laughlin's art director in 1984.<ref name=\"jasper\" /> When the Fiesta line was re-introduced in 1986, it featured a more durable, [[Vitreous china|vitreous]] composition.  \n\nFiesta is sold in sets or from open stock, where customers can select by the piece, mixing and matching from the entire color range.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fiestafactorydirect.com/pages/dinnerware|title=Dinnerware|website=Fiesta Factory Direct|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the Smithsonian Institution Press, Fiesta's appeal lies in its colors, design, and affordability.<ref name=\"smithsonian\"/>  In 2002, ''[[The New York Times]]'' called Fiesta \"the most collected brand of china in the United States\".<ref name=\"nyt01\">{{cite web\n  | title = The Way We Live Now\n  | publisher = The New York Times\n  | author = Kelly Alexander\n  | date = December 1, 2002\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/magazine/the-way-we-live-now-12-01-02-object-of-desire-a-different-shade-of-green.html}}</ref>  Pre-1972 pieces in various colors may be slightly radioactive, due to [[uranium]] compounds being used in the [[ceramic glaze]] to achieve certain colors, especially red.<ref>''Radon, Health and Natural Hazards'', Editors: G.K. Gillmore, F.E. Perrier, R.G.M. Crockett, pp. 50-52, 2018, [[Geological Society of London]], {{ISBN|1786203081}}, 9781786203083, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oJtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 google books]</ref>\n\n==Popularity and marketing==\n[[File:Fiesta ware SP.jpg|thumb|Salt and pepper shakers showing the [[Art Deco]] design of Fiesta ware.]]\nFiesta was introduced at the annual [[Pottery and Glass Exhibit]] in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] in January 1936.<ref name=huxford>{{cite book | last=Huxford | first=Bob |author2=Sharon Huxford | title=Collector's Encyclopedia of Fiesta: Tenth Edition | location=Paducah, Kentucky | publisher=Collector's Books|  year=2005}}</ref>  It was not the first solid color [[dinnerware]] in the US; smaller companies, especially [[Bauer Pottery]] in [[California]], had been producing [[dinnerware]], vases, and garden pottery, in solid color [[ceramic glaze|glaze]]s for the better part of a decade by the time Fiesta was introduced to the [[Market (economics)|market]]. However, Fiesta was the first widely mass-promoted and marketed solid-color [[dinnerware]] in the US.\n\nWhen it was introduced, the decoration of [[dinnerware]] and [[kitchenware]] [[ceramics (art)|ceramics]] was still inspired by the [[Victorian era]], based on full, predetermined sets of dinnerware, all decorated with the same [[decal]] designs.  With its solid color glazes and mix-and-match concept, Fiesta represented something radically new to the general public. The forms and surfaces expressed an [[Art Deco]] influence. At introduction, the Fiesta line of dinnerware comprised some 37 different pieces, including such occasional pieces as candle holders in two designs, a bud vase, and an ash tray.  A set of seven nested mixing bowls ranged in size, from the smallest at five inches in diameter up to a nearly twelve-inch diameter.<ref name=huxford/>  The company sold basic table service sets for four, six and eight persons, made up of the usual dinner plate, salad plate, soup bowl, and cup and saucer.  But, the promotion and presentation of Fiesta from the start was as a line of open-stock items from which the individual purchaser could choose to combine serving and place pieces by personal preference and need.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAs an early Homer Laughlin Company brochure said:{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n<blockquote>\"COLOR!  that's the trend today ...\" and it went on to say, \"It gives the hostess the opportunity to create her own table effects ... Plates of one color, Cream Soups of another, contrasting Cups and Saucers ... it's FUN to set a table with Fiesta!\" </blockquote>\n\nThe Homer Laughlin Company quickly added several additional items to the line. During this period some items were modified, and several items were eliminated, including the covered onion soup bowl, and the mixing bowl covers. In the years up to 1940, the line was expanded by the production of more new items.  At its most numerous, the Fiesta line comprised approximately 64 different items, including flower [[vase]]s in three sizes, divided plates, water tumblers, [[Decanter|carafes]], [[teapot]]s in two sizes, five part relish trays, and large chop plates in fifteen-inch and thirteen-inch diameters.  In addition, it offered several unique promotional items for one dollar each, available only in a predetermined glaze color.\n\nWith [[World War II]] and the need for manufacturers to focus on production for that effort, non-war related production and public demand declined.  Beginning in 1942, the Fiesta line of items began to be reduced. Over the next four years, the more unusual serving pieces were being discontinued, and by 1946, the line's variety of items had been reduced by nearly one third.  Overall sales of the more typical place-setting pieces of Fiesta remained strong and reportedly peaked around 1948.  The popularity of Fiesta was due to its bright colors, durable construction, stylized [[art deco]] shapes and designs, and its promotion through mass marketing. From its first introduction in 1936 and for over a decade, Fiesta products were a widespread fad.  The dinnerware became something of a status symbol for late 1930s and pre-war 1940s middle-class households.{{cn|date=September 2019}}  Today, vintage Fiesta trades briskly on [[auction|auction websites]] and at other antique/vintage product sales venues.\n\n==1936\u20131969==\nThe line name and design is still owned by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] of [[Newell, West Virginia|Newell]], [[West Virginia]], which was the original company that produced and marketed it. Except for minor adjustments due to manufacturing requirements, the design of the original shapes remained virtually unchanged from 1936 to 1969.  As home decorating color styles changed, the company changed the solid color glazes.  The texture of the original glazes, and throughout the life of vintage Fiesta, was semi-opaque.  This is smooth and glossy, but without any shining glare, rather more like an eggshell.  The ware sometimes shows \" glaze curtains\", areas of uneven glazing where a heavy application meets a lighter one.\n\nAt its introduction in 1936, Fiesta was produced in five colors: Red (orange red), Blue (cobalt), Green (light green), Yellow (deep golden), and Old Ivory (yellowish cream). By 1938, two years into production, a sixth color was added: Turquoise ([[American robin|robin]]'s egg blue). With the exception of the Red, this color assortment remained in production until approximately 1950. The original Red had been discontinued before 1944 (see below).\n\nThe discontinuation of red, plus the general changes in society due to the United States' participation in World War II, caused a slump in sales of the larger serving pieces from the early 1940s. Prior to this reduction in the number of shapes offered, only one or two very specialized shapes had been discontinued and those by 1938. These early discontinued items, such as covered onion soup bowls in turquoise glaze and mixing bowl covers in any color, are today quite rare.\n\nBy 1950, home decorating styles and colors had changed.  The Homer Laughlin Company discontinued some original glaze colors and replaced them with four new colors.  The original Blue (cobalt), the original Green (light green), and the original Old Ivory (yellowish cream) were discontinued, replaced by Rose (dark pink), Gray (medium), Forest (dark green), and Chartreuse (bright yellowish green).  Two existing glaze colors, Yellow and Turquoise, were retained, allowing the company to offer six colors through the 1950s.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nBy the end of the 1950s, sales had again dropped.  The company reduced its offering of items and changed the glaze colors.  By 1959 the United States government had released its block on [[uranium]], which enabled the Homer Laughlin Company to produce the original bright orange-red glaze again (see below). The company discontinued the four new glazes of the previous decade in favor of a new green color and the re-introduced original bright orange-red color, which along with the yellow and turquoise colors made up the four glaze colors offered from 1959 through 1969.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAlthough the company always referred to the new color simply as Green in its brochures, collectors later called it Medium Green, to distinguish it from other green glazes which the company had produced.  The Medium Green is a bright, almost Kelly green.  Some have described it as a \"[[List of John Deere tractors|John Deere Tractor]]\" green.  Beginning in 1959, Fiesta was available in the following colors: Red (original orange red), Green (new Medium green), Yellow (original golden), and Turquoise (original robin's egg blue).{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAlthough this color assortment was available and sold for ten years (1959\u20131969), the popularity of Fiesta had fallen.  The newest shade of green is in very short supply{{according to whom?|date=September 2019}} on the secondary market relative to the other glaze colors.  It has gained almost mythical status and, for certain pieces in this glaze, commands astronomical prices wholly disproportionate to the rest of the line.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe Yellow glaze is the one glaze that was in production throughout the life of vintage Fiesta. Turquoise, while not strictly an original color (having been introduced about a year into Fiesta's production) was otherwise also in continuous production until the end of the original vintage era in 1969. Red, while an original color at the line's introduction, was removed from the market before 1944 (see below).  Although it was brought back into production from 1959 to 1969, this was after most of the unusual serving pieces had long been discontinued.  Red pieces also usually command a premium price in the secondary market, both for its vibrancy in the mix of colors and for its scarcity due to limited years of production.  While many collectors love all the colors, some only want those of the \"Original 6\" or \"Fifties Colors\".\n\n==Radioactive glazes==\n[[File:FiestaWare Velleman-K2645 GeigerCounter.ogv|thumb|right|[[Geiger counter]] (kit without housing) audibly reacting to an orange Fiestaware shard.]]\n\nBrilliant red Fiesta (and indeed the red glazes produced by all U.S. potteries of the era) is known for having a detectable amount of [[uranium oxide]] in its [[ceramic glaze|glaze]], which produced the orange-red [[color]].<ref>''Radon, Health and Natural Hazards'', Editors: G.K. Gillmore, F.E. Perrier, R.G.M. Crockett, pp. 50-52, 2018, [[Geological Society of London]], {{ISBN|1786203081}}, 9781786203083, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oJtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 google books]</ref> During [[World War II]], the government took control of [[uranium]] for [[Manhattan Project|development of the atom bomb]], and confiscated the company's stocks.<ref name=\"OakRidge\">Fiesta Ware (ca. 1930s), [http://www.orau.org/ptp/collection/consumer%20products/fiesta.htm], Oak Ridge Associated Universities 1999</ref>  Homer Laughlin discontinued Fiesta red in 1944.  The company reintroduced Fiesta red in 1959 using [[depleted uranium]] (rather than the original natural uranium), after the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] relaxed its restrictions on uranium oxide.  In addition to pottery glazing, uranium oxide was used even more extensively in the tiling industry, producing [[uranium tile]].\n\nRed is not the only color of vintage ceramic glaze that is radioactive; it is detectable from other colors, including ivory.<ref name=\"orau.org\">{{cite web|author=Oak Ridge Associated Universities| title=Fiesta Ware (ca. 1930s)|url=http://www.orau.org/ptp/collection/consumer%20products/fiesta.htm|date=January 20, 2009|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>  The level of radioactivity of vintage fiestaware has been published and is available online.<ref name=\"orau.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Vaughn Aubuchon|url=http://www.vaughns-1-pagers.com/science/geiger-counters-compare.htm|title=Geiger Counter Performance Data Compared - My Measurements|year=2006|accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n \nThe U.S. Environmental Protection Agency warns consumers not to use radioactive glazed ceramics for food or drink use.<ref>{{cite web|author=United States EPA|title=Radioactive Materials in Antiques|url=http://www.epa.gov/radtown/antiques.html|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>  Others recommend against using such pieces for food storage due to the possibility of [[Leaching (chemical science)|leaching]] of uranium or other [[Heavy metal (chemistry)|heavy metals]] (often present in some colored glazes) into food, especially acidic foods.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nOn March 16, 2011, the Homer Laughlin Company posted this statement on its website, in response to a ''[[Good Morning America]]'' broadcast about radioactivity in the home:<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/gmastatement.html \"Statement regarding the ''Good Morning America'' broadcast,\" The Homer Laughlin China Co.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401000958/http://www.hlchina.com/gmastatement.html |date=2012-04-01 }}, 16 March 2011, accessed 25 March 2012.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Included in the report was a product that has not been sold in the market for nearly 40 years, Antique/Vintage Fiesta dinnerware. The anchor narrating the segment passes a radiation measuring tool over several products including the Antique/Vintage Fiesta plate that was produced nearly 70 years ago. The narrator also stated that it was taken off the market because when people heard about the uranium in the glaze, they did not want to buy the product. In fact, The Homer Laughlin China Company stopped manufacturing all Fiestaware in 1972 because of low sales. The product that was used within the segment has been discontinued and has not available for close to 40 years time. Fiesta today is frequently tested by federally licensed independent laboratories and is lead free, microwave/dishwasher safe, oven proof and made in the USA ...\n \nPrior to World War II, it was common practice for manufacturers of ceramic dinnerware to use uranium oxide in color glazes. The Homer Laughlin China Company was no exception, using this material in the original \"Fiesta Red\" glaze, among others.\n \nIn 1943, the U.S. Government stopped all civilian use of uranium oxide because available supplies were needed for the war effort. Homer Laughlin stopped producing the red glaze color at that time and for that reason. Nonetheless, this interruption in production is believed to be the source of the rumor that Fiesta's red glaze was removed from the market because it was radioactive. In truth, the red glaze emitted far less radiation than some other consumer products. Following the lifting of wartime restrictions, Homer Laughlin again began producing the red glaze in the 1950s, using a depleted grade of uranium oxide.\n \nHomer Laughlin stopped all use of depleted uranium oxide in 1972 and it is not used in Fiesta Dinnerware which is produced today.}}\n\n==1969\u20131973==\nBy 1969 home decorating tastes had again changed.  The company restyled the shapes of Fiesta to try to modernize it.  Finials on covers, handles on cups, bowl contours and shapes, were all modified to give Fiesta a more contemporary appearance.  The glaze colors were also changed, with the choices being limited to three colors for the place-setting pieces, and one color for the five major serving pieces.  These were the remainder of the 64-piece assortment of shapes. Although essentially the same Red glaze as had then been available since 1959, it was renamed Mango Red.  Replacing  Yellow, Turquoise, and Medium Green, were two new glaze colors. One was Turf Green, which nearly matched the popular [[Avocado]] color of the day.  The second color was Antique Gold, a brownish-yellow which nearly matched the popular Harvest Gold of the era.  The line's name was changed to \"Fiesta Ironstone\".  The shape redesigns and color changes did not restore Fiesta's  popularity, and in January 1973 the company discontinued the Fiesta line.\n\n==Decaled and decorated Fiesta shapes==\nAs is common with many dinnerware shapes, the manufacturers add different decals to the shapes and give them new names.  Throughout its long life (1936\u20131973), the item shapes of Fiesta were often decorated with decals and marketed under other names, or a name variation.  One example was \"Fiesta Casuals\", which consisted of two patterns, one with yellow and brown florals and accented with solid color Fiesta yellow items, the other with turquoise and brown florals and accented with solid color Fiesta turquoise items.\n\nAs another example, in the late 1960s, the shapes of Fiesta were glazed in a dark 'bean-pot' brown, flat pieces were given an underglaze 'Mediterranean-style' geometric decal in black, and the line was marketed as \"Amberstone\" in a supermarket promotion.  Later these shapes were glazed in Antique Gold, with a different stylized pattern under the glaze.  This line was dubbed \"Casualstone\" for another supermarket promotion.\n\n==Collectors and the secondary market==\nDuring the 1970s, a new appreciation for [[Art Deco]] designs from the 1920s and 1930s flourished. Along with this, the [[baby boomers]] were establishing their own households.  They made Fiesta popular once again.  Almost immediately after Fiesta was discontinued in January 1973, collectors began buying heavily in second-hand shops and the newly popular [[garage sale]]s. Another avenue for acquiring pieces, and sometimes entire collections, was through local auctions.  Due to the enormous popularity of Fiesta in the secondary market, its prices skyrocketed.  By the end of the 1970s and into the 1980s, Fiesta items once costing pennies were commanding nearly a hundred U.S. [[dollar]]s for scarcer items.  By the mid-1980s, prices had climbed higher.  Certain pieces and colors were being traded for hundreds of dollars.\n\n==Contemporary Fiesta from 1986 ==\n[[File:Fiesta ware fiesta.jpg|thumb|A display of Fiesta]]\nThe [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] noticed the activity on the secondary market.  After a production lapse of 13 years, in 1986 the company marked the 50th anniversary of Fiesta by its reintroduction.  Prior to mass production and promotion, Laughlin used the original semi-vitreous clay body on shapes taken mostly from the last incarnation of vintage Fiesta (1969\u20131973). The company then changed the body to a fully vitrified clay, to enable marketing to the restaurant and service industry, as this clay was more durable.  Many original shapes required a redesign because of shrinkage associated with the new clay.  Although old and new runs appear similar, direct comparison demonstrates the newer pieces (made with the fully vitrified clay body) are noticeably smaller.  In addition to redesigns, new shapes were added to the line.\n\nIn 1986, Laughlin offered five colors:\n*Rose (pink) (1986\u20132005) [This color changed significantly in the post-2000 firings but was still considered the same Rose],\n*Black (black) (1986\u20132015),\n*Cobalt (dark navy blue) (1986\u2013),\n*White (bright stark white) (1986\u2013),\n*Apricot (pale pinkish tan) (1986\u20131998).\n\nThe glaze texture on this new Fiesta is very smooth, hard and much shinier than the original Fiesta.  Since its introduction, new Fiesta has remained popular.  In addition, it has increased collector interest in all the lines.  Many people are collecting vintage pieces, as well as purchasing new items from department stores and catalog retailers.  Fiesta collectors often add this new ware to existing collections of vintage Fiesta, while others concentrate on buying from the new assortment.  Early in Fiesta's second incarnation, the Homer Laughlin Company marketed it as a new [[collectible]].  The manufacturer has maintained interest in Fiesta and manipulated the  collectors' market over the past 20 years by discontinuing glaze colors, and by limiting production quantities on some items, or controlling production time frames.  Similar techniques have been used by numerous other housewares, china, silver, toy, ornament, etc. companies.<ref>Curtis, Wayne. \"[http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2004/2/2004_2_66.shtml China Town]\" ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', April/May 2004.</ref>\n\nLaughlin has produced new Fiesta in a total of 34 glaze colors, none of which matches exactly any of the thirteen colors of vintage Fiesta.  As of early 2008, many Fiesta shapes exist in a total of 39 color [[Ceramic glaze|glaze]]s.  In addition to the first five glazes, the names of the new color glazes, in order of introduction, are:\n*Yellow (pale custard/butter) (1987\u20132002),\n*Turquoise (more greenish than vintage Turquoise) (1988\u2013),\n*Periwinkle (slightly lavenderish-blue) (1989\u20132006),\n*Sea Mist (pale mint green) (1991\u20132005),\n*Lilac (soft purple) (1993\u20131995),\n*Persimmon (pinkish-orange) (1995\u20132008),\n*Sapphire (medium bright blue) (Bloomingdale's exclusive 1996\u20131997),\n*Chartreuse (brighter and greener than vintage Chartreuse) (1997\u20131999),\n*Pearl Gray (light gray) (1999\u20132001),\n*Juniper (dark bluish-green) (1999\u20132001),\n*Cinnabar (brownish-burgundy) (2000\u20132010),\n*Sunflower (bright yellow) (2001\u2013),\n*Plum (dark purple) (2002\u20132016),\n*Shamrock (bright deep green) (2002\u2013),\n*Tangerine (bright orange) (2003\u20132018),\n*Scarlet (deep true red) (2004\u2013),\n*Peacock (bright blue) (2005\u20132015),\n*Heather (dark reddish-purple) (2006\u20132009), \n*Evergreen (dark green) (2007\u20132009),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/evergreenrelease.htm Evergreen Release 2007<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Ivory (egg shell/off white) (2008\u2013),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/ivoryrelease.htm Ivory Release 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Chocolate (brown) (2008\u20132012),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/chocolaterelease.htm Chocolate Release 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Lemongrass (yellowish chartreuse) (2009\u2013),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/lemongrassrelease.htm Lemongrass Release 2009<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Paprika (dark rust) (2010\u20132017),<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/notes/homer-laughlin-china/the-new-2010-fiestar-color-ispaprika/395032000165 Paprika Release 2010<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Marigold (yellowish-orange), HLC's 75th Anniversary Fiesta color - limited 75-week run (2011\u20132012)<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/marigoldrelease.htm Marigold Release 2011<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Flamingo (light salmon pink) (2012\u20132013),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.eatnlisten.com/2012/03/28/fiesta-dinnerware-new-flamingo-color-homer-laughlin-china-dinnerware/ |title=Flamingo Release<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2012-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331053800/http://www.eatnlisten.com/2012/03/28/fiesta-dinnerware-new-flamingo-color-homer-laughlin-china-dinnerware/ |archive-date=2012-03-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Lapis (denim blue) (2013\u2013), announced March 2, 2013<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/#!/pages/Homer-Laughlin-China/68478260109?id=68478260109&sk=app_344049209045098 Lapis Release<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Poppy (bright reddish-orange) (2014\u2013), announced March 15, 2014<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Homer-Laughlin-China/68478260109?hc_location=timeline]</ref>\n*Sage (earthy green) (2015\u20132019), announced March 7, 2015<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\">[http://alwaysfestive.com/2015/03/2015-new-colors/]</ref>\n*Slate (charcoal gray) (2015\u2013), announced March 7, 2015<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Claret (red wine) (2016\u20132018), announced March 5, 2016<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Daffodil (vibrant golden yellow) (2017\u2013), announced January 10, 2017<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Mulberry (deep purple) (2018\u2013), announced January 9, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/homerlaughlinchina/photos/a.76045405109.110619.68478260109/10156462172275110/?type=3&theater|title=Fiesta Dinnerware|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref>\n*Meadow (deep mint green) (2019\u2013), announced January 8, 2019<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Butterscotch (orange yellow) (2020\u2013), announced January 12, 2020<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n\n===Special edition colors===\nSince the reintroduction of Fiesta in 1986, Homer Laughlin has introduced three colors that were available for two years: Lilac (1993\u20131995), Chartreuse (1997\u20131999) and Juniper (1999\u20132001).  Sapphire was sold exclusively at [[Bloomingdale's]] from 1996 to 1997.  In November 2008, Homer Laughlin released the limited-edition color, Chocolate.  The color of [[milk chocolate]], the new shade adds a second neutral tone to Fiesta's color palette.  It was available for a limited period of time and in a limited number of pieces.\n\nIn 1997, 500 limited-edition presentation bowls in an exclusive Raspberry (reddish maroon) colored glaze were made to commemorate the production of the 500 millionth piece of [[dinnerware]] carrying the name Fiesta produced by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] since 1936.  In anticipation of Fiesta's 75th anniversary in 2011, Homer Laughlin announced its 75th anniversary color: Marigold.  In addition, it introduced the first of a line of specially backstamped annual anniversary items, a set of three baking bowls, at the 2008 International Home and Housewares Show in [[Chicago]], Illinois.  This was followed by the introduction of a large serving platter in 2009 and a numbered soup tureen.  Dinnerware and accessories were available in 2011\u20132012, with each introduction marketed for 75 weeks, beginning April 1, before being retired.<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/marigoldrelease.htm Fiesta 75th Anniversary!<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs an indication of its influence, Fiestaware was featured in a design exhibit at the [[Cooper-Hewitt]] Museum in [[New York City]] in 1988.\n\n===Square Fiesta dinnerware===\nIn 2009, a new line of square Fiesta dinnerware was introduced.  Square is available as dinner, luncheon and salad plates, 19 oz. bowls and mugs, four-piece place settings, as well as a full line of accessories. \nDespite square silhouettes, pieces maintain a strong relationship to the company's established 'round' deco offering; coupe shape and height remain the same, along with the brand's signature concentric rings.\n\nIn October 2016, Fiesta announced the discontinuation of the square bowl (992) and the square mug (923).\n<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/squarerelease.htm Square Fiesta Dinnerware<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n''[[American Fiesta]]'', a one-man play written and performed by [[Steven Tomlinsoni]], refers to the central character's obsession with collecting vintage Fiesta dinnerware.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news\n  | title = A Nation Bound by Colorful Dinnerware\n  | publisher = The New York Times, Ginia Bellafante, April 28, 2007\n  | url = http://theater2.nytimes.com/2007/04/28/theater/reviews/28fies.html\n| date=April 28, 2007\n| accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bauer Pottery]]\n*[[Franciscan Ceramics]]\n*[[Metlox]]\n*[[Pacific Clay]]\n*[[Sencer Sari]]\n*[[Uranium glass]]\n*[[Uranium tile]]\n*[[Vernon Kilns]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Rowe, Willyum.  ''Fiestaware: a booklet.'' Rochester, NY: Press of the Visual Studies Workshop.\n\n==External links==\n<!--Do not add more links to this article unless they are truly helpful. See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.-->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070220135105/http://www.hlchina.com/ Homer Laughlin China Company], manufacturer of Fiesta\n*[http://www.hlcca.org/ Homer Laughlin China Collectors Association]\n\n{{Revivals}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fiesta (Dinnerware)}}\n[[Category:Art Deco]]\n[[Category:American pottery]]\n[[Category:Collecting]]\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:History of ceramics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1930s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Individual patterns of tableware]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fiesta at Macys in East Wenatchee.jpg|thumb|New Fiesta in a store]]\n[[File:Fiesta ware fundraiser.jpg|thumb|Vintage Fiesta - 5 pieces for $45 in 2012]]\n'''Fiesta''', often called '''Fiestaware,''' is a line of [[ceramic]] [[ceramic glaze|glazed]] [[dinnerware]] manufactured and marketed by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] of [[Newell, West Virginia]]<ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{cite web\n  | title = Legacies: Collecting America's History, Fiestaware, about 1940\n  | publisher = Smithsonian Institution Press\n  | url =http://www.smithsonianlegacies.si.edu/objectdescription.cfm?ID=223}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web\n  | title = A Different Shade of Green\n  | publisher = The New York Times, Kelly Alexander, November 30, 2002\n  | url =http://www.hlchina.com/FIESTARETAILNEWYORKTIMES.htm}}</ref> since its introduction in 1936,<ref name=\"smithsonian\" /> with a hiatus from 1973 to 1985. Fiesta is noted for its [[Art Deco]] styling featuring concentric circles&mdash;and its range of solid colors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/local/north/2011/11/23/Iconic-dinnerware-that-turns-a-meal-into-a-party/stories/201111230343|title=Iconic dinnerware that turns a meal into a party|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nBoth Fiesta's original shapes and its glazes were designed by [[Frederick Hurten Rhead]], Homer Laughlin's art director.<ref name=\"jasper\">{{cite web\n  | title = History of Homer Laughlin Pottery\n  | publisher = The Collector's Encyclopedia of Homer Laughlin China, Joanne Jasper at Missingpiece.com\n  | url =http://www.missing-piece.com/HLC_HISTORY.html}}</ref> Several of the original shapes were redesigned (and other new shapes added) by Jonathan O. Parry, who became Homer Laughlin's art director in 1984.<ref name=\"jasper\" /> When the Fiesta line was re-introduced in 1986, it featured a more durable, [[Vitreous china|vitreous]] composition.  \n\nFiesta is sold in sets or from open stock, where customers can select by the piece, mixing and matching from the entire color range.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fiestafactorydirect.com/pages/dinnerware|title=Dinnerware|website=Fiesta Factory Direct|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the Smithsonian Institution Press, Fiesta's appeal lies in its colors, design, and affordability.<ref name=\"smithsonian\"/>  In 2002, ''[[The New York Times]]'' called Fiesta \"the most collected brand of china in the United States\".<ref name=\"nyt01\">{{cite web\n  | title = The Way We Live Now\n  | publisher = The New York Times\n  | author = Kelly Alexander\n  | date = December 1, 2002\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/magazine/the-way-we-live-now-12-01-02-object-of-desire-a-different-shade-of-green.html}}</ref>  Pre-1972 pieces in various colors may be slightly radioactive, due to [[uranium]] compounds being used in the [[ceramic glaze]] to achieve certain colors, especially red.<ref>''Radon, Health and Natural Hazards'', Editors: G.K. Gillmore, F.E. Perrier, R.G.M. Crockett, pp. 50-52, 2018, [[Geological Society of London]], {{ISBN|1786203081}}, 9781786203083, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oJtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 google books]</ref>\n\n==Popularity and marketing==\n[[File:Fiesta ware SP.jpg|thumb|Salt and pepper shakers showing the [[Art Deco]] design of Fiesta ware.]]\nFiesta was introduced at the annual [[Pottery and Glass Exhibit]] in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] in January 1936.<ref name=huxford>{{cite book | last=Huxford | first=Bob |author2=Sharon Huxford | title=Collector's Encyclopedia of Fiesta: Tenth Edition | location=Paducah, Kentucky | publisher=Collector's Books|  year=2005}}</ref>  It was not the first solid color [[dinnerware]] in the US; smaller companies, especially [[Bauer Pottery]] in [[California]], had been producing [[dinnerware]], vases, and garden pottery, in solid color [[ceramic glaze|glaze]]s for the better part of a decade by the time Fiesta was introduced to the [[Market (economics)|market]]. However, Fiesta was the first widely mass-promoted and marketed solid-color [[dinnerware]] in the US.\n\nWhen it was introduced, the decoration of [[dinnerware]] and [[kitchenware]] [[ceramics (art)|ceramics]] was still inspired by the [[Victorian era]], based on full, predetermined sets of dinnerware, all decorated with the same [[decal]] designs.  With its solid color glazes and mix-and-match concept, Fiesta represented something radically new to the general public. The forms and surfaces expressed an [[Art Deco]] influence. At introduction, the Fiesta line of dinnerware comprised some 37 different pieces, including such occasional pieces as candle holders in two designs, a bud vase, and an ash tray.  A set of seven nested mixing bowls ranged in size, from the smallest at five inches in diameter up to a nearly twelve-inch diameter.<ref name=huxford/>  The company sold basic table service sets for four, six and eight persons, made up of the usual dinner plate, salad plate, soup bowl, and cup and saucer.  But, the promotion and presentation of Fiesta from the start was as a line of open-stock items from which the individual purchaser could choose to combine serving and place pieces by personal preference and need.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAs an early Homer Laughlin Company brochure said:{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n<blockquote>\"COLOR!  that's the trend today ...\" and it went on to say, \"It gives the hostess the opportunity to create her own table effects ... Plates of one color, Cream Soups of another, contrasting Cups and Saucers ... it's FUN to set a table with Fiesta!\" </blockquote>\n\nThe Homer Laughlin Company quickly added several additional items to the line. During this period some items were modified, and several items were eliminated, including the covered onion soup bowl, and the mixing bowl covers. In the years up to 1940, the line was expanded by the production of more new items.  At its most numerous, the Fiesta line comprised approximately 64 different items, including flower [[vase]]s in three sizes, divided plates, water tumblers, [[Decanter|carafes]], [[teapot]]s in two sizes, five part relish trays, and large chop plates in fifteen-inch and thirteen-inch diameters.  In addition, it offered several unique promotional items for one dollar each, available only in a predetermined glaze color.\n\nWith [[World War II]] and the need for manufacturers to focus on production for that effort, non-war related production and public demand declined.  Beginning in 1942, the Fiesta line of items began to be reduced. Over the next four years, the more unusual serving pieces were being discontinued, and by 1946, the line's variety of items had been reduced by nearly one third.  Overall sales of the more typical place-setting pieces of Fiesta remained strong and reportedly peaked around 1948.  The popularity of Fiesta was due to its bright colors, durable construction, stylized [[art deco]] shapes and designs, and its promotion through mass marketing. From its first introduction in 1936 and for over a decade, Fiesta products were a widespread fad.  The dinnerware became something of a status symbol for late 1930s and pre-war 1940s middle-class households.{{cn|date=September 2019}}  Today, vintage Fiesta trades briskly on [[auction|auction websites]] and at other antique/vintage product sales venues.\n\n==1936\u20131969==\nThe line name and design is still owned by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] of [[Newell, West Virginia|Newell]], [[West Virginia]], which was the original company that produced and marketed it. Except for minor adjustments due to manufacturing requirements, the design of the original shapes remained virtually unchanged from 1936 to 1969.  As home decorating color styles changed, the company changed the solid color glazes.  The texture of the original glazes, and throughout the life of vintage Fiesta, was semi-opaque.  This is smooth and glossy, but without any shining glare, rather more like an eggshell.  The ware sometimes shows \" glaze curtains\", areas of uneven glazing where a heavy application meets a lighter one.\n\nAt its introduction in 1936, Fiesta was produced in five colors: Red (orange red), Blue (cobalt), Green (light green), Yellow (deep golden), and Old Ivory (yellowish cream). By 1938, two years into production, a sixth color was added: Turquoise ([[American robin|robin]]'s egg blue). With the exception of the Red, this color assortment remained in production until approximately 1950. The original Red had been discontinued before 1944 (see below).\n\nThe discontinuation of red, plus the general changes in society due to the United States' participation in World War II, caused a slump in sales of the larger serving pieces from the early 1940s. Prior to this reduction in the number of shapes offered, only one or two very specialized shapes had been discontinued and those by 1938. These early discontinued items, such as covered onion soup bowls in turquoise glaze and mixing bowl covers in any color, are today quite rare.\n\nBy 1950, home decorating styles and colors had changed.  The Homer Laughlin Company discontinued some original glaze colors and replaced them with four new colors.  The original Blue (cobalt), the original Green (light green), and the original Old Ivory (yellowish cream) were discontinued, replaced by Rose (dark pink), Gray (medium), Forest (dark green), and Chartreuse (bright yellowish green).  Two existing glaze colors, Yellow and Turquoise, were retained, allowing the company to offer six colors through the 1950s.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nBy the end of the 1950s, sales had again dropped.  The company reduced its offering of items and changed the glaze colors.  By 1959 the United States government had released its block on [[uranium]], which enabled the Homer Laughlin Company to produce the original bright orange-red glaze again (see below). The company discontinued the four new glazes of the previous decade in favor of a new green color and the re-introduced original bright orange-red color, which along with the yellow and turquoise colors made up the four glaze colors offered from 1959 through 1969.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAlthough the company always referred to the new color simply as Green in its brochures, collectors later called it Medium Green, to distinguish it from other green glazes which the company had produced.  The Medium Green is a bright, almost Kelly green.  Some have described it as a \"[[List of John Deere tractors|John Deere Tractor]]\" green.  Beginning in 1959, Fiesta was available in the following colors: Red (original orange red), Green (new Medium green), Yellow (original golden), and Turquoise (original robin's egg blue).{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nAlthough this color assortment was available and sold for ten years (1959\u20131969), the popularity of Fiesta had fallen.  The newest shade of green is in very short supply{{according to whom?|date=September 2019}} on the secondary market relative to the other glaze colors.  It has gained almost mythical status and, for certain pieces in this glaze, commands astronomical prices wholly disproportionate to the rest of the line.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe Yellow glaze is the one glaze that was in production throughout the life of vintage Fiesta. Turquoise, while not strictly an original color (having been introduced about a year into Fiesta's production) was otherwise also in continuous production until the end of the original vintage era in 1969. Red, while an original color at the line's introduction, was removed from the market before 1944 (see below).  Although it was brought back into production from 1959 to 1969, this was after most of the unusual serving pieces had long been discontinued.  Red pieces also usually command a premium price in the secondary market, both for its vibrancy in the mix of colors and for its scarcity due to limited years of production.  While many collectors love all the colors, some only want those of the \"Original 6\" or \"Fifties Colors\".\n\n==Radioactive glazes==\n[[File:FiestaWare Velleman-K2645 GeigerCounter.ogv|thumb|right|[[Geiger counter]] (kit without housing) audibly reacting to an orange Fiestaware shard.]]\n\nBrilliant red Fiesta (and indeed the red glazes produced by all U.S. potteries of the era) is known for having a detectable amount of [[uranium oxide]] in its [[ceramic glaze|glaze]], which produced the orange-red [[color]].<ref>''Radon, Health and Natural Hazards'', Editors: G.K. Gillmore, F.E. Perrier, R.G.M. Crockett, pp. 50-52, 2018, [[Geological Society of London]], {{ISBN|1786203081}}, 9781786203083, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oJtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 google books]</ref> During [[World War II]], the government took control of [[uranium]] for [[Manhattan Project|development of the atom bomb]], and confiscated the company's stocks.<ref name=\"OakRidge\">Fiesta Ware (ca. 1930s), [http://www.orau.org/ptp/collection/consumer%20products/fiesta.htm], Oak Ridge Associated Universities 1999</ref>  Homer Laughlin discontinued Fiesta red in 1944.  The company reintroduced Fiesta red in 1959 using [[depleted uranium]] (rather than the original natural uranium), after the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] relaxed its restrictions on uranium oxide.  In addition to pottery glazing, uranium oxide was used even more extensively in the tiling industry, producing [[uranium tile]].\n\nRed is not the only color of vintage ceramic glaze that is radioactive; it is detectable from other colors, including ivory.<ref name=\"orau.org\">{{cite web|author=Oak Ridge Associated Universities| title=Fiesta Ware (ca. 1930s)|url=http://www.orau.org/ptp/collection/consumer%20products/fiesta.htm|date=January 20, 2009|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>  The level of radioactivity of vintage fiestaware has been published and is available online.<ref name=\"orau.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Vaughn Aubuchon|url=http://www.vaughns-1-pagers.com/science/geiger-counters-compare.htm|title=Geiger Counter Performance Data Compared - My Measurements|year=2006|accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n \nThe U.S. Environmental Protection Agency warns consumers not to use radioactive glazed ceramics for food or drink use.<ref>{{cite web|author=United States EPA|title=Radioactive Materials in Antiques|url=http://www.epa.gov/radtown/antiques.html|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>  Others recommend against using such pieces for food storage due to the possibility of [[Leaching (chemical science)|leaching]] of uranium or other [[Heavy metal (chemistry)|heavy metals]] (often present in some colored glazes) into food, especially acidic foods.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nOn March 16, 2011, the Homer Laughlin Company posted this statement on its website, in response to a ''[[Good Morning America]]'' broadcast about radioactivity in the home:<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/gmastatement.html \"Statement regarding the ''Good Morning America'' broadcast,\" The Homer Laughlin China Co.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401000958/http://www.hlchina.com/gmastatement.html |date=2012-04-01 }}, 16 March 2011, accessed 25 March 2012.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Included in the report was a product that has not been sold in the market for nearly 40 years, Antique/Vintage Fiesta dinnerware. The anchor narrating the segment passes a radiation measuring tool over several products including the Antique/Vintage Fiesta plate that was produced nearly 70 years ago. The narrator also stated that it was taken off the market because when people heard about the uranium in the glaze, they did not want to buy the product. In fact, The Homer Laughlin China Company stopped manufacturing all Fiestaware in 1972 because of low sales. The product that was used within the segment has been discontinued and has not available for close to 40 years time. Fiesta today is frequently tested by federally licensed independent laboratories and is lead free, microwave/dishwasher safe, oven proof and made in the USA ...\n \nPrior to World War II, it was common practice for manufacturers of ceramic dinnerware to use uranium oxide in color glazes. The Homer Laughlin China Company was no exception, using this material in the original \"Fiesta Red\" glaze, among others.\n \nIn 1943, the U.S. Government stopped all civilian use of uranium oxide because available supplies were needed for the war effort. Homer Laughlin stopped producing the red glaze color at that time and for that reason. Nonetheless, this interruption in production is believed to be the source of the rumor that Fiesta's red glaze was removed from the market because it was radioactive. In truth, the red glaze emitted far less radiation than some other consumer products. Following the lifting of wartime restrictions, Homer Laughlin again began producing the red glaze in the 1950s, using a depleted grade of uranium oxide.\n \nHomer Laughlin stopped all use of depleted uranium oxide in 1972 and it is not used in Fiesta Dinnerware which is produced today.}}\n\n==1969\u20131973==\nBy 1969 home decorating tastes had again changed.  The company restyled the shapes of Fiesta to try to modernize it.  Finials on covers, handles on cups, bowl contours and shapes, were all modified to give Fiesta a more contemporary appearance.  The glaze colors were also changed, with the choices being limited to three colors for the place-setting pieces, and one color for the five major serving pieces.  These were the remainder of the 64-piece assortment of shapes. Although essentially the same Red glaze as had then been available since 1959, it was renamed Mango Red.  Replacing  Yellow, Turquoise, and Medium Green, were two new glaze colors. One was Turf Green, which nearly matched the popular [[Avocado]] color of the day.  The second color was Antique Gold, a brownish-yellow which nearly matched the popular Harvest Gold of the era.  The line's name was changed to \"Fiesta Ironstone\".  The shape redesigns and color changes did not restore Fiesta's  popularity, and in January 1973 the company discontinued the Fiesta line.\n\n==Decaled and decorated Fiesta shapes==\nAs is common with many dinnerware shapes, the manufacturers add different decals to the shapes and give them new names.  Throughout its long life (1936\u20131973), the item shapes of Fiesta were often decorated with decals and marketed under other names, or a name variation.  One example was \"Fiesta Casuals\", which consisted of two patterns, one with yellow and brown florals and accented with solid color Fiesta yellow items, the other with turquoise and brown florals and accented with solid color Fiesta turquoise items.\n\nAs another example, in the late 1960s, the shapes of Fiesta were glazed in a dark 'bean-pot' brown, flat pieces were given an underglaze 'Mediterranean-style' geometric decal in black, and the line was marketed as \"Amberstone\" in a supermarket promotion.  Later these shapes were glazed in Antique Gold, with a different stylized pattern under the glaze.  This line was dubbed \"Casualstone\" for another supermarket promotion.\n\n==Collectors and the secondary market==\nDuring the 1970s, a new appreciation for [[Art Deco]] designs from the 1920s and 1930s flourished. Along with this, the [[baby boomers]] were establishing their own households.  They made Fiesta popular once again.  Almost immediately after Fiesta was discontinued in January 1973, collectors began buying heavily in second-hand shops and the newly popular [[garage sale]]s. Another avenue for acquiring pieces, and sometimes entire collections, was through local auctions.  Due to the enormous popularity of Fiesta in the secondary market, its prices skyrocketed.  By the end of the 1970s and into the 1980s, Fiesta items once costing pennies were commanding nearly a hundred U.S. [[dollar]]s for scarcer items.  By the mid-1980s, prices had climbed higher.  Certain pieces and colors were being traded for hundreds of dollars.\n\n==Contemporary Fiesta from 1986 ==\n[[File:Fiesta ware fiesta.jpg|thumb|A display of Fiesta]]\nThe [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] noticed the activity on the secondary market.  After a production lapse of 13 years, in 1986 the company marked the 50th anniversary of Fiesta by its reintroduction.  Prior to mass production and promotion, Laughlin used the original semi-vitreous clay body on shapes taken mostly from the last incarnation of vintage Fiesta (1969\u20131973). The company then changed the body to a fully vitrified clay, to enable marketing to the restaurant and service industry, as this clay was more durable.  Many original shapes required a redesign because of shrinkage associated with the new clay.  Although old and new runs appear similar, direct comparison demonstrates the newer pieces (made with the fully vitrified clay body) are noticeably smaller.  In addition to redesigns, new shapes were added to the line.\n\nIn 1986, Laughlin offered five colors:\n*Rose (pink) (1986\u20132005) [This color changed significantly in the post-2000 firings but was still considered the same Rose],\n*Black (black) (1986\u20132015),\n*Cobalt (dark navy blue) (1986\u2013),\n*White (bright stark white) (1986\u2013),\n*Apricot (pale pinkish tan) (1986\u20131998).\n\nThe glaze texture on this new Fiesta is very smooth, hard and much shinier than the original Fiesta.  Since its introduction, new Fiesta has remained popular.  In addition, it has increased collector interest in all the lines.  Many people are collecting vintage pieces, as well as purchasing new items from department stores and catalog retailers.  Fiesta collectors often add this new ware to existing collections of vintage Fiesta, while others concentrate on buying from the new assortment.  Early in Fiesta's second incarnation, the Homer Laughlin Company marketed it as a new [[collectible]].  The manufacturer has maintained interest in Fiesta and manipulated the  collectors' market over the past 20 years by discontinuing glaze colors, and by limiting production quantities on some items, or controlling production time frames.  Similar techniques have been used by numerous other housewares, china, silver, toy, ornament, etc. companies.<ref>Curtis, Wayne. \"[http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/2004/2/2004_2_66.shtml China Town]\" ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', April/May 2004.</ref>\n\nLaughlin has produced new Fiesta in a total of 34 glaze colors, none of which matches exactly any of the thirteen colors of vintage Fiesta.  As of early 2008, many Fiesta shapes exist in a total of 39 color [[Ceramic glaze|glaze]]s.  In addition to the first five glazes, the names of the new color glazes, in order of introduction, are:\n*Yellow (pale custard/butter) (1987\u20132002),\n*Turquoise (more greenish than vintage Turquoise) (1988\u2013),\n*Periwinkle (slightly lavenderish-blue) (1989\u20132006),\n*Sea Mist (pale mint green) (1991\u20132005),\n*Lilac (soft purple) (1993\u20131995),\n*Persimmon (pinkish-orange) (1995\u20132008),\n*Sapphire (medium bright blue) (Bloomingdale's exclusive 1996\u20131997),\n*Chartreuse (brighter and greener than vintage Chartreuse) (1997\u20131999),\n*Pearl Gray (light gray) (1999\u20132001),\n*Juniper (dark bluish-green) (1999\u20132001),\n*Cinnabar (brownish-burgundy) (2000\u20132010),\n*Sunflower (bright yellow) (2001\u2013),\n*Plum (dark purple) (2002\u20132016),\n*Shamrock (bright deep green) (2002\u2013),\n*Tangerine (bright orange) (2003\u20132018),\n*Scarlet (deep true red) (2004\u2013),\n*Peacock (bright blue) (2005\u20132015),\n*Heather (dark reddish-purple) (2006\u20132009), \n*Evergreen (dark green) (2007\u20132009),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/evergreenrelease.htm Evergreen Release 2007<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Ivory (egg shell/off white) (2008\u2013),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/ivoryrelease.htm Ivory Release 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Chocolate (brown) (2008\u20132012),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/chocolaterelease.htm Chocolate Release 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Lemongrass (yellowish chartreuse) (2009\u2013),<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/lemongrassrelease.htm Lemongrass Release 2009<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Paprika (dark rust) (2010\u20132017),<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/notes/homer-laughlin-china/the-new-2010-fiestar-color-ispaprika/395032000165 Paprika Release 2010<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Marigold (yellowish-orange), HLC's 75th Anniversary Fiesta color - limited 75-week run (2011\u20132012)<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/marigoldrelease.htm Marigold Release 2011<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Flamingo (light salmon pink) (2012\u20132013),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.eatnlisten.com/2012/03/28/fiesta-dinnerware-new-flamingo-color-homer-laughlin-china-dinnerware/ |title=Flamingo Release<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2012-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331053800/http://www.eatnlisten.com/2012/03/28/fiesta-dinnerware-new-flamingo-color-homer-laughlin-china-dinnerware/ |archive-date=2012-03-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Lapis (denim blue) (2013\u2013), announced March 2, 2013<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/#!/pages/Homer-Laughlin-China/68478260109?id=68478260109&sk=app_344049209045098 Lapis Release<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Poppy (bright reddish-orange) (2014\u2013), announced March 15, 2014<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Homer-Laughlin-China/68478260109?hc_location=timeline]</ref>\n*Sage (earthy green) (2015\u20132019), announced March 7, 2015<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\">[http://alwaysfestive.com/2015/03/2015-new-colors/]</ref>\n*Slate (charcoal gray) (2015\u2013), announced March 7, 2015<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Claret (red wine) (2016\u20132018), announced March 5, 2016<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Daffodil (vibrant golden yellow) (2017\u2013), announced January 10, 2017<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Mulberry (deep purple) (2018\u2013), announced January 9, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/homerlaughlinchina/photos/a.76045405109.110619.68478260109/10156462172275110/?type=3&theater|title=Fiesta Dinnerware|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref>\n*Meadow (deep mint green) (2019\u2013), announced January 8, 2019<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n*Butterscotch (orange yellow) (2020\u2013), announced January 12, 2020<ref name=\"alwaysfestive.com\"/>\n\n===Special edition colors===\nSince the reintroduction of Fiesta in 1986, Homer Laughlin has introduced three colors that were available for two years: Lilac (1993\u20131995), Chartreuse (1997\u20131999) and Juniper (1999\u20132001).  Sapphire was sold exclusively at [[Bloomingdale's]] from 1996 to 1997.  In November 2008, Homer Laughlin released the limited-edition color, Chocolate.  The color of [[milk chocolate]], the new shade adds a second neutral tone to Fiesta's color palette.  It was available for a limited period of time and in a limited number of pieces.\n\nIn 1997, 500 limited-edition presentation bowls in an exclusive Raspberry (reddish maroon) colored glaze were made to commemorate the production of the 500 millionth piece of [[dinnerware]] carrying the name Fiesta produced by the [[Homer Laughlin China Company]] since 1936.  In anticipation of Fiesta's 75th anniversary in 2011, Homer Laughlin announced its 75th anniversary color: Marigold.  In addition, it introduced the first of a line of specially backstamped annual anniversary items, a set of three baking bowls, at the 2008 International Home and Housewares Show in [[Chicago]], Illinois.  This was followed by the introduction of a large serving platter in 2009 and a numbered soup tureen.  Dinnerware and accessories were available in 2011\u20132012, with each introduction marketed for 75 weeks, beginning April 1, before being retired.<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/marigoldrelease.htm Fiesta 75th Anniversary!<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs an indication of its influence, Fiestaware was featured in a design exhibit at the [[Cooper-Hewitt]] Museum in [[New York City]] in 1988.\n\n===Square Fiesta dinnerware===\nIn 2009, a new line of square Fiesta dinnerware was introduced.  Square is available as dinner, luncheon and salad plates, 19 oz. bowls and mugs, four-piece place settings, as well as a full line of accessories. \nDespite square silhouettes, pieces maintain a strong relationship to the company's established 'round' deco offering; coupe shape and height remain the same, along with the brand's signature concentric rings.\n\nIn October 2016, Fiesta announced the discontinuation of the square bowl (992) and the square mug (923).\n<ref>[http://www.hlchina.com/squarerelease.htm Square Fiesta Dinnerware<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n''[[American Fiesta]]'', a one-man play written and performed by [[Steven Tomlinsoni]], refers to the central character's obsession with collecting vintage Fiesta dinnerware.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news\n  | title = A Nation Bound by Colorful Dinnerware\n  | publisher = The New York Times, Ginia Bellafante, April 28, 2007\n  | url = http://theater2.nytimes.com/2007/04/28/theater/reviews/28fies.html\n| date=April 28, 2007\n| accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bauer Pottery]]\n*[[Franciscan Ceramics]]\n*[[Metlox]]\n*[[Pacific Clay]]\n*[[Sencer Sari]]\n*[[Uranium glass]]\n*[[Uranium tile]]\n*[[Vernon Kilns]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Rowe, Willyum.  ''Fiestaware: a booklet.'' Rochester, NY: Press of the Visual Studies Workshop.\n\n==External links==\n<!--Do not add more links to this article unless they are truly helpful. See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.-->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070220135105/http://www.hlchina.com/ Homer Laughlin China Company], manufacturer of Fiesta\n*[http://www.hlcca.org/ Homer Laughlin China Collectors Association]\n\n{{Revivals}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fiesta (Dinnerware)}}\n[[Category:Art Deco]]\n[[Category:American pottery]]\n[[Category:Collecting]]\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:History of ceramics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1930s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Individual patterns of tableware]]\n", "name_user": "JackME", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiesta_(dinnerware)"}
{"title_page": "The Interview", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film directed by Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg}}\n{{about|the 2014 film||Interview (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Interview\n| image          = The Interview 2014 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster{{efn|The [[Korean language|Korean]] text translates as: \"The war will begin\" (on the missiles and tanks). The Korean text line right beneath the stars' names above the movie title translates to: \"Please do not believe these ignorant dishonorable Americans!\" while the small text to the left and right of the title, meanwhile, translates to the film's title. The fine print at the bottom of the poster reiterates the opening tagline from the top of the poster, translating to: \"Awful work by the 'pigs' that created ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' and ''[[This Is the End]]''{{-\"}}.<ref>Vary, Adam B. (June 11, 2014). [https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill#.nq6r90dzZ3 \"The Poster For Seth Rogen and James Franco's New Comedy Is Filled with Anti-American Propaganda\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328132022/http://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill |date=March 28, 2016 }}. [[BuzzFeed]]. Retrieved December 21, 2014.</ref>}}\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Evan Goldberg]]\n}}\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* James Weaver\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Dan Sterling]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* Dan Sterling\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Franco]]\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Randall Park]]\n<!--per billing block-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Henry Jackman]]\n| cinematography = [[Brandon Trost]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Zene Baker]]\n* Evan Henke\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Point Grey Pictures]]\n* [[LStar Capital]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]{{efn|All references to [[Sony Pictures]] were removed from the final film and marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |title=Hack Attack: Sony Orders Its Name Removed from \u2018Interview\u2019 Marketing Materials |url=https://www.thewrap.com/hack-attack-sony-orders-its-name-removed-from-interview-marketing-materials/ |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|12|11|Los Angeles|2014|12|24|United States<!--- This is for the on demand date, and the film was only released on December 24. Please go to the talk page before changing this --->}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 111:49 --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | title=''The Interview'' (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129045957/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | archivedate=November 29, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Korean\n}}\n| budget         = $44 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|title=Sony Weighing Premium VOD Release for 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 17, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=January 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116144807/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|title=Sony Could Lose $75 Million on 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 18, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220194759/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = $12.3 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | title = The Interview (2014) \u2013 Financial Information | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = May 1, 2019  | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180422062312/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | archivedate = April 22, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Interview''''' is a 2014 American [[action comedy film]] co-produced and directed by [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] in their second directorial work, following ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013). The screenplay was written by [[Dan Sterling]], based on a story he co-wrote with Rogen and Goldberg. The film stars Rogen and [[James Franco]] as journalists who set up an interview with [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ([[Randall Park]]), and are then recruited by the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] to assassinate him. The film is heavily inspired by a 2012 ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' documentary.\n\nRogen and Goldberg developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, with [[Kim Jong-il]] as the original assassination target. In 2011, after [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Jong-il's death]] and Jong-un's succession as the [[List of heads of state of North Korea|North Korean leader]], Rogen and Goldberg redeveloped the script with the focus on Jong-un's character. ''The Interview'' was first announced in March 2013, at the beginning of pre-production. [[Principal photography]] was in [[Vancouver]] from October to December 2013. The film was produced by [[Columbia Pictures]], [[LStar Capital]] and Rogen and Goldberg's [[Point Grey Pictures]], and distributed by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]].\n\nIn June 2014, the North Korean government threatened action against the United States if Sony released the film. As a result, Sony delayed the release from October to December and reportedly re-edited the film to make it more acceptable to North Korea. In November, the computer systems of Sony were [[Sony Pictures hack|hacked]] by the \"Guardians of Peace\", a group the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] claimed has ties to North Korea.<ref>[[Gabi Siboni]] and David Siman-Tov, [http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf Cyberspace Extortion: North Korea versus the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820031432/http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf |date=August 20, 2016 }}, [[Institute for National Security Studies (Israel)|INSS]] Insight No. 646, December 23, 2014.</ref> The group also threatened terrorist attacks against theaters showing the film. As a result, major theater chains opted not to release the film, and Sony instead released it for online digital rental and purchase on December 24, 2014, followed by a [[limited release]] at selected theaters the next day.\n\nIn December 2014, [[South Korea|South Korean]] singer [[Yoon Mi-rae]] revealed that the film used her song \"Pay Day\" without permission, and that she was taking legal action.<ref name=\"newsmp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.soompi.com/2014/12/26/yoon-mi-rae-to-take-legal-action-against-sony-pictures-for-using-her-song-in-the-interview-without-permission/|title=Yoon Mi Rae to Take Legal Action against Sony Pictures for Using Her Song in \"The Interview\" without Permission|date=27 December 2014|work=Soompi|author=|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> Yoon Mi-rae and her label [[Feel Ghood Music]] reached a settlement with Sony Pictures Entertainment on the 13th of May 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/201343/20150517/sony-the-interview-yoon-mi-rae-payday.htm|title=Sony And Yoon Mi Rae Reach Settlement Over Unlicensed Song Usage In 'The Interview'|website=KpopStarz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> \n\n''The Interview'' grossed $40 million in digital rentals, making it Sony's most successful digital release and earned an additional $12.3 million worldwide in box office ticket sales on a $44 million budget. It received mixed reviews for its humor and subject matter, although a few critics praised the performances of Rogen, Franco, Park and [[Diana Bang]].\n\n==Plot==\nDave Skylark is the host of the [[talk show]] ''Skylark Tonight'', where he interviews various celebrities about personal topics and gossip. After Skylark and his crew celebrate their producer Aaron Rapaport's 1,000th episode, Rapaport is upset by a producer peer who criticized the show as not being a real news program. Rapaport reveals his concern and urge for change, to which Skylark agrees. Later, Skylark discovers that [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] is a fan of ''Skylark Tonight'', prompting Rapaport to arrange an interview for him. Rapaport travels to a place outside [[Dandong]], [[China]] to receive instructions from Sook-yin Park, a [[Propaganda in North Korea|propaganda minister]], and Rapaport accepts the task of interviewing Kim on behalf of Skylark.\n\nThe next day, [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent Lacey shows up at Skylark and Rapaport's place, proposing that the duo assassinate Kim using a [[transdermal patch|transdermal strip]] that will poison Kim with [[ricin]] via handshake; they reluctantly agree. Skylark carries the ricin strip hidden inside a pack of gum. Upon their arrival in the [[Residences of North Korean leaders|presidential palace]] in [[Pyongyang]], they are introduced to security officers Koh and Yu; Koh discovers the strip and chews it, believing it to be gum. That night, Lacey airdrops them two more patches from a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]], but in order to smuggle it back to their room, Rapaport has to evade a [[Siberian tiger]] and then hide the container in his rectum. Later, Kim shows up and introduces himself to Skylark.\n\nSkylark spends the day with Kim by playing [[basketball]], hanging out and partying together. Kim persuades Skylark that he is misunderstood as both a cruel dictator and a failed administrator, and they become friends. At dinner, Koh has a [[Epileptic seizure|seizure]] due to the ricin poisoning and accidentally shoots Yu before dying. The next morning, Skylark feels guilty and discards one of the ricin strip, then thwarts Rapaport's attempt to poison Kim with the second strip. After another dinner mourning the death of Kim's bodyguards, Skylark witnesses Kim's malicious side as he [[Korean conflict|threatens war]] against [[South Korea]] and everyone who try to undermine his leadership. Skylark leaves and after taking a walk, he discovers that a nearby grocery store is merely [[Potemkin village|fake]] and realizes that Kim has been lying to him. At the same time, during an attempted sex with Rapaport (who still has the ricin strip in his hand), Sook-yin reveals that she despises Kim and apologizes for defending the regime. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin plan to break [[North Korean cult of personality|Kim's cult of personality]] by causing him to cry on air. Before the broadcast starts, Kim gives Skylark a puppy as a gift to keep.\n\nDuring the internationally televised interview with Kim, Skylark addresses increasingly sensitive topics (including the country's [[North Korean famine|food shortage]] issues and [[Sanctions against North Korea|economic sanctions]] imposed by the US) and challenges Kim's need for [[Kim Jong-il|his father]]'s approval. Meanwhile, Sook-yin and Rapaport seize control of the broadcasting center and attack guards trying to cut off the broadcast. Despite his initial resistance, Kim eventually cries uncontrollably and soils himself after Skylark sings [[Firework (song)|\"Firework\"]] by [[Katy Perry]] (having learned of Kim's fondness of Perry earlier), ruining his reputation. Betrayed and humiliated, Kim shoots Skylark (who survives due to a bulletproof vest) and goes into a violent rage, vowing to get his revenge. Skylark then regroups with Rapaport and Sook-yin to escape the presidential palace with the puppy in tow. After a security guard helps them escape, the trio hijack Kim's [[T-54/T-55|personal tank]] to get to their pickup point. Kim boards a helicopter and attacks the group alongside his army. He prepares a nuclear missile launch, but before he can issue the command to launch, Skylark shoots down Kim's helicopter, killing him. \n\nWith the immediate threat over, Sook guides Skylark and Rapaport to an escape route where they are rescued and loaded onto a rescue craft by [[SEAL Team Six]] members disguised as [[Korean People's Army]] troops, while Sook goes to [[Pyongyang]] to ensure political stability. Back in the United States, Skylark writes a book about his experience while North Korea become a [[denuclearization|denuclearized]] [[democracy]] with Sook-yin as an [[Transitional government|interim leader]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Franco]] as Dave Skylark\n* [[Seth Rogen]] as Aaron Rapaport\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as Agent Lacey\n* [[Randall Park]] as [[Kim Jong-un]]\n* [[Diana Bang]] as Sook-yin Park\n* [[Timothy Simons]] as Malcolm\n<!-- these are listed after the main six in the longer closing credits -->\n* Reese Alexander as Agent Botwin\n* [[Anders Holm]] as Jake\n* [[Charles Chun|Charles Rahi Chun]] as General Jong\n* [[Ben Schwartz]] as Daryl\n<!-- ones listed after here were minor characters such as Two-Fingered Man, Train Passengers, Korean Girl, Hot Korean Girls, Drone Pilot, etc. -->\n\nThe film also features [[cameo appearance]]s from [[Eminem]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Bill Maher]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Brian Williams]] and [[Scott Pelley]]. [[Iggy Azalea]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Zac Efron]] and [[Guy Fieri]] appear in the title graphic card for ''Skylark Tonight''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, joking about what would happen if a journalist was required to assassinate a world leader.<ref name=\"December2014RS\">{{cite journal| first =Josh| last =Eells| date =December 17, 2014| title =Seth Rogen at the Crossroads| journal =[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]| issue =1224/1225| pages =52\u201357; 86| location =[[New York City]]| issn =0035-791X| url =https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| accessdate =December 17, 2014| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141225013015/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| archivedate =December 25, 2014| df =mdy-all}}</ref>\nInitially, screenwriter [[Dan Sterling]] wrote his script involving a fictional dictator from a fictional country, but Rogen, Goldberg and Sony executives asked him to rewrite the script focusing on Kim.<ref name=\"Maroff\">{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|title=The Interview: an \"Act of War\"|last=Maroff|first=Melissa|date=December 18, 2014|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=July 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150721111520/http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|archivedate=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The screenplay was then titled ''Kill Kim Jong Un''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weinstein|first1=Shelli|title=Seth Rogen: Censoring North Korea in 'The Interview' 'Seemed Wrong'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|accessdate=February 6, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205115351/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|archivedate=February 5, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Previous iterations of the story revolved around [[Kim Jong-il]], but put the project on hold until Jong-il died and his son [[Kim Jong-un]] assumed power in 2011. Development resumed when Rogen and Goldberg realized that Jong-un is closer to their own age, which they felt would be more humorous. To write the story, co-written with ''[[Daily Show]]'' writer [[Dan Sterling]], they researched meticulously by reading non-fiction books and watching video footage about North Korea. The script was later reviewed by an employee in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref name=Jan2015NewYorker>{{cite news|last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|title=A North Korea Watcher Watches \"The Interview\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|accessdate=July 7, 2015|work=newyorker.com|date=January 2, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714153529/http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|archivedate=July 14, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg aimed to make the project more relevant and satirical than their previous films while retaining [[toilet humor]].<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> They were pleased when former [[NBA]] star [[Dennis Rodman]] visited North Korea, as it reinforced their belief that the premise of the film was realistic.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-production===\nIn March 2013, it was announced that Rogen and Goldberg would direct a comedy film for [[Columbia Pictures]] in which Rogen would star alongside [[James Franco]], with Franco playing a talk-show host and Rogen playing his producer.<ref name=March2013THR>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Seth Rogen to Direct, Star in 'The Interview' for Columbia Pictures (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=March 21, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613020954/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|archivedate=June 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg were on board to produce along with James Weaver through [[Point Grey Pictures]], while Columbia was said to finance the $30 million budgeted film.<ref name=\"March2013THR\" /> [[Lizzy Caplan]] joined the film's cast in October 2013. Caplan signed on to play Agent Lacey, a CIA agent who tries to get Franco's character to assassinate the Korean prime minister.<ref name=October2013THR>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Lizzy Caplan Joins Seth Rogen and James Franco in 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232251/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Randall Park]] and [[Timothy Simons]] signed on to co-star later that month. Park plays the North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-Un]] and Simons the director of the talk show.<ref name=October2013THR1>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Randall Park and 'Veep's' Timothy Simons to Co-Star in Seth Rogen's 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=October 8, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420010237/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|archivedate=April 20, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | title=North Korea Calls Seth Rogen-James Franco Film An 'Act Of War' | work=The Huffington Post | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | author=Mazza, Ed | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627132111/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | archivedate=June 27, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Park was the first to audition for the role of Kim and got the part immediately.  Before filming began, Park gained 15 pounds and shaved his head to resemble Jong-un's [[crew cut]].  His role was praised by critics.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /><ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /> Although Rogen and Goldberg wrote the character of Kim as \"robotic and strict\", Park instead played it \"sheepish and shy\", which they found more humorous.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> [[Diana Bang]] was cast as Sook-yin Park, for which she was well received by critics.<ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |title=''The Interview'' Actress Diana Bang Is Ready for Anything |author=Smith, Krista |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217174628/http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |archivedate=December 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Glen|title=Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg come home to shoot B.C. for Korea in The Interview|url=http://blogs.theprovince.com/2013/10/12/seth-rogen-and-evan-goldberg-come-home-to-shoot-b-c-for-korea-in-the-interview/|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Province|date=October 12, 2013}}</ref> and concluded on December 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg to Direct 'The Interview' in Vancouver|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232252/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There are hundreds of visual effects in the film;  a crowd scene at the Pyongyang airport, for example, was digitally manipulated with a shot from ''[[22 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-release reaction===\nIn June 2014, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the film had \"touched a nerve\" within the North Korean government, as they are \"notoriously paranoid about perceived threats to their safety.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=North Korea threatens 'merciless' response over Seth Rogen film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418173750/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|archivedate=April 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianBranigan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|title=Sony's cancellation of ''The Interview'' surprises North Korea-watchers|last=Branigan|first=Tanya|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220190356/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Korean Central News Agency]] (KCNA), the state news agency of North Korea, reported that their government  promised \"stern\" and \"merciless\" retaliation if the film was released. KCNA said that the release of a film portraying the assassination of the North Korean leader would not be allowed and it would be considered the \"most blatant act of terrorism and war.\"<ref name=\"North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war'\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | title=North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war' | publisher=CBC News | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626045743/http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | archivedate=June 26, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea threatens war on US over Kim Jong-un movie|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=BBC|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625140625/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|archivedate=June 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next month, North Korea's [[Permanent Representative to the United Nations|United Nations ambassador]] Ja Song-nam condemned the film, describing its production and distribution as \"an act of war\" and because of Kim's assassination in the film, \"the most undisguised sponsoring of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\">{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |title=North Korea complains to UN about Seth Rogen comedy The Interview |work=The Guardian |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730031714/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |archivedate=July 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''The Guardian''  described Song-nam's comments as \"perfect publicity for the movie.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\" /> Later in July, KCNA wrote to U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], asking to have the film pulled.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Julian|title=North Korea appeals to White House to halt release of US comedy film|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=July 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812122012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Shortly before the planned release of the film on December 25, 2014, screenwriter Dan Sterling told ''Creative Screenwriting:'' \"I couldn't believe that the most infamous man in the world knew about my script \u2013 but most importantly, I would never want something I wrote to lead to some kind of humanitarian disaster. I would be horrified if anyone got hurt over this.\"<ref name=\"Maroff\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Delay and changes===\nIn August 2014, Sony delayed the film's release from October 10 to December 25, 2014.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' with Seth Rogen, James Franco Pushed Back to Christmas|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|accessdate=August 7, 2014|work=Variety|date=August 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810035632/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|archivedate=August 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Sony made post-production alterations to the film to modify its portrayal of North Korea, including modifying the designs of buttons worn by characters, originally modeled after real North Korean military buttons praising the country's leaders, and cutting a portion of Kim Jong-un's death scene.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Sony Altering Kim Jong Un Assassination Film 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815064109/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|archivedate=August 15, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sony Pictures Entertainment hack and threats===\n{{main|Sony Pictures hack}}\n[[File:Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg|right|thumb|A hacker group compromised much of Sony Pictures Entertainment's computer system in late 2014 in retaliation for the film's content.]]\nOn November 24, 2014, an anonymous group identifying themselves as the \"Guardians of Peace\" hacked the computer networks of Columbia Pictures's parent company Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sanger|first1=David E.|last2=Perlroth|first2=Nicole|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|title=U.S. Said to Find North Korea Ordered Cyberattack on Sony|work=The New York Times|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218130909/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The hackers [[Internet leak|leaked]] internal emails, employee records and several recent and unreleased Sony Pictures films, including ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', ''[[Mr. Turner (film)|Mr. Turner]]'', ''[[Still Alice]]'', and ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]''. The North Korean government denied involvement in the hack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|title=North Korea denies hacking Sony Pictures|first=Justin|last=McCurry|work=The Guardian|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218083138/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\">{{cite news|title=Hackers who targeted Sony invoke 9/11 attacks in warning to moviegoers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|accessdate=December 17, 2014|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217042527/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sony's New Movies Leak Online Following Hack Attack|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|website=NBC News|accessdate=December 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202203232/http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|archivedate=December 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 8, the hackers leaked further materials, including a demand that Sony pull \"the movie of terrorism\", widely interpreted as referring to ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hackers told Sony to pull 'The Interview'|first=Elizabeth|last=Weise|work=USA Today|date=December 9, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130004703/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|archivedate=November 30, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korean Government Thought To Be Behind Sony Pictures Hack|date=December 1, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234518/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|archivedate=April 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Cyber Skills Get Attention Amid Sony Hacking Mystery|date=December 4, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407195600/http://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|archivedate=April 7, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2014, the hackers threatened to attack the [[New York City|New York]] premiere of ''The Interview'' and any cinema showing the film.<ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\" /> Two further messages were released on December 1; one, sent in a private message to Sony executives, said that the hackers would not release further information if Sony never released the film and removed it from the internet. The other, posted to [[Pastebin]], a web application used for text storage which the Guardians of Peace had used for previous messages, stated that Sony had \"suffered enough\" and could release ''The Interview'', but only if Kim Jong-un's death scene was not \"too happy\". The message also threatened that if Sony made another film antagonizing North Korea, the hackers \"will be here ready to fight\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weise |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Johnson |first2=Kevin |title=Obama: Sony \"did the wrong thing\" when it pulled movie |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219204906/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |archivedate=December 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Distribution===\n''The Interview'' was not released in Japan, as live-action comedy films do not often perform well in the market. In the Asia-Pacific region, it was released only in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|title='The Interview' to Have Only Limited Release in Asia|date=December 10, 2014|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Schilling|first1=Mark|accessdate=December 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213194607/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|archivedate=December 13, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRogen predicted that the film would make its way to North Korea, stating that \"we were told one of the reasons they're so against the movie is that they're afraid it'll actually get into North Korea. They do have [[Bootleg recording|bootlegs]] and stuff. Maybe the tapes will make their way to North Korea and cause a revolution.\"<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> ''[[Business Insider]]'' reported via [[Free North Korea Radio]] that there was high demand for bootleg copies of the film in North Korea.<ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Eugene|title=Demand For 'The Interview' Is Shooting Up In North Korea And Its Government Is Freaking Out|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|website=Business Insider|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229032411/http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The South Korean [[human rights organization]]s [[Fighters for a Free North Korea]] and [[Human Rights Foundation]], largely made up of North Korean defectors, planned to distribute DVD copies of ''The Interview'' [[Balloon campaigns in Korea|via balloon drops]].<ref name=\"hr20141216\">{{cite news|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|title=Sony Hack: Activists to Drop 'Interview' DVDs Over North Korea Via Balloon|first=Paul|last=Bond|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217073943/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|title=Launching Balloons into North Korea: Propaganda Over Pyongyang|date=18 March 2015|work=VICE news|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162347/https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The groups had previously air-dropped offline copies of the [[Korean Wikipedia]] into North Korea on a [[bootable USB]] memory device.<ref name=\"cnn20141218\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|title=Activists plan to drop 'Interview' DVDs in North Korea|last=Segall|first=Laurie|publisher=CNN|authorlink=Laurie Segall|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220202241/http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The balloon drop was scrapped after the North Korean government referred to the plan as a [[de facto]] \"declaration of war.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|title=South Korean activists postpone sending of copies of The Interview to North Korea by balloon|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323214646/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|archivedate=March 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|title=North Korea Calls Planned Balloon Drop of 'The Interview' DVDs a 'De Facto Declaration of War'|first=Gillian|last=Mohney|date=23 March 2015|work=VICE News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094846/https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of wide theatrical release===\nThe [[Film premiere|premiere]] was held in [[Los Angeles]] on December 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|title='The Interview' Premiere: Seth Rogen Thanks Amy Pascal \"For Having The Balls to Make This Movie\"|first=Tim|last=Appelo|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217202418/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film scheduled a [[wide release]] in the UK and Ireland on February 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | title = 'The Interview' To Get Wide Release In The UK | first = Ali | last = Jaafar | publisher = Deadline.com | date = January 7, 2015 | accessdate = January 12, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150110034332/http://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | archivedate = January 10, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Following the hackers' threats on December 16, Rogen and Franco canceled scheduled publicity appearances and Sony pulled all television advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|title=Seth Rogen and James Franco Cancel All Media Appearances for 'The Interview'|work=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216230918/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] said that they would not object to cinema owners delaying the film to ensure the safety of filmgoers. Shortly afterwards, the [[ArcLight Hollywood|ArcLight]] and [[Carmike Cinemas|Carmike]] cinema chains announced that they would not screen the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|title=First Theaters Cancel 'The Interview' After Hacker Threats|first1=Jen|last1=Yamato|first2=Dominic|last2=Patten|work=Deadline|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217055402/http://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, Sony canceled the New York City premiere. Later that day, other major theater chains including [[AMC Theatres|AMC]], [[Cinemark Theatres|Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment|Cineplex]], [[Regal Entertainment Group|Regal]] and [[Southern Theatres]] either delayed or canceled screenings of the film.<ref name=\"variety-interviewdropped\">{{cite web|title=Major U.S. Theaters Drop 'The Interview' After Sony Hacker Threats|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141217061335/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The chains reportedly came under pressure from [[shopping mall]]s where many theaters are located, which feared that the terror threat would ruin their holiday sales. They also feared expensive lawsuits in the event of an attack; Cinemark, for instance, contended that it could not have foreseen the [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting]], which took place at one of its multiplexes, a defense that would not hold in the event of an attack at a screening of ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|title=Sony Drops 'The Interview' Following Terrorist Threats|first1=Brooks|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael|last2=Cieply|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129055352/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|archivedate=January 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cancellation also affected other films in which each films' subject matter is North Korea. An [[Alamo Drafthouse Cinema]] location in [[Dallas]] planned to hold a free screening of ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', which satirizes Kim Jong-un's father [[Kim Jong-il]], in place of its previously scheduled screening of ''The Interview'';<ref name=\"thr-tawp\">{{cite web|title=Texas Theater to Show 'Team America' In Place of 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218054150/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"variety-tawpdallas\">{{cite web|title='Team America: World Police' Replaces 'The Interview' at Dallas Theater|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218051139/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] refused to permit the screening.<ref name=\"deadline-tawpcancelled\">{{cite web|title=Paramount Cancels 'Team America' Showings, Theaters Say|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218215711/https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[New Regency]] pulled out of a planned film adaptation of the graphic novel ''[[Pyongyang: A Journey in North Korea|Pyongyang]]'' starring [[Steve Carell]]; Carell declared it a \"sad day for creative expression\".<ref name=\"cbc-carellcancelled\">{{cite news|title=Steve Carell's North Korea movie from Guy Delisle novel scrapped after Sony hack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|website=CBC News|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219202505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|archivedate=December 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony received criticism for canceling the wide release.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=Sinha-Roy|first1=Piya|title=Hollywood slams Sony, movie theaters for canceling 'The Interview'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|agency=Reuters|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211630/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcus|first1=Stephanie|title=Celebrities React To Sony Canceling 'The Interview' Release|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111029/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|title=Hollywood Hits Twitter To Vent Anger About 'The Interview' Being Pulled|work=Deadline|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218045202/http://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Guardian'' film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] wrote that it was an \"unprecedented defeat on American turf\", but that \"North Korea will find that their bullying edict will haunt them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=The Interview: Sony's retreat signals an unprecedented defeat on American turf|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219171059/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''In the Capital'' and [[Gizmodo]] suggested the cancellation caused a [[Streisand effect]], whereby the attempt to remove or censor a work has the unintended consequence of publicizing it more widely.<ref name=\"itc20141215\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=Sony Pictures Is in for a Lesson on the Streisand Effect |url=http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |accessdate=December 20, 2014 |work=In The Capital |date=December 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218174836/http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |archivedate=December 18, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |title=The Streisand Effect and Why We All Now Want to See 'The Interview' |publisher=Gizmodo.co.uk |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227120034/http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |archivedate=December 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a press conference, U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] said that though he was sympathetic to Sony's need to protect employees, he thought Sony had \"made a mistake. We cannot have a society in which some dictator in some place can start imposing censorship in the United States. I wish they'd spoken to me first. I would have told them: do not get into the pattern in which you are intimidated.\"<ref name=\"obama\">{{cite news|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/obama-sony-made-mistake-canceling-film-release/story?id=27720800|title=Sony Hacking: President Obama Says Company Made 'Mistake' in Canceling 'The Interview'|first1=Devin|last1=Dwyer |first2=Mary|last2=Bruce|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO [[Michael Lynton]], the cancellation of the wide release was a response to the refusal of cinema chains to screen the film, not the hackers' threats, and that Sony would seek other ways to distribute the film. Sony released a statement saying that the company \"is and always has been strongly committed to the First Amendment ... Free expression should never be suppressed by threats and extortion.\"<ref name=\"hrdec19\" />\n\nThe movie was not released in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/327422-banned-movies-russia|title=Final cut: Movies that have been banned in Russia|last=Tokmasheva|first=Maria|date=2018-01-30|website=www.rbth.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n===Revised release===\nAfter the wide release cancellation, Sony considered other ways to release the film, citing pressure from the film industry, theater owners, and the White House.<ref name=\"hrdec19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|title=Sony Fires Back at Obama: \"We Had No Choice\" But to Cancel 'The Interview' Release|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Erik|last2=Hayden|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170752/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|archivedate=December 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"whitehouseofficialinterviewresponsenbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|title=Obama: Sony 'Made a Mistake' By Pulling 'The Interview' Movie|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403013318/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|archivedate=April 3, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DecPressure\">{{cite news|last1=Atkinson|first1=Claire|title=Sony faces pressure to release 'The Interview'|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=New York Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223122056/http://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[NBC News|NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on December 21, Sony's legal counsel [[David Boies]] noted that the company was still committed to releasing the film.<ref name=\"DecPressure\" /> Sony planned a  [[limited release]] for December 25, 2014, at more than three hundred American independent and [[arthouse cinema]]s.<ref>Shaw, Lucas (December 23, 2014). [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html \"Sony to Release ''The Interview'' in More Than 300 Theaters on Christmas Day\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225220539/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}. ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\" /><ref name=\"dp20141223\" /><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ 'Hobbit' rules box office, 'Interview' succeeds online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916012041/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ |date=September 16, 2017 }}. ''USA Today''. Retrieved December 29, 2014.</ref> Lynton stated that Sony was trying to show the film to the largest audience by securing as many theaters as they could.<ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\">{{cite web|title='The Interview' Release Back On For Christmas Day \u2013 Update|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223224802/https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"dp20141223\">{{cite web|last=Pankratz|first=Howard|title=Alamo Drafthouse in Littleton will screen 'The Interview' starting Christmas|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=The Denver Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223221307/http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony released ''The Interview'' for rental or purchase in the United States through the [[Streaming media|streaming]] services [[Google Play]], [[Xbox Video]], and [[YouTube]] on December 24, 2014. It was also available for a limited time on SeeTheInterview.com, a website operated by the [[stealth startup]] Kernel.com, which Sony previously worked with to market ''[[The Fifth Wave (film)|The Fifth Wave]]''.<ref name=\"variety-kernel\">{{cite web|title=What is Kernel? The Stealth Startup Sony Tapped to Stream 'The Interview' (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 30, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230054245/http://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|archivedate=December 30, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within hours, ''The Interview'' spread to [[file sharing]] websites after a security hole allowed people to download rather than stream the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|title=Oops: people are downloading and keeping Sony's rental for The Interview|work=The Verge|accessdate=December 26, 2014|date=December 24, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226080153/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|archivedate=December 26, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[TorrentFreak]] estimated that ''The Interview'' had been downloaded illegally via [[BitTorrent|torrents]] at least 1.5 million times in just two days.<ref name=\"tf-theinterview\">{{cite web|title=The Interview Is A Pirate Hit With 200k Downloads (Updated)|url=http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225|website=[[TorrentFreak]]|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228135544/http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225/|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 27, the North Korean [[National Defence Commission]] released a statement accusing President Obama of forcing Sony to distribute the film.<ref name=\"bbc27/12/2014\">{{cite web|title=North Korea berates Obama over The Interview release|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|publisher=BBC News|date=December 27, 2014|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228161521/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on [[iTunes]] on December 28.<ref name=\"verge-15mill\">{{cite web|title=The Interview makes over $15 million online, beating movie theaters|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|website=The Verge|accessdate=December 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229020127/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the first week of January 2015, Sony announced ''The Interview'' would receive a wide theatrical release in the United Kingdom and Ireland on February 6, but it would not be distributed digitally in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |title=The Interview to receive UK release, Sony confirms |publisher=BBC News |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110053317/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |archivedate=January 10, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film became available for [[Streaming media|streaming]] on [[Netflix]] on January 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|title='The Interview' is on Netflix streaming|website=engadget.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601025257/http://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nSony released the film on [[Blu-ray Disc]] and [[DVD]] on February 17, 2015. The home release was packaged as the \"Freedom Edition\", and included 90 minutes of [[deleted scene]]s, behind-the-scenes featurettes, a [[blooper]] reel, [[Audio commentary|feature commentary]] with directors Rogen and Goldberg, and a special episode of ''[[Naked and Afraid]]'' featuring Rogen and Franco.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Chris|title=The Interview is coming to Blu-ray and DVD on February 17th|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|accessdate=January 16, 2015|work=[[The Verge]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116121756/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> {{as of|df=US|2015|07|21|}}, the film had earned over $6.7 million in sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | title = The Interview (2014) | publisher = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = July 21, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703215408/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | archivedate = July 3, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office and online rentals===\n''The Interview'' opened to a limited release in the United States on December 25, 2014, across 331 theaters<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | title = 'The Interview' Release: 331 Theaters Aboard For Christmas Day | first1 = Lisa | last1 = de Moraes | first2 = Nellie | last2 = Andreeva | publisher = Deadline.com | date = December 24, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225615/http://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | archivedate = December 26, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and earned over $1 million on its opening day. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the opening gross \"an impressive launch for a title playing in only about 300 independent theaters in the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | title = Box Office: 'The Interview' Earns $1 Million on Christmas; 'Unbroken,' 'Into the Woods' Surging to $40M | first = Dave | last = McNarry | work = Variety | date = December 26, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141227125400/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | archivedate = December 27, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It went on to earn over $1.8 million in its opening weekend, and by the end of its run on January 25, 2015, had grossed $6.1 million at the box office.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report (cont.): Huge Limited Debuts for 'American Sniper,' 'Selma' | first = Ray | last = Subers | publisher = Box Office Mojo | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229090238/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWithin four days of its online release on December 24, 2014, ''The Interview'' earned over $15 million through online rentals and purchases. It became Sony Pictures' highest-grossing online release, outselling ''[[Arbitrage (film)|Arbitrage]]'' ($14 million), ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]'' ($8.2 million), and ''[[Snowpiercer]]'' ($7 million).<ref name=\"VOD\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | title = Sony: 'The Interview' Has Made Over $15 Million Online | first = Brent | last = Lang | work = Variety | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229012755/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It is the top-selling [[Google Play]] and [[YouTube]] film of 2014.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ The Year's top-selling movie on YouTube, Google Play] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231195212/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ |date=December 31, 2014 }}. ''Entertainment Weekly''. Retrieved December 31, 2014.</ref> By January 20, 2015, the film had earned more than $40 million from online sales and rentals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' Makes $40 Million Online and On-Demand|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20180116143833/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|archivedate=January 16, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony expected ''The Interview'' to break even through video-on-demand sales and saving millions of dollars on marketing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Faughdner|first1=Ryan|title=Sony's 'The Interview' to get 'freedom edition' home video release|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117094529/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|archivedate=January 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] contended that Sony would lose at least $30 million due to poor box office performance.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | title = 'The Interview' Lost Sony $30 Million, Says Theater Group | first = Pamela | last = McClintock | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date = January 16, 2015 | accessdate = January 17, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150120044501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | archivedate = January 20, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 51% approval rating, based on 141 reviews, with an average rating of 5.6/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Unfortunately overshadowed by controversy (and under-screened as a result), ''The Interview''{{'}}s screenplay offers middling laughs bolstered by its two likable leads.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|title=The Interview (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141222025822/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|archivedate=December 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 52 out of 100, based on 33 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|title=The Interview|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209073010/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|archivedate=February 9, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]]'s Roth Cornet wrote that \"though it's unlikely to stand out as one of the shrewdest political satires of its time, [it] is a clever, unrestrained and\u2014most importantly\u2014sidesplitting parody that pokes fun at both a vapid media and one of the world's most dangerous dictators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/12/the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=IGN.com}}</ref> Edward Douglas of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] said the film was \"hilarious, but it will probably get us nuked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=ComingSoon.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229175043/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jordan Hoffman of ''The Guardian'' gave the film three out of five stars and wrote that \"if this unessential but agreeable movie really triggered an international response, this is life reflecting art in a major way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|title = The Interview review: stoned, anally fixated \u2013 and funny|date = December 12, 2014|accessdate = December 28, 2014|work = The Guardian|last = Hoffman|first = Jordan|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226005452/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|archivedate = December 26, 2014|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' panned the film as \"cinematic [[waterboarding]]\" and \"about as funny as a communist food shortage, and just as protracted\", but praised the performances of Randall Park and Diana Bang.<ref name=ScottFoundasVariety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=Film Review: 'The Interview'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093148/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293/|archivedate=December 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' also praised Park and Bang, but wrote that \"after seeing ''The Interview'' and the ruckus its mere existence has caused, the only sensible reaction is amazement at the huge disconnect between the innocuousness of the film and the viciousness of the response.\"<ref name=\"hale\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|title=Memo to Kim Jong-un: Dying Is Easy, Comedy Is Hard|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220053144/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Political response===\nIn the wake of the Sony Pictures Entertainment hack, leaks revealed e-mails between Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO Michael Lynton and [[RAND Corporation]] defense analyst Bruce Bennett from June 2014. Bennett advised against toning down ''The Interview''{{-'}}s graphic Jong-un death scene, in the hope that it would \"start some real thinking in South Korea and, I believe, in the North once the DVD leaks into the North\". Bennett expressed his view that \"the only resolution I can see to the North Korean nuclear and other threats is for the North Korean government to eventually go away\", which he felt would be likeliest to occur following an assassination of Kim. Lynton replied that a senior figure in the [[United States Department of State]] agreed. Bennett responded that the office of [[Robert R. King]], U.S. Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, had determined that the North Korean statements had been \"typical North Korean bullying, likely without follow-up\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: Sony Emails Say State Department Blessed Kim Jong-Un Assassination in 'The Interview'|first=William|last=Boot|work=The Daily Beast|date=December 17, 2014|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217180144/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[CNN]], Bennett said Lynton sits on the board of trustees of the RAND Corporation, which had asked Bennett to talk to Lynton and give his opinion on the film.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |title=Expert on N. Korea on 'The Interview' |date=December 19, 2014 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223202708/http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |archivedate=December 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Bennett felt ''The Interview'' was \"coarse\" and \"over the top\", but that \"the depiction of Kim Jong-un was a picture that needed to get into North Korea. There are a lot of people in prison camps in North Korea who need to take advantage of a change of thinking in the north.\" Bennett felt that if the DVD were smuggled into the country it might have an effect \"over time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|title='The Interview' Release Would Have Damaged Kim Jong Un Internally, Says Rand Expert Who Saw Movie At Sony's Request|date=December 19, 2014|work=Yahoo Movies UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223211521/https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bennett contacted the Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, a personal friend of his, who \"took the standard government approach: we don't tell industry what to do\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\" /> [[Jen Psaki]], a spokesperson for the United States Department of State, confirmed that [[Daniel R. Russel]], the U.S. [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], had spoken to Sony executives; she reiterated that \"entertainers are free to make movies of their choosing, and we are not involved in that\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2014/12/235370.htm#DEPARTMENT|title=Daily Press Briefing - December 17, 2014|work=U.S. Department of State|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn [[Greece]], in April 2017, the film's opening scene, depicting a young girl reciting a poem with hate speech, was mistakenly broadcast in the news bulletin of [[Alpha TV]] and the [[news program]] ''Live News'' on [[Open TV|Epsilon TV]], as a real-life provocative event against the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressproject.gr/article/110363/O-Euaggelatos-parousiazei-skini-satirikis-tainias-gia-ti-BKorea-os-pragmatiki-video|title=\u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Alpha \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd\u03ae \u03ba\u03c9\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392.\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|trans-title=Evangelatos and Alpha present scene of a comedy film about North Korea as a real-life event|language=Greek|website=The Press Project|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref> In response to the backlash on various [[online newspaper]]s, Antonis Sroiter and Nikos Evangelatos, the hosts of the said programs, apologized in posts they made on their social accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topontiki.gr/article/217430/o-nikos-eyaggelatos-zita-syggnomi-gia-tin-gkafa-kaname-lathos|title=\u039f \u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03b3\u03bd\u03ce\u03bc\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b3\u03ba\u03ac\u03c6\u03b1: \u039a\u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5 \u03bb\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|trans-title=Nikos Evangelatos apologizes for the blunder: We made a mistake|language=Greek|website=[[To Pontiki]]|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eleftherostypos.gr/perierga/94235-i-apologia-sroiter-gia-to-reportaz-me-to-koritsaki-apo-ti-boreia-korea/|title=\u0397\u2026 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 \u03a3\u03c1\u03cc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b6 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1|trans-title=Sroiter's... apology for the reportage with the girl from North Korea|language=Greek|website=[[Eleftheros Typos]]|date=2017-04-22|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Freedom of speech|North Korea}}\n* [[Assassinations in fiction]]\n* [[List of films set in or about North Korea]]\n* ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', another comedy film satirizing North Korea\n* ''[[The Dictator (2012 film)|The Dictator]]'', a comedy film satirizing [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] dictators\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seetheinterview.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2788710|The Interview}}\n* {{mojo title|interview2014|The Interview}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_interview_2014|The Interview}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-interview|The Interview}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interview, The (2014 film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 controversies]]\n[[Category:2010s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]] \n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s satirical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]] \n[[Category:American political comedy films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:Fiction about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Point Grey Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Kim Jong-un]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Events relating to freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Henry Jackman]]\n[[Category:Films about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Films about the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Evan Goldberg]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pyongyang]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:North Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Self-censorship]]\n[[Category:Works banned in Russia]]\n[[Category:Films about journalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film directed by Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg}}\n{{about|the 2014 film||Interview (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Interview\n| image          = The Interview 2014 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster{{efn|The [[Korean language|Korean]] text translates as: \"The war will begin\" (on the missiles and tanks). The Korean text line right beneath the stars' names above the movie title translates to: \"Please do not believe these ignorant dishonorable Americans!\" while the small text to the left and right of the title, meanwhile, translates to the film's title. The fine print at the bottom of the poster reiterates the opening tagline from the top of the poster, translating to: \"Awful work by the 'pigs' that created ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' and ''[[This Is the End]]''{{-\"}}.<ref>Vary, Adam B. (June 11, 2014). [https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill#.nq6r90dzZ3 \"The Poster For Seth Rogen and James Franco's New Comedy Is Filled with Anti-American Propaganda\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328132022/http://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill |date=March 28, 2016 }}. [[BuzzFeed]]. Retrieved December 21, 2014.</ref>}}\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Evan Goldberg]]\n}}\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* James Weaver\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Dan Sterling]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* Dan Sterling\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Franco]]\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Randall Park]]\n<!--per billing block-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Henry Jackman]]\n| cinematography = [[Brandon Trost]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Zene Baker]]\n* Evan Henke\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Point Grey Pictures]]\n* [[LStar Capital]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]{{efn|All references to [[Sony Pictures]] were removed from the final film and marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |title=Hack Attack: Sony Orders Its Name Removed from \u2018Interview\u2019 Marketing Materials |url=https://www.thewrap.com/hack-attack-sony-orders-its-name-removed-from-interview-marketing-materials/ |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|12|11|Los Angeles|2014|12|24|United States<!--- This is for the on demand date, and the film was only released on December 24. Please go to the talk page before changing this --->}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 111:49 --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | title=''The Interview'' (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129045957/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | archivedate=November 29, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Korean\n}}\n| budget         = $44 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|title=Sony Weighing Premium VOD Release for 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 17, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=January 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116144807/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|title=Sony Could Lose $75 Million on 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 18, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220194759/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = $12.3 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | title = The Interview (2014) \u2013 Financial Information | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = May 1, 2019  | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180422062312/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | archivedate = April 22, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Interview''''' is a 2014 American [[action comedy film]] co-produced and directed by [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] in their second directorial work, following ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013). The screenplay was written by [[Dan Sterling]], based on a story he co-wrote with Rogen and Goldberg. The film stars Rogen and [[James Franco]] as journalists who set up an interview with [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ([[Randall Park]]), and are then recruited by the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] to assassinate him. The film is heavily inspired by a 2012 ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' documentary.\n\nRogen and Goldberg developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, with [[Kim Jong-il]] as the original assassination target. In 2011, after [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Jong-il's death]] and Jong-un's succession as the [[List of heads of state of North Korea|North Korean leader]], Rogen and Goldberg redeveloped the script with the focus on Jong-un's character. ''The Interview'' was first announced in March 2013, at the beginning of pre-production. [[Principal photography]] was in [[Vancouver]] from October to December 2013. The film was produced by [[Columbia Pictures]], [[LStar Capital]] and Rogen and Goldberg's [[Point Grey Pictures]], and distributed by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]].\n\nIn June 2014, the North Korean government threatened action against the United States if Sony released the film. As a result, Sony delayed the release from October to December and reportedly re-edited the film to make it more acceptable to North Korea. In November, the computer systems of Sony were [[Sony Pictures hack|hacked]] by the \"Guardians of Peace\", a group the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] claimed has ties to North Korea.<ref>[[Gabi Siboni]] and David Siman-Tov, [http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf Cyberspace Extortion: North Korea versus the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820031432/http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf |date=August 20, 2016 }}, [[Institute for National Security Studies (Israel)|INSS]] Insight No. 646, December 23, 2014.</ref> The group also threatened terrorist attacks against theaters showing the film. As a result, major theater chains opted not to release the film, and Sony instead released it for online digital rental and purchase on December 24, 2014, followed by a [[limited release]] at selected theaters the next day.\n\nIn December 2014, [[South Korea|South Korean]] singer [[Yoon Mi-rae]] revealed that the film used her song \"Pay Day\" without permission, and that she was taking legal action.<ref name=\"newsmp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.soompi.com/2014/12/26/yoon-mi-rae-to-take-legal-action-against-sony-pictures-for-using-her-song-in-the-interview-without-permission/|title=Yoon Mi Rae to Take Legal Action against Sony Pictures for Using Her Song in \"The Interview\" without Permission|date=27 December 2014|work=Soompi|author=|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> Yoon Mi-rae and her label [[Feel Ghood Music]] reached a settlement with Sony Pictures Entertainment on the 13th of May 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/201343/20150517/sony-the-interview-yoon-mi-rae-payday.htm|title=Sony And Yoon Mi Rae Reach Settlement Over Unlicensed Song Usage In 'The Interview'|website=KpopStarz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> \n\n''The Interview'' grossed $40 million in digital rentals, making it Sony's most successful digital release and earned an additional $12.3 million worldwide in box office ticket sales on a $44 million budget. It received mixed reviews for its humor and subject matter, although a few critics praised the performances of Rogen, Franco, Park and [[Diana Bang]].\n\n==Plot==\nDave Skylark is the host of the [[talk show]] ''Skylark Tonight'', where he interviews various celebrities about personal topics and gossip. After Skylark and his crew celebrate their producer Aaron Rapaport's 1,000th episode, Rapaport is upset by a producer peer who criticized the show as not being a real news program. Rapaport reveals his concern and urge for change, to which Skylark agrees. Later, Skylark discovers that [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] is a fan of ''Skylark Tonight'', prompting Rapaport to arrange an interview for him. Rapaport travels to a place outside [[Dandong]], [[China]] to receive instructions from Sook-yin Park, a [[Propaganda in North Korea|propaganda minister]], and Rapaport accepts the task of interviewing Kim on behalf of Skylark.\n\nThe next day, [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent Lacey shows up at Skylark and Rapaport's place, proposing that the duo assassinate Kim using a [[transdermal patch|transdermal strip]] that will poison Kim with [[ricin]] via handshake; they reluctantly agree. Skylark carries the ricin strip hidden inside a pack of gum. Upon their arrival in the [[Residences of North Korean leaders|presidential palace]] in [[Pyongyang]], they are introduced to security officers Koh and Yu; Koh discovers the strip and chews it, believing it to be gum. That night, Lacey airdrops them two more patches from a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]], but in order to smuggle it back to their room, Rapaport has to evade a [[Siberian tiger]] and then hide the container in his rectum. Later, Kim shows up and introduces himself to Skylark.\n\nSkylark spends the day with Kim by playing [[basketball]], hanging out and partying together. Kim persuades Skylark that he is misunderstood as both a cruel dictator and a failed administrator, and they become friends. At dinner, Koh has a [[Epileptic seizure|seizure]] due to the ricin poisoning and accidentally shoots Yu before dying. The next morning, Skylark feels guilty and discards one of the ricin strip, then thwarts Rapaport's attempt to poison Kim with the second strip. After another dinner mourning the death of Kim's bodyguards, Skylark witnesses Kim's malicious side as he [[Korean conflict|threatens war]] against [[South Korea]] and everyone who try to undermine his leadership. Skylark leaves and after taking a walk, he discovers that a nearby grocery store is merely [[Potemkin village|fake]] and realizes that Kim has been lying to him. At the same time, during an attempted sex with Rapaport (who still has the ricin strip in his hand), Sook-yin reveals that she despises Kim and apologizes for defending the regime. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin plan to break [[North Korean cult of personality|Kim's cult of personality]] by causing him to cry on air. Before the broadcast starts, Kim gives Skylark a puppy as a gift to keep.\n\nDuring the internationally televised interview with Kim, Skylark addresses increasingly sensitive topics (including the country's [[North Korean famine|food shortage]] issues and [[Sanctions against North Korea|economic sanctions]] imposed by the US) and challenges Kim's need for [[Kim Jong-il|his father]]'s approval. Meanwhile, Sook-yin and Rapaport seize control of the broadcasting center and attack guards trying to cut off the broadcast. Despite his initial resistance, Kim eventually cries uncontrollably and soils himself after Skylark sings [[Firework (song)|\"Firework\"]] by [[Katy Perry]] (having learned of Kim's fondness of Perry earlier), ruining his reputation. Betrayed and humiliated, Kim shoots Skylark (who survives due to a bulletproof vest) and goes into a violent rage, vowing to get his revenge. Skylark then regroups with Rapaport and Sook-yin to escape the presidential palace with the puppy in tow. After a security guard help them escape, the trio hijack Kim's [[T-54/T-55|personal tank]] to get to their pickup point. Kim boards a helicopter and attacks the group alongside his army. He prepares a nuclear missile launch, but before he can issue the command to launch, Skylark shoots down Kim's helicopter, killing him. \n\nWith the immediate threat over, Sook guides Skylark and Rapaport to an escape route where they are rescued and loaded onto a rescue craft by [[SEAL Team Six]] members disguised as [[Korean People's Army]] troops, while Sook goes to [[Pyongyang]] to ensure political stability. Back in the United States, Skylark writes a book about his experience while North Korea become a [[denuclearization|denuclearized]] [[democracy]] with Sook-yin as an [[Transitional government|interim leader]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Franco]] as Dave Skylark\n* [[Seth Rogen]] as Aaron Rapaport\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as Agent Lacey\n* [[Randall Park]] as [[Kim Jong-un]]\n* [[Diana Bang]] as Sook-yin Park\n* [[Timothy Simons]] as Malcolm\n<!-- these are listed after the main six in the longer closing credits -->\n* Reese Alexander as Agent Botwin\n* [[Anders Holm]] as Jake\n* [[Charles Chun|Charles Rahi Chun]] as General Jong\n* [[Ben Schwartz]] as Daryl\n<!-- ones listed after here were minor characters such as Two-Fingered Man, Train Passengers, Korean Girl, Hot Korean Girls, Drone Pilot, etc. -->\n\nThe film also features [[cameo appearance]]s from [[Eminem]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Bill Maher]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Brian Williams]] and [[Scott Pelley]]. [[Iggy Azalea]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Zac Efron]] and [[Guy Fieri]] appear in the title graphic card for ''Skylark Tonight''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, joking about what would happen if a journalist was required to assassinate a world leader.<ref name=\"December2014RS\">{{cite journal| first =Josh| last =Eells| date =December 17, 2014| title =Seth Rogen at the Crossroads| journal =[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]| issue =1224/1225| pages =52\u201357; 86| location =[[New York City]]| issn =0035-791X| url =https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| accessdate =December 17, 2014| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141225013015/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| archivedate =December 25, 2014| df =mdy-all}}</ref>\nInitially, screenwriter [[Dan Sterling]] wrote his script involving a fictional dictator from a fictional country, but Rogen, Goldberg and Sony executives asked him to rewrite the script focusing on Kim.<ref name=\"Maroff\">{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|title=The Interview: an \"Act of War\"|last=Maroff|first=Melissa|date=December 18, 2014|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=July 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150721111520/http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|archivedate=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The screenplay was then titled ''Kill Kim Jong Un''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weinstein|first1=Shelli|title=Seth Rogen: Censoring North Korea in 'The Interview' 'Seemed Wrong'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|accessdate=February 6, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205115351/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|archivedate=February 5, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Previous iterations of the story revolved around [[Kim Jong-il]], but put the project on hold until Jong-il died and his son [[Kim Jong-un]] assumed power in 2011. Development resumed when Rogen and Goldberg realized that Jong-un is closer to their own age, which they felt would be more humorous. To write the story, co-written with ''[[Daily Show]]'' writer [[Dan Sterling]], they researched meticulously by reading non-fiction books and watching video footage about North Korea. The script was later reviewed by an employee in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref name=Jan2015NewYorker>{{cite news|last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|title=A North Korea Watcher Watches \"The Interview\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|accessdate=July 7, 2015|work=newyorker.com|date=January 2, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714153529/http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|archivedate=July 14, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg aimed to make the project more relevant and satirical than their previous films while retaining [[toilet humor]].<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> They were pleased when former [[NBA]] star [[Dennis Rodman]] visited North Korea, as it reinforced their belief that the premise of the film was realistic.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-production===\nIn March 2013, it was announced that Rogen and Goldberg would direct a comedy film for [[Columbia Pictures]] in which Rogen would star alongside [[James Franco]], with Franco playing a talk-show host and Rogen playing his producer.<ref name=March2013THR>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Seth Rogen to Direct, Star in 'The Interview' for Columbia Pictures (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=March 21, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613020954/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|archivedate=June 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg were on board to produce along with James Weaver through [[Point Grey Pictures]], while Columbia was said to finance the $30 million budgeted film.<ref name=\"March2013THR\" /> [[Lizzy Caplan]] joined the film's cast in October 2013. Caplan signed on to play Agent Lacey, a CIA agent who tries to get Franco's character to assassinate the Korean prime minister.<ref name=October2013THR>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Lizzy Caplan Joins Seth Rogen and James Franco in 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232251/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Randall Park]] and [[Timothy Simons]] signed on to co-star later that month. Park plays the North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-Un]] and Simons the director of the talk show.<ref name=October2013THR1>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Randall Park and 'Veep's' Timothy Simons to Co-Star in Seth Rogen's 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=October 8, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420010237/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|archivedate=April 20, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | title=North Korea Calls Seth Rogen-James Franco Film An 'Act Of War' | work=The Huffington Post | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | author=Mazza, Ed | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627132111/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | archivedate=June 27, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Park was the first to audition for the role of Kim and got the part immediately.  Before filming began, Park gained 15 pounds and shaved his head to resemble Jong-un's [[crew cut]].  His role was praised by critics.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /><ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /> Although Rogen and Goldberg wrote the character of Kim as \"robotic and strict\", Park instead played it \"sheepish and shy\", which they found more humorous.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> [[Diana Bang]] was cast as Sook-yin Park, for which she was well received by critics.<ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |title=''The Interview'' Actress Diana Bang Is Ready for Anything |author=Smith, Krista |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217174628/http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |archivedate=December 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Glen|title=Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg come home to shoot B.C. for Korea in The Interview|url=http://blogs.theprovince.com/2013/10/12/seth-rogen-and-evan-goldberg-come-home-to-shoot-b-c-for-korea-in-the-interview/|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Province|date=October 12, 2013}}</ref> and concluded on December 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg to Direct 'The Interview' in Vancouver|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232252/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There are hundreds of visual effects in the film;  a crowd scene at the Pyongyang airport, for example, was digitally manipulated with a shot from ''[[22 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-release reaction===\nIn June 2014, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the film had \"touched a nerve\" within the North Korean government, as they are \"notoriously paranoid about perceived threats to their safety.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=North Korea threatens 'merciless' response over Seth Rogen film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418173750/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|archivedate=April 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianBranigan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|title=Sony's cancellation of ''The Interview'' surprises North Korea-watchers|last=Branigan|first=Tanya|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220190356/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Korean Central News Agency]] (KCNA), the state news agency of North Korea, reported that their government  promised \"stern\" and \"merciless\" retaliation if the film was released. KCNA said that the release of a film portraying the assassination of the North Korean leader would not be allowed and it would be considered the \"most blatant act of terrorism and war.\"<ref name=\"North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war'\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | title=North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war' | publisher=CBC News | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626045743/http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | archivedate=June 26, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea threatens war on US over Kim Jong-un movie|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=BBC|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625140625/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|archivedate=June 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next month, North Korea's [[Permanent Representative to the United Nations|United Nations ambassador]] Ja Song-nam condemned the film, describing its production and distribution as \"an act of war\" and because of Kim's assassination in the film, \"the most undisguised sponsoring of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\">{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |title=North Korea complains to UN about Seth Rogen comedy The Interview |work=The Guardian |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730031714/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |archivedate=July 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''The Guardian''  described Song-nam's comments as \"perfect publicity for the movie.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\" /> Later in July, KCNA wrote to U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], asking to have the film pulled.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Julian|title=North Korea appeals to White House to halt release of US comedy film|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=July 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812122012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Shortly before the planned release of the film on December 25, 2014, screenwriter Dan Sterling told ''Creative Screenwriting:'' \"I couldn't believe that the most infamous man in the world knew about my script \u2013 but most importantly, I would never want something I wrote to lead to some kind of humanitarian disaster. I would be horrified if anyone got hurt over this.\"<ref name=\"Maroff\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Delay and changes===\nIn August 2014, Sony delayed the film's release from October 10 to December 25, 2014.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' with Seth Rogen, James Franco Pushed Back to Christmas|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|accessdate=August 7, 2014|work=Variety|date=August 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810035632/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|archivedate=August 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Sony made post-production alterations to the film to modify its portrayal of North Korea, including modifying the designs of buttons worn by characters, originally modeled after real North Korean military buttons praising the country's leaders, and cutting a portion of Kim Jong-un's death scene.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Sony Altering Kim Jong Un Assassination Film 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815064109/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|archivedate=August 15, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sony Pictures Entertainment hack and threats===\n{{main|Sony Pictures hack}}\n[[File:Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg|right|thumb|A hacker group compromised much of Sony Pictures Entertainment's computer system in late 2014 in retaliation for the film's content.]]\nOn November 24, 2014, an anonymous group identifying themselves as the \"Guardians of Peace\" hacked the computer networks of Columbia Pictures's parent company Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sanger|first1=David E.|last2=Perlroth|first2=Nicole|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|title=U.S. Said to Find North Korea Ordered Cyberattack on Sony|work=The New York Times|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218130909/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The hackers [[Internet leak|leaked]] internal emails, employee records and several recent and unreleased Sony Pictures films, including ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', ''[[Mr. Turner (film)|Mr. Turner]]'', ''[[Still Alice]]'', and ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]''. The North Korean government denied involvement in the hack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|title=North Korea denies hacking Sony Pictures|first=Justin|last=McCurry|work=The Guardian|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218083138/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\">{{cite news|title=Hackers who targeted Sony invoke 9/11 attacks in warning to moviegoers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|accessdate=December 17, 2014|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217042527/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sony's New Movies Leak Online Following Hack Attack|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|website=NBC News|accessdate=December 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202203232/http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|archivedate=December 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 8, the hackers leaked further materials, including a demand that Sony pull \"the movie of terrorism\", widely interpreted as referring to ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hackers told Sony to pull 'The Interview'|first=Elizabeth|last=Weise|work=USA Today|date=December 9, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130004703/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|archivedate=November 30, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korean Government Thought To Be Behind Sony Pictures Hack|date=December 1, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234518/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|archivedate=April 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Cyber Skills Get Attention Amid Sony Hacking Mystery|date=December 4, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407195600/http://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|archivedate=April 7, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2014, the hackers threatened to attack the [[New York City|New York]] premiere of ''The Interview'' and any cinema showing the film.<ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\" /> Two further messages were released on December 1; one, sent in a private message to Sony executives, said that the hackers would not release further information if Sony never released the film and removed it from the internet. The other, posted to [[Pastebin]], a web application used for text storage which the Guardians of Peace had used for previous messages, stated that Sony had \"suffered enough\" and could release ''The Interview'', but only if Kim Jong-un's death scene was not \"too happy\". The message also threatened that if Sony made another film antagonizing North Korea, the hackers \"will be here ready to fight\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weise |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Johnson |first2=Kevin |title=Obama: Sony \"did the wrong thing\" when it pulled movie |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219204906/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |archivedate=December 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Distribution===\n''The Interview'' was not released in Japan, as live-action comedy films do not often perform well in the market. In the Asia-Pacific region, it was released only in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|title='The Interview' to Have Only Limited Release in Asia|date=December 10, 2014|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Schilling|first1=Mark|accessdate=December 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213194607/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|archivedate=December 13, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRogen predicted that the film would make its way to North Korea, stating that \"we were told one of the reasons they're so against the movie is that they're afraid it'll actually get into North Korea. They do have [[Bootleg recording|bootlegs]] and stuff. Maybe the tapes will make their way to North Korea and cause a revolution.\"<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> ''[[Business Insider]]'' reported via [[Free North Korea Radio]] that there was high demand for bootleg copies of the film in North Korea.<ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Eugene|title=Demand For 'The Interview' Is Shooting Up In North Korea And Its Government Is Freaking Out|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|website=Business Insider|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229032411/http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The South Korean [[human rights organization]]s [[Fighters for a Free North Korea]] and [[Human Rights Foundation]], largely made up of North Korean defectors, planned to distribute DVD copies of ''The Interview'' [[Balloon campaigns in Korea|via balloon drops]].<ref name=\"hr20141216\">{{cite news|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|title=Sony Hack: Activists to Drop 'Interview' DVDs Over North Korea Via Balloon|first=Paul|last=Bond|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217073943/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|title=Launching Balloons into North Korea: Propaganda Over Pyongyang|date=18 March 2015|work=VICE news|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162347/https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The groups had previously air-dropped offline copies of the [[Korean Wikipedia]] into North Korea on a [[bootable USB]] memory device.<ref name=\"cnn20141218\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|title=Activists plan to drop 'Interview' DVDs in North Korea|last=Segall|first=Laurie|publisher=CNN|authorlink=Laurie Segall|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220202241/http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The balloon drop was scrapped after the North Korean government referred to the plan as a [[de facto]] \"declaration of war.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|title=South Korean activists postpone sending of copies of The Interview to North Korea by balloon|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323214646/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|archivedate=March 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|title=North Korea Calls Planned Balloon Drop of 'The Interview' DVDs a 'De Facto Declaration of War'|first=Gillian|last=Mohney|date=23 March 2015|work=VICE News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094846/https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of wide theatrical release===\nThe [[Film premiere|premiere]] was held in [[Los Angeles]] on December 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|title='The Interview' Premiere: Seth Rogen Thanks Amy Pascal \"For Having The Balls to Make This Movie\"|first=Tim|last=Appelo|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217202418/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film scheduled a [[wide release]] in the UK and Ireland on February 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | title = 'The Interview' To Get Wide Release In The UK | first = Ali | last = Jaafar | publisher = Deadline.com | date = January 7, 2015 | accessdate = January 12, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150110034332/http://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | archivedate = January 10, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Following the hackers' threats on December 16, Rogen and Franco canceled scheduled publicity appearances and Sony pulled all television advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|title=Seth Rogen and James Franco Cancel All Media Appearances for 'The Interview'|work=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216230918/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] said that they would not object to cinema owners delaying the film to ensure the safety of filmgoers. Shortly afterwards, the [[ArcLight Hollywood|ArcLight]] and [[Carmike Cinemas|Carmike]] cinema chains announced that they would not screen the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|title=First Theaters Cancel 'The Interview' After Hacker Threats|first1=Jen|last1=Yamato|first2=Dominic|last2=Patten|work=Deadline|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217055402/http://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, Sony canceled the New York City premiere. Later that day, other major theater chains including [[AMC Theatres|AMC]], [[Cinemark Theatres|Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment|Cineplex]], [[Regal Entertainment Group|Regal]] and [[Southern Theatres]] either delayed or canceled screenings of the film.<ref name=\"variety-interviewdropped\">{{cite web|title=Major U.S. Theaters Drop 'The Interview' After Sony Hacker Threats|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141217061335/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The chains reportedly came under pressure from [[shopping mall]]s where many theaters are located, which feared that the terror threat would ruin their holiday sales. They also feared expensive lawsuits in the event of an attack; Cinemark, for instance, contended that it could not have foreseen the [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting]], which took place at one of its multiplexes, a defense that would not hold in the event of an attack at a screening of ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|title=Sony Drops 'The Interview' Following Terrorist Threats|first1=Brooks|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael|last2=Cieply|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129055352/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|archivedate=January 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cancellation also affected other films in which each films' subject matter is North Korea. An [[Alamo Drafthouse Cinema]] location in [[Dallas]] planned to hold a free screening of ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', which satirizes Kim Jong-un's father [[Kim Jong-il]], in place of its previously scheduled screening of ''The Interview'';<ref name=\"thr-tawp\">{{cite web|title=Texas Theater to Show 'Team America' In Place of 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218054150/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"variety-tawpdallas\">{{cite web|title='Team America: World Police' Replaces 'The Interview' at Dallas Theater|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218051139/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] refused to permit the screening.<ref name=\"deadline-tawpcancelled\">{{cite web|title=Paramount Cancels 'Team America' Showings, Theaters Say|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218215711/https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[New Regency]] pulled out of a planned film adaptation of the graphic novel ''[[Pyongyang: A Journey in North Korea|Pyongyang]]'' starring [[Steve Carell]]; Carell declared it a \"sad day for creative expression\".<ref name=\"cbc-carellcancelled\">{{cite news|title=Steve Carell's North Korea movie from Guy Delisle novel scrapped after Sony hack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|website=CBC News|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219202505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|archivedate=December 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony received criticism for canceling the wide release.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=Sinha-Roy|first1=Piya|title=Hollywood slams Sony, movie theaters for canceling 'The Interview'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|agency=Reuters|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211630/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcus|first1=Stephanie|title=Celebrities React To Sony Canceling 'The Interview' Release|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111029/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|title=Hollywood Hits Twitter To Vent Anger About 'The Interview' Being Pulled|work=Deadline|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218045202/http://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Guardian'' film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] wrote that it was an \"unprecedented defeat on American turf\", but that \"North Korea will find that their bullying edict will haunt them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=The Interview: Sony's retreat signals an unprecedented defeat on American turf|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219171059/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''In the Capital'' and [[Gizmodo]] suggested the cancellation caused a [[Streisand effect]], whereby the attempt to remove or censor a work has the unintended consequence of publicizing it more widely.<ref name=\"itc20141215\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=Sony Pictures Is in for a Lesson on the Streisand Effect |url=http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |accessdate=December 20, 2014 |work=In The Capital |date=December 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218174836/http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |archivedate=December 18, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |title=The Streisand Effect and Why We All Now Want to See 'The Interview' |publisher=Gizmodo.co.uk |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227120034/http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |archivedate=December 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a press conference, U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] said that though he was sympathetic to Sony's need to protect employees, he thought Sony had \"made a mistake. We cannot have a society in which some dictator in some place can start imposing censorship in the United States. I wish they'd spoken to me first. I would have told them: do not get into the pattern in which you are intimidated.\"<ref name=\"obama\">{{cite news|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/obama-sony-made-mistake-canceling-film-release/story?id=27720800|title=Sony Hacking: President Obama Says Company Made 'Mistake' in Canceling 'The Interview'|first1=Devin|last1=Dwyer |first2=Mary|last2=Bruce|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO [[Michael Lynton]], the cancellation of the wide release was a response to the refusal of cinema chains to screen the film, not the hackers' threats, and that Sony would seek other ways to distribute the film. Sony released a statement saying that the company \"is and always has been strongly committed to the First Amendment ... Free expression should never be suppressed by threats and extortion.\"<ref name=\"hrdec19\" />\n\nThe movie was not released in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/327422-banned-movies-russia|title=Final cut: Movies that have been banned in Russia|last=Tokmasheva|first=Maria|date=2018-01-30|website=www.rbth.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n===Revised release===\nAfter the wide release cancellation, Sony considered other ways to release the film, citing pressure from the film industry, theater owners, and the White House.<ref name=\"hrdec19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|title=Sony Fires Back at Obama: \"We Had No Choice\" But to Cancel 'The Interview' Release|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Erik|last2=Hayden|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170752/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|archivedate=December 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"whitehouseofficialinterviewresponsenbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|title=Obama: Sony 'Made a Mistake' By Pulling 'The Interview' Movie|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403013318/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|archivedate=April 3, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DecPressure\">{{cite news|last1=Atkinson|first1=Claire|title=Sony faces pressure to release 'The Interview'|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=New York Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223122056/http://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[NBC News|NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on December 21, Sony's legal counsel [[David Boies]] noted that the company was still committed to releasing the film.<ref name=\"DecPressure\" /> Sony planned a  [[limited release]] for December 25, 2014, at more than three hundred American independent and [[arthouse cinema]]s.<ref>Shaw, Lucas (December 23, 2014). [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html \"Sony to Release ''The Interview'' in More Than 300 Theaters on Christmas Day\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225220539/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}. ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\" /><ref name=\"dp20141223\" /><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ 'Hobbit' rules box office, 'Interview' succeeds online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916012041/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ |date=September 16, 2017 }}. ''USA Today''. Retrieved December 29, 2014.</ref> Lynton stated that Sony was trying to show the film to the largest audience by securing as many theaters as they could.<ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\">{{cite web|title='The Interview' Release Back On For Christmas Day \u2013 Update|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223224802/https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"dp20141223\">{{cite web|last=Pankratz|first=Howard|title=Alamo Drafthouse in Littleton will screen 'The Interview' starting Christmas|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=The Denver Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223221307/http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony released ''The Interview'' for rental or purchase in the United States through the [[Streaming media|streaming]] services [[Google Play]], [[Xbox Video]], and [[YouTube]] on December 24, 2014. It was also available for a limited time on SeeTheInterview.com, a website operated by the [[stealth startup]] Kernel.com, which Sony previously worked with to market ''[[The Fifth Wave (film)|The Fifth Wave]]''.<ref name=\"variety-kernel\">{{cite web|title=What is Kernel? The Stealth Startup Sony Tapped to Stream 'The Interview' (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 30, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230054245/http://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|archivedate=December 30, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within hours, ''The Interview'' spread to [[file sharing]] websites after a security hole allowed people to download rather than stream the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|title=Oops: people are downloading and keeping Sony's rental for The Interview|work=The Verge|accessdate=December 26, 2014|date=December 24, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226080153/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|archivedate=December 26, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[TorrentFreak]] estimated that ''The Interview'' had been downloaded illegally via [[BitTorrent|torrents]] at least 1.5 million times in just two days.<ref name=\"tf-theinterview\">{{cite web|title=The Interview Is A Pirate Hit With 200k Downloads (Updated)|url=http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225|website=[[TorrentFreak]]|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228135544/http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225/|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 27, the North Korean [[National Defence Commission]] released a statement accusing President Obama of forcing Sony to distribute the film.<ref name=\"bbc27/12/2014\">{{cite web|title=North Korea berates Obama over The Interview release|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|publisher=BBC News|date=December 27, 2014|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228161521/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on [[iTunes]] on December 28.<ref name=\"verge-15mill\">{{cite web|title=The Interview makes over $15 million online, beating movie theaters|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|website=The Verge|accessdate=December 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229020127/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the first week of January 2015, Sony announced ''The Interview'' would receive a wide theatrical release in the United Kingdom and Ireland on February 6, but it would not be distributed digitally in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |title=The Interview to receive UK release, Sony confirms |publisher=BBC News |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110053317/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |archivedate=January 10, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film became available for [[Streaming media|streaming]] on [[Netflix]] on January 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|title='The Interview' is on Netflix streaming|website=engadget.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601025257/http://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nSony released the film on [[Blu-ray Disc]] and [[DVD]] on February 17, 2015. The home release was packaged as the \"Freedom Edition\", and included 90 minutes of [[deleted scene]]s, behind-the-scenes featurettes, a [[blooper]] reel, [[Audio commentary|feature commentary]] with directors Rogen and Goldberg, and a special episode of ''[[Naked and Afraid]]'' featuring Rogen and Franco.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Chris|title=The Interview is coming to Blu-ray and DVD on February 17th|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|accessdate=January 16, 2015|work=[[The Verge]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116121756/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> {{as of|df=US|2015|07|21|}}, the film had earned over $6.7 million in sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | title = The Interview (2014) | publisher = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = July 21, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703215408/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | archivedate = July 3, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office and online rentals===\n''The Interview'' opened to a limited release in the United States on December 25, 2014, across 331 theaters<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | title = 'The Interview' Release: 331 Theaters Aboard For Christmas Day | first1 = Lisa | last1 = de Moraes | first2 = Nellie | last2 = Andreeva | publisher = Deadline.com | date = December 24, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225615/http://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | archivedate = December 26, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and earned over $1 million on its opening day. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the opening gross \"an impressive launch for a title playing in only about 300 independent theaters in the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | title = Box Office: 'The Interview' Earns $1 Million on Christmas; 'Unbroken,' 'Into the Woods' Surging to $40M | first = Dave | last = McNarry | work = Variety | date = December 26, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141227125400/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | archivedate = December 27, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It went on to earn over $1.8 million in its opening weekend, and by the end of its run on January 25, 2015, had grossed $6.1 million at the box office.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report (cont.): Huge Limited Debuts for 'American Sniper,' 'Selma' | first = Ray | last = Subers | publisher = Box Office Mojo | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229090238/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWithin four days of its online release on December 24, 2014, ''The Interview'' earned over $15 million through online rentals and purchases. It became Sony Pictures' highest-grossing online release, outselling ''[[Arbitrage (film)|Arbitrage]]'' ($14 million), ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]'' ($8.2 million), and ''[[Snowpiercer]]'' ($7 million).<ref name=\"VOD\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | title = Sony: 'The Interview' Has Made Over $15 Million Online | first = Brent | last = Lang | work = Variety | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229012755/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It is the top-selling [[Google Play]] and [[YouTube]] film of 2014.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ The Year's top-selling movie on YouTube, Google Play] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231195212/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ |date=December 31, 2014 }}. ''Entertainment Weekly''. Retrieved December 31, 2014.</ref> By January 20, 2015, the film had earned more than $40 million from online sales and rentals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' Makes $40 Million Online and On-Demand|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20180116143833/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|archivedate=January 16, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony expected ''The Interview'' to break even through video-on-demand sales and saving millions of dollars on marketing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Faughdner|first1=Ryan|title=Sony's 'The Interview' to get 'freedom edition' home video release|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117094529/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|archivedate=January 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] contended that Sony would lose at least $30 million due to poor box office performance.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | title = 'The Interview' Lost Sony $30 Million, Says Theater Group | first = Pamela | last = McClintock | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date = January 16, 2015 | accessdate = January 17, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150120044501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | archivedate = January 20, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 51% approval rating, based on 141 reviews, with an average rating of 5.6/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Unfortunately overshadowed by controversy (and under-screened as a result), ''The Interview''{{'}}s screenplay offers middling laughs bolstered by its two likable leads.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|title=The Interview (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141222025822/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|archivedate=December 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 52 out of 100, based on 33 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|title=The Interview|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209073010/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|archivedate=February 9, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]]'s Roth Cornet wrote that \"though it's unlikely to stand out as one of the shrewdest political satires of its time, [it] is a clever, unrestrained and\u2014most importantly\u2014sidesplitting parody that pokes fun at both a vapid media and one of the world's most dangerous dictators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/12/the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=IGN.com}}</ref> Edward Douglas of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] said the film was \"hilarious, but it will probably get us nuked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=ComingSoon.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229175043/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jordan Hoffman of ''The Guardian'' gave the film three out of five stars and wrote that \"if this unessential but agreeable movie really triggered an international response, this is life reflecting art in a major way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|title = The Interview review: stoned, anally fixated \u2013 and funny|date = December 12, 2014|accessdate = December 28, 2014|work = The Guardian|last = Hoffman|first = Jordan|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226005452/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|archivedate = December 26, 2014|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' panned the film as \"cinematic [[waterboarding]]\" and \"about as funny as a communist food shortage, and just as protracted\", but praised the performances of Randall Park and Diana Bang.<ref name=ScottFoundasVariety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=Film Review: 'The Interview'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093148/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293/|archivedate=December 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' also praised Park and Bang, but wrote that \"after seeing ''The Interview'' and the ruckus its mere existence has caused, the only sensible reaction is amazement at the huge disconnect between the innocuousness of the film and the viciousness of the response.\"<ref name=\"hale\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|title=Memo to Kim Jong-un: Dying Is Easy, Comedy Is Hard|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220053144/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Political response===\nIn the wake of the Sony Pictures Entertainment hack, leaks revealed e-mails between Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO Michael Lynton and [[RAND Corporation]] defense analyst Bruce Bennett from June 2014. Bennett advised against toning down ''The Interview''{{-'}}s graphic Jong-un death scene, in the hope that it would \"start some real thinking in South Korea and, I believe, in the North once the DVD leaks into the North\". Bennett expressed his view that \"the only resolution I can see to the North Korean nuclear and other threats is for the North Korean government to eventually go away\", which he felt would be likeliest to occur following an assassination of Kim. Lynton replied that a senior figure in the [[United States Department of State]] agreed. Bennett responded that the office of [[Robert R. King]], U.S. Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, had determined that the North Korean statements had been \"typical North Korean bullying, likely without follow-up\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: Sony Emails Say State Department Blessed Kim Jong-Un Assassination in 'The Interview'|first=William|last=Boot|work=The Daily Beast|date=December 17, 2014|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217180144/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[CNN]], Bennett said Lynton sits on the board of trustees of the RAND Corporation, which had asked Bennett to talk to Lynton and give his opinion on the film.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |title=Expert on N. Korea on 'The Interview' |date=December 19, 2014 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223202708/http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |archivedate=December 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Bennett felt ''The Interview'' was \"coarse\" and \"over the top\", but that \"the depiction of Kim Jong-un was a picture that needed to get into North Korea. There are a lot of people in prison camps in North Korea who need to take advantage of a change of thinking in the north.\" Bennett felt that if the DVD were smuggled into the country it might have an effect \"over time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|title='The Interview' Release Would Have Damaged Kim Jong Un Internally, Says Rand Expert Who Saw Movie At Sony's Request|date=December 19, 2014|work=Yahoo Movies UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223211521/https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bennett contacted the Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, a personal friend of his, who \"took the standard government approach: we don't tell industry what to do\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\" /> [[Jen Psaki]], a spokesperson for the United States Department of State, confirmed that [[Daniel R. Russel]], the U.S. [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], had spoken to Sony executives; she reiterated that \"entertainers are free to make movies of their choosing, and we are not involved in that\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2014/12/235370.htm#DEPARTMENT|title=Daily Press Briefing - December 17, 2014|work=U.S. Department of State|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn [[Greece]], in April 2017, the film's opening scene, depicting a young girl reciting a poem with hate speech, was mistakenly broadcast in the news bulletin of [[Alpha TV]] and the [[news program]] ''Live News'' on [[Open TV|Epsilon TV]], as a real-life provocative event against the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressproject.gr/article/110363/O-Euaggelatos-parousiazei-skini-satirikis-tainias-gia-ti-BKorea-os-pragmatiki-video|title=\u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Alpha \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd\u03ae \u03ba\u03c9\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392.\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|trans-title=Evangelatos and Alpha present scene of a comedy film about North Korea as a real-life event|language=Greek|website=The Press Project|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref> In response to the backlash on various [[online newspaper]]s, Antonis Sroiter and Nikos Evangelatos, the hosts of the said programs, apologized in posts they made on their social accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topontiki.gr/article/217430/o-nikos-eyaggelatos-zita-syggnomi-gia-tin-gkafa-kaname-lathos|title=\u039f \u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03b3\u03bd\u03ce\u03bc\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b3\u03ba\u03ac\u03c6\u03b1: \u039a\u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5 \u03bb\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|trans-title=Nikos Evangelatos apologizes for the blunder: We made a mistake|language=Greek|website=[[To Pontiki]]|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eleftherostypos.gr/perierga/94235-i-apologia-sroiter-gia-to-reportaz-me-to-koritsaki-apo-ti-boreia-korea/|title=\u0397\u2026 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 \u03a3\u03c1\u03cc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b6 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1|trans-title=Sroiter's... apology for the reportage with the girl from North Korea|language=Greek|website=[[Eleftheros Typos]]|date=2017-04-22|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Freedom of speech|North Korea}}\n* [[Assassinations in fiction]]\n* [[List of films set in or about North Korea]]\n* ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', another comedy film satirizing North Korea\n* ''[[The Dictator (2012 film)|The Dictator]]'', a comedy film satirizing [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] dictators\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seetheinterview.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2788710|The Interview}}\n* {{mojo title|interview2014|The Interview}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_interview_2014|The Interview}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-interview|The Interview}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interview, The (2014 film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 controversies]]\n[[Category:2010s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]] \n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s satirical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]] \n[[Category:American political comedy films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:Fiction about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Point Grey Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Kim Jong-un]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Events relating to freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[