p Final winners}}\n{{St. Helens RLFC - 1987 Challenge Cup Final runners-up}}\n{{Challenge Cup}}\n\n[[Category:Challenge Cup]]\n[[Category:1987 in English rugby league|Challenge Cup]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Rugby football league challenge cup\n|title               = 1987 Silk Cut Challenge Cup \n|league              = \n|logo                = \n|pixels              = \n|duration            = 6 Rounds\n|no_of_teams         = 38\n|highest_attendance  = \n|lowest_attendance   = \n|avg_attendance      = \n|TV                  = \n|biggest_home_win    = \n|biggest_away_win    = \n|season              = 1986\u201387\n|season_champs       = {{leagueicon|halifax|16px}} [[Halifax R.L.F.C.|Halifax]]\n|season_champ_name   = Winners\n|second_place        = {{leagueicon|st helens|16px}} [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]\n|MVP                 = {{leagueicon|halifax|16px}} [[Graham Eadie]]\n|MVP_link            = Lance Todd Trophy\n|top_scorer          =\n|prevseason_link     = 1986 Challenge Cup\n|prevseason_year     = 1986\n|nextseason_link     = 1988 Challenge Cup\n|nextseason_year     = 1988\n}}\nThe '''1987 Challenge Cup''' was the 86th staging of [[rugby league]]'s oldest knockout competition, the [[Challenge Cup]]. Known as the '''Silk Cut Challenge Cup''' for due to sponsorship froom [[Silk Cut]], the tournament featured clubs from the [[1986-87 Rugby Football League season]]. It culminated in the final contested by [[Halifax R.L.F.C.|Halifax]] and [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]. Halifax won the match 19\u201318.\n\n==First Round==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!width=150| Date\n!width=250| Team One\n!width=250| Team Two\n!width=100| Score\n|-\n|31 Jan ||Castleford\t||\tWidnes\t||16-24\n|-\n|01 Feb ||Fulham\t||\tHalifax\t||10-38\n|-\n|01 Feb ||Salford\t||\tLeeds\t||0-4\n|-\n|01 Feb ||Warrington\t||\tBradford Northern\t||17-21\n|-\n|03 Feb ||Barrow\t||\tBatley\t||54-2\n|-\n|04 Feb ||Hull Kingston Rovers\t||